00:31:42,109 --> 00:31:45,737
<i>The Canadians are reporting tremendous
circulation moving down from the Arctic.</i>

389
00:31:45,821 --> 00:31:49,074
In Siberia, there's a low pressure system
unlike anything we've seen...

390
00:31:49,157 --> 00:31:52,160
and Australia just saw
the strongest typhoon ever recorded.

391
00:31:52,244 --> 00:31:55,080
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> Hang on. Are you saying that
these things are interconnected?</i>

392
00:31:55,163 --> 00:31:57,082
<i><font color="#bce4f3">BOOKER:</font> We have to consider
the possibility.</i>

393
00:31:57,165 --> 00:32:00,043
The only force strong enough
to affect global weather is the sun.

394
00:32:00,127 --> 00:32:04,923
- What's NASA have to say?
- We've already checked. Solar output is normal.

395
00:32:05,006 --> 00:32:10,095
- What about the North Atlantic current?
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">VORSTEEN:</font> What about it?</i>

396
00:32:10,178 --> 00:32:13,974
I got a call last night from Professor Rapson
at the Hedland Center.

397
00:32:14,057 --> 00:32:15,976
He thinks the current
has changed.

398
00:32:16,059 --> 00:32:18,061
<font color="#6088d2">[MURMURING]</font>

399
00:32:18,145 --> 00:32:20,355
Come on, Jack.
How could that be?

400
00:32:20,439 --> 00:32:23,400
The current depends upon
a delicate balance of salt and fresh water.

401
00:32:23,483 --> 00:32:26,695
- We all know that.
- Yes.

402
00:32:26,778 --> 00:32:28,864
But no one has
taken into account...

403
00:32:28,947 --> 00:32:33,285
how much fresh water has been dumped
into the ocean because of melting polar ice.

404
00:32:33,368 --> 00:32:36,121
I think we've hit
a critical desalinization point.

405
00:32:36,204 --> 00:32:38,290
<i><font color="#6088d2">[MURMURING]</font></i>

406
00:32:40,041 --> 00:32:42,169
It would explain
what's driving this extreme weather.

407
00:32:42,252 --> 00:32:45,172
Hedland had some pretty
convincing data.

408
00:32:45,255 --> 00:32:49,217
They've asked me to feed it into my paleoclimate
model to track the next set of events.

409
00:32:49,301 --> 00:32:52,971
<i>Hold on, Jack. Are you suggesting these
weather anomalies are gonna continue?</i>

410
00:32:53,054 --> 00:32:56,057
Not just continue...
get worse.

411
00:33:00,187 --> 00:33:02,731
I think we're on the verge
of a major climate shift.

412
00:33:02,814 --> 00:33:05,317
<i><font color="#6088d2">[MURMURING]</font></i>

413
00:33:07,736 --> 00:33:10,864
<i>Tom! What are you gonna tell
the administration?</i>

414
00:33:10,947 --> 00:33:12,866
What do you expect me
to tell them?

415
00:33:12,949 --> 00:33:15,660
The government has to start making
long-term preparations now.

416
00:33:15,744 --> 00:33:18,705
- Jack, all you have is a theory.
- Then give me the mainframe
and let me prove it!

417
00:33:18,788 --> 00:33:21,917
No.

418
00:33:22,959 --> 00:33:24,878
You have 48 hours.

419
00:33:24,961 --> 00:33:26,880
- <font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>
<i>- Professor Hall.</i>

420
00:33:26,963 --> 00:33:29,382
- Yes?
- I think your theory may be correct.

421
00:33:29,466 --> 00:33:31,176
Walk with me.

422
00:33:31,259 --> 00:33:34,971
Just a few weeks ago, I monitored
the strongest hurricane on record.

423
00:33:35,055 --> 00:33:37,766
The hail, the tornadoes...
it all fits.

424
00:33:37,849 --> 00:33:40,352
Can the model you're working on
factor in storm scenarios?

425
00:33:40,435 --> 00:33:43,939
- Oh, we haven't had the time.
- Maybe I can help.

426
00:33:44,022 --> 00:33:45,982
- Welcome aboard.
- Thanks.

427
00:33:46,066 --> 00:33:48,568
- Hi, I'm Jason.
- Hi.

428
00:33:50,153 --> 00:33:51,613
Ow!

429
00:33:51,696 --> 00:33:54,366
<i>Do you have the results
of Peter's C. T. scan?</i>

430
00:33:54,449 --> 00:33:57,077
Yeah, the treatment
shrunk the tumor 20%.

431
00:33:57,160 --> 00:33:59,621
- Is his eyesight better today?
- No. No change.

432
00:34:10,131 --> 00:34:12,676
Hey, Peter.
How you doin' today?

433
00:34:12,759 --> 00:34:15,929
- A little better.
- Good.

434
00:34:16,012 --> 00:34:18,557
Let me listen here.

435
00:34:18,640 --> 00:34:20,934
Can you read that?

436
00:34:21,017 --> 00:34:25,772
No, but I remember
the story from the pictures.

437
00:34:25,855 --> 00:34:29,484
- You do?
- My mother used to read it to me.

438
00:34:29,568 --> 00:34:33,989
She must be very proud of you.
You've been such a brave, big boy.

439
00:34:34,072 --> 00:34:37,701
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

440
00:34:37,784 --> 00:34:41,246
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

441
00:34:45,750 --> 00:34:49,254
Jack, you've been working
for 24 hours straight...

442
00:34:49,337 --> 00:34:53,216
- the only one who hasn't taken a break.
- <font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>

443
00:34:53,300 --> 00:34:55,969
Maybe I'll try
to shut my eyes for a while.

444
00:34:56,052 --> 00:34:58,430
Call me when you
get the results.

445
00:35:02,559 --> 00:35:05,895
- Frank, is he always so obsessive?
- <font color="#bce4f3">TOGETHER:</font> Yes.

446
00:35:08,940 --> 00:35:11,776
- Does he ever lighten up?
- No.
- Not really.

447
00:35:15,530 --> 00:35:17,449
How long have you been
working together?

448
00:35:17,532 --> 00:35:22,120
Well, uh, Frank's been working with him
since the Stone Age.

449
00:35:22,203 --> 00:35:25,540
I've only had to endure
two years of servitude.

450
00:35:33,506 --> 00:35:36,885
Jack. Jack.
We got the results.

451
00:35:45,644 --> 00:35:47,896
Six to eight months.
That can't be.

452
00:35:47,979 --> 00:35:51,733
<i>That time scale isn't in months.
It's in weeks.</i>

453
00:35:55,570 --> 00:35:57,656
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> Widespread flooding
has slowed transportation...</i>

454
00:35:57,739 --> 00:36:01,159
<i>and caused numerous closures,
including the Lincoln and Holland Tunnels.</i>

455
00:36:01,242 --> 00:36:03,495
<i>The plumbing in the school
is really old.</i>

456
00:36:03,578 --> 00:36:05,830
With all this rain,
the sewage got stopped up.

457
00:36:05,914 --> 00:36:07,832
Where are you staying
tonight?

458
00:36:07,916 --> 00:36:10,502
They're finding us a place to stay with kids
here in New York City.

459
00:36:10,585 --> 00:36:13,129
Are you sure you can't get home
any sooner than tomorrow?

460
00:36:13,213 --> 00:36:15,382
Well, look, Dad,
I would if I could, you know.

461
00:36:15,465 --> 00:36:17,425
<i>It's just, uh...</i>

462
00:36:17,509 --> 00:36:21,346
Ugh! This smell
is unbearable, Dad.

463
00:36:21,429 --> 00:36:25,350
- Stop kidding around. I want you home.
- Dad, I'll be on the train.

464
00:36:25,433 --> 00:36:28,603
Do me a favor, okay?
Just don't worry about me. I'll figure it out.

465
00:36:28,687 --> 00:36:31,940
<font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>
All right, son. I'll see ya tomorrow.

466
00:36:35,610 --> 00:36:39,322
Hey, Sam. Guess what.
We got a place to stay.

467
00:36:40,740 --> 00:36:42,659
Great.

468
00:36:42,742 --> 00:36:45,286
<i>So far, the terrible weather
hasn't hit the D.C. area...</i>

469
00:36:45,370 --> 00:36:48,206
but local residents
aren't taking any chances...

470
00:36:48,289 --> 00:36:50,875
<i>as people stock up
for what is already being billed...</i>

471
00:36:50,959 --> 00:36:53,420
<i>as the worst storm season
on record.</i>

472
00:36:53,503 --> 00:36:56,089
You better be sure about this, Jack.
My ass is on the line.

473
00:36:56,172 --> 00:36:59,175
- You saw the model.
- And I hope to God it's wrong.

474
00:36:59,259 --> 00:37:01,636
- Oh. Mr. Vice President.
- Tom.

475
00:37:01,720 --> 00:37:04,472
- You know Professor Hall.
- Yes, we've met.

476
00:37:04,556 --> 00:37:08,059
Uh, Professor Hall has some new information
I think you should take a look at.

477
00:37:08,143 --> 00:37:10,895
We just got these results
from our simulation model.

478
00:37:10,979 --> 00:37:12,981
They explain what's causing
the severe weather.

479
00:37:13,064 --> 00:37:16,568
I'll look at this later. I have a meeting
with the director of FEMA now.

480
00:37:16,651 --> 00:37:19,446
This is very urgent, sir.
Our climate is changing violently.

481
00:37:19,529 --> 00:37:22,198
It's going to happen
over the next six to eight weeks.

482
00:37:22,282 --> 00:37:25,076
I thought you said this wouldn't happen
for another hundred years or so.

483
00:37:25,160 --> 00:37:27,704
- I was wrong.
- Well, suppose you're wrong this time.

484
00:37:27,787 --> 00:37:31,750
I wish that I were, but I'm sure that you're aware
of what's happening all around the world.

485
00:37:31,833 --> 00:37:35,253
We're making all the necessary preparations
for this storm. What more do you expect?

486
00:37:35,336 --> 00:37:39,174
You have to start thinking about large scale
evacuations right now...

487
00:37:39,257 --> 00:37:41,301
especially in
the northern states.

488
00:37:41,384 --> 00:37:43,344
- Evacuations?
- Yes.

489
00:37:43,428 --> 00:37:47,390
Have you lost your mind, Hall?
I have to go.

490
00:37:47,474 --> 00:37:52,270
Mr. Vice President, if we don't act now,
it's going to be too late.

491
00:37:56,274 --> 00:37:58,193
Come on, Jack.

492
00:37:58,276 --> 00:38:00,361
Hey, thanks for
bringing us here.

493
00:38:00,445 --> 00:38:04,282
I couldn't let you leave New York
without seeing the Natural History Museum.

494
00:38:04,365 --> 00:38:06,785
Of course not. It's the world's finest
collection of stuffed animals.

495
00:38:06,868 --> 00:38:08,787
Hey, guys.
Check this out.

496
00:38:08,870 --> 00:38:13,958
"The body of this mammoth was found
perfectly preserved in the Siberian tundra...

497
00:38:14,042 --> 00:38:18,588
"with food still
in its mouth and stomach...

498
00:38:18,671 --> 00:38:23,134
indicating that it froze
instantly while grazing."

499
00:38:29,015 --> 00:38:32,268
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> It's been 24 hours now since
the snow started falling...</i>

500
00:38:32,352 --> 00:38:34,270
across the British Isles
and over northern Europe...

501
00:38:34,354 --> 00:38:36,439
and it shows no signs
of letting up.

502
00:38:36,523 --> 00:38:39,234
<i>No. No, no, no.
You gotta stop worrying. No.</i>

503
00:38:39,317 --> 00:38:43,196
It's fine. We got plenty of supplies with us.
We're just snowed in.

504
00:38:43,279 --> 00:38:46,282
<i>Yeah. No, it's all right.
It's all right.</i>

505
00:38:46,366 --> 00:38:48,284
You stay where you are, okay?
I'll be fine.

506
00:38:48,368 --> 00:38:52,163
Yeah, I love you too. Okay. Bye.
<font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>

507
00:38:52,247 --> 00:38:56,793
- Hey. How's Jeanette?
- Oh, fine.

508
00:38:56,876 --> 00:39:01,881
- Ferry just landed.
<i>- Must be nice in Spain. I wish I was there.</i>

509
00:39:01,965 --> 00:39:04,634
<i><font color="#bce4f3">REPORTER:</font> <font color="#6088d2">[TV]</font> The search and rescue team
has been deployed by helicopter...</i>

510
00:39:04,717 --> 00:39:07,470
to airlift
the royal family to safety.

511
00:39:07,554 --> 00:39:09,639
You think they'll come get us,
since we got snowed in?

512
00:39:09,722 --> 00:39:12,141
Not likely.

513
00:39:12,225 --> 00:39:14,143
Luckily,
we got our own genny...

514
00:39:14,227 --> 00:39:16,688
enough tea and biscuits
to sink a ship.

515
00:39:16,771 --> 00:39:20,400
Oh, we'll be fine.
As long as the loo doesn't back up again.

516
00:39:20,483 --> 00:39:22,443
<font color="#6088d2">[ALL CHUCKLE]</font>

517
00:39:25,280 --> 00:39:29,617
<i>In Ireland, those remaining in Belfast
and Banbridge have been urged to evacuate...</i>

518
00:39:29,701 --> 00:39:32,787
<i>to Dublin as soon
as possible.</i>

519
00:39:32,871 --> 00:39:36,875
<i>The north continues
to receive the worst of the storm...</i>

520
00:39:36,958 --> 00:39:39,043
<i><font color="#6088d2">[HELICOPTER APPROACHING]</font></i>

521
00:39:41,713 --> 00:39:44,716
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> We've got zero visibility.
Maintain heading and speed.</i>

522
00:39:44,799 --> 00:39:47,302
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">MAN #2:</font> What's our heading?</i>
- Zero, three, five, sir.

523
00:39:47,385 --> 00:39:50,388
Approximately 40 kilometers
from Balmoral Castle.

524
00:39:50,471 --> 00:39:52,640
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font>
We've lost visual contact with you.</i>

525
00:40:16,748 --> 00:40:18,666
This gauge here
can't be right.

526
00:40:18,750 --> 00:40:20,668
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN #3:</font></i>
Wind speed has dropped to zero.

527
00:40:20,752 --> 00:40:23,171
<i>We have vertical walls
of cirrus cloud formations.</i>

528
00:40:23,254 --> 00:40:24,881
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font>
What the hell is going on?</i>

529
00:40:24,964 --> 00:40:26,883
Bloody fuel lines
are starting to freeze!

530
00:40:31,346 --> 00:40:33,890
<i><font color="#6088d2">[MEN SHOUTING]</font></i>

531
00:40:38,061 --> 00:40:42,065
<i>Port engine pressure's dropping!
The rotor R.P.M. is dropping!</i>

532
00:40:42,148 --> 00:40:44,192
<i>We've got a flame-out
on the starboard side as well!</i>

533
00:40:48,780 --> 00:40:50,907
Prepare
for crash landing!

534
00:40:52,408 --> 00:40:55,370
Select emergency fuel!

535
00:40:55,453 --> 00:40:58,081
Come on,
you bastard!

536
00:40:58,164 --> 00:41:00,416
Come on!

537
00:41:13,930 --> 00:41:16,349
<font color="#6088d2">[BREATHING HEAVILY]</font>

538
00:41:23,314 --> 00:41:26,192
<i><font color="#bce4f3">RAPSON:</font> What I'm about to tell you
is supposed to be confidential.</i>

539
00:41:26,275 --> 00:41:30,154
Several hours ago,
three helicopters went down over Scotland.

540
00:41:30,238 --> 00:41:33,700
They crashed because the fuel
in their lines froze.

541
00:41:33,783 --> 00:41:35,702
At what temperature does...

542
00:41:35,785 --> 00:41:40,873
<i><font color="#bce4f3">RAPSON:</font> <font color="#6088d2">[ON SPEAKER]</font> Negative 150 degrees
Fahrenheit. We had to look it up.</i>

543
00:41:40,957 --> 00:41:43,167
The temperature dropped
phenomenally fast.

544
00:41:43,251 --> 00:41:46,671
On the ground, people froze before
they could get out of their cars.

545
00:41:46,754 --> 00:41:50,758
- Get me a satellite picture
of Scotland two hours ago.
- Yeah.

546
00:41:50,842 --> 00:41:55,179
We've got mountains of data but nowhere
near enough computer power to analyze it.

547
00:41:55,263 --> 00:41:58,599
- Can you help us?
- Send us what you've got, and we'll do our best.

548
00:41:58,683 --> 00:42:02,353
<i><font color="#bce4f3">RAPSON:</font>
Thanks, Jack. Bye for now.</i>

549
00:42:02,437 --> 00:42:05,606
This is Scotland at the time
the temperature dropped.

550
00:42:08,109 --> 00:42:10,862
<i><font color="#bce4f3">FRANK:</font>
This thing looks just like a hurricane.</i>

551
00:42:10,945 --> 00:42:13,781
<i><font color="#bce4f3">JANET:</font>
Only hurricanes don't form overland.</i>

552
00:42:21,039 --> 00:42:24,042
- Good evening, sir.
- Hey, Harold.

553
00:42:24,125 --> 00:42:26,335
<i>- Thanks, Victor. I'll see you in the morning.</i>
- Right, sir.

554
00:42:26,419 --> 00:42:29,047
- Terrible weather.
- Tell me about it.

555
00:42:33,468 --> 00:42:35,970
Wow.

556
00:42:36,054 --> 00:42:38,097
You live here?

557
00:42:38,181 --> 00:42:41,476
Just on the weekends.
It's my dad's place...

558
00:42:41,559 --> 00:42:43,519
and he's kind of
never around, so...

559
00:42:43,603 --> 00:42:45,605
Where is he?

560
00:42:45,688 --> 00:42:48,149
Skiing in Europe
with my stepmom.

561
00:42:50,401 --> 00:42:52,695
Is this you
and your brother?

562
00:42:52,779 --> 00:42:55,990
Oh, yeah. That's when
we took a bike trip together.

563
00:42:59,744 --> 00:43:04,207
It's been raining like this
for three days now.

564
00:43:04,290 --> 00:43:07,168
<font color="#6088d2">[THUNDERCLAP]</font>

565
00:43:12,423 --> 00:43:15,843
<font color="#6088d2">[HORNS HONKING,
PEOPLE SHOUTING]</font>

566
00:43:30,149 --> 00:43:33,736
- I'm just standin' here.
- You can't stay here.

567
00:43:33,820 --> 00:43:36,948
- I never liked this neighborhood anyway.
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[DOG BARKING]</font></i>

568
00:43:37,031 --> 00:43:39,325
It's a mob scene here
at Grand Central Station.

569
00:43:39,408 --> 00:43:41,619
Over half the platforms
are flooded...

570
00:43:41,702 --> 00:43:44,664
<i>and service has been
suspended on all trains.</i>

571
00:43:44,747 --> 00:43:49,168
<i>With planes still grounded
and trains now out of service, that's bad news...</i>

572
00:43:49,252 --> 00:43:52,922
Victor's coming to pick me up. Do you guys
want a ride to the train station?

573
00:43:53,005 --> 00:43:56,092
<i>- Stranded since this morning.</i>
- Not anymore.

574
00:43:56,175 --> 00:44:00,721
In Nova Scotia earlier, the ocean rose
by 25 feet in a matter of seconds.

575
00:44:00,805 --> 00:44:04,976
What we have feared for the past few days
has indeed happened.

576
00:44:05,059 --> 00:44:07,311
<i>The cold front moving down
from the Arctic...</i>

577
00:44:07,395 --> 00:44:10,148
<i>has created an enormous
storm system in Canada...</i>

578
00:44:10,231 --> 00:44:13,651
which, incredible as it sounds,
looks like a tropical hurricane.

579
00:44:13,734 --> 00:44:17,155
I gotta go pick up my little brother.
Do you guys want a ride?

580
00:44:17,238 --> 00:44:20,533
- Where is he?
- He's in a boarding school in Philadelphia.

581
00:44:20,616 --> 00:44:25,538
If this system moves south,
we could see a wind-driven storm surge...

582
00:44:25,621 --> 00:44:28,749
that could threaten
the entire Eastern Seaboard.

583
00:44:28,833 --> 00:44:33,045
Okay. Bye. Victor's stuck
in traffic on Fifth Avenue.

584
00:44:33,129 --> 00:44:36,048
<i>It'll be easier to head out of town
if we meet him over there.</i>

585
00:44:36,132 --> 00:44:39,260
- All right.
- You mean walk? No, not in this.

586
00:44:40,469 --> 00:44:43,055
<i><font color="#6088d2">[THUNDER RUMBLING]</font></i>

587
00:44:43,139 --> 00:44:45,433
We should take
the stairs.

588
00:44:45,516 --> 00:44:48,186
We're on the top floor.

589
00:44:50,354 --> 00:44:52,273
I guess we're walkin'.

590
00:44:54,775 --> 00:44:56,944
<i><font color="#6088d2">[THUNDERCLAP]</font></i>

591
00:44:57,028 --> 00:45:00,406
<font color="#6088d2">[HORNS HONKING,
PEOPLE SHOUTING]</font>

592
00:45:04,619 --> 00:45:09,081
- Maybe we should just stay here.
- I think the young lady is right, sir.

593
00:45:09,165 --> 00:45:12,001
No. We need to get home.

594
00:45:12,084 --> 00:45:15,463
Come on!
<font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING CONTINUES]</font>

595
00:45:24,722 --> 00:45:27,850
<font color="#6088d2">[GOATS BLEATING]</font>

596
00:45:30,436 --> 00:45:32,647
<font color="#6088d2">[GROWLS]</font>

597
00:45:36,651 --> 00:45:38,861
Hey, Cesar, come here.

598
00:45:38,945 --> 00:45:40,947
What are you doing?

599
00:45:45,701 --> 00:45:48,621
The wolves!
They're gone!

600
00:45:48,704 --> 00:45:51,290
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> <font color="#6088d2">[ON NEWS]</font>
Just to give you an idea of the situation...</i>

601
00:45:51,374 --> 00:45:54,502
<i>which seems to be becoming
worse with each passing minute...</i>

602
00:45:54,585 --> 00:45:58,547
<i>at the moment, we have flooding
in most parts of the island.</i>

603
00:45:58,631 --> 00:46:01,467
We've got traffic snarl-ups
because the electricity is now out...

604
00:46:01,550 --> 00:46:04,637
to almost every part
of Manhattan.

605
00:46:04,720 --> 00:46:08,057
No traffic signals,
car accidents... at least 200...

606
00:46:08,140 --> 00:46:12,353
<i>and Lower Manhattan, we've been
told, is virtually inaccessible.</i>

607
00:46:12,436 --> 00:46:16,941
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font>
No one is to be on the streets. Please go inside.</i>

608
00:46:17,024 --> 00:46:20,528
- <font color="#6088d2">[EXCITED CHATTERING]</font>
- Sir, just calm down.

609
00:46:22,363 --> 00:46:25,950
<i>Public library's right up here. Make your way
up there. You can stay warm and dry.</i>

610
00:46:26,033 --> 00:46:28,202
<i><font color="#6088d2">[CHATTERING CONTINUES]</font></i>

611
00:46:29,453 --> 00:46:32,456
Sir, just take it easy.

612
00:46:32,540 --> 00:46:35,876
Um, can you call Mom?
Please phone her for me.

613
00:46:35,960 --> 00:46:37,878
- Hey.
- <font color="#6088d2">[BLUBBERING]</font>

614
00:46:37,962 --> 00:46:39,964
That dog can't come in here.

615
00:46:40,047 --> 00:46:42,550
Come on, man.
It's pouring out there.

616
00:46:42,633 --> 00:46:45,720
<i>I don't care.
Read the sign.</i>

617
00:46:46,846 --> 00:46:49,724
It's supposed to be
a public library.

618
00:46:49,807 --> 00:46:52,893
<i><font color="#6088d2">[EXCITED CHATTERING]</font></i>

619
00:46:55,813 --> 00:46:58,316
Come on, guys.
This way.

620
00:46:58,399 --> 00:47:00,818
Excuse me.
Your bad.

621
00:47:00,901 --> 00:47:03,904
Goddamn $ 1,500
waterproof raincoat!

622
00:47:03,988 --> 00:47:05,906
Please shut up, man.

623
00:47:05,990 --> 00:47:08,659
- There must be rats everywhere.
- That's 'cause it's New York.

624
00:47:08,743 --> 00:47:12,705
Hey! Hey!
Open up, big poppa!

625
00:47:12,788 --> 00:47:16,542
<i>It's out of service.
It's out of service!</i>

626
00:47:16,625 --> 00:47:19,545
- No, no. I'll give you $ 100 to put it in service.
<i>- You don't have to do that.</i>

627
00:47:19,628 --> 00:47:22,965
No, no. Really, $200.
I won't have it. I won't have it.

628
00:47:23,049 --> 00:47:25,926
<i>Oh, God, I love buses.
This is just so much fun.</i>

629
00:47:26,010 --> 00:47:28,512
- <font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING]</font>
- Hello?

630
00:47:28,596 --> 00:47:31,098
I can't reach my driver.
I lost the signal.

631
00:47:31,182 --> 00:47:33,851
This is insane. We should just go back
to your apartment.

632
00:47:33,934 --> 00:47:35,853
<i><font color="#bce4f3">BRIAN:</font>
Yeah. I vote for that.</i>

633
00:47:35,936 --> 00:47:38,522
What? Are you kidding?
We have to get higher!

634
00:47:38,606 --> 00:47:41,609
Come on.
Up to the library.

635
00:47:41,692 --> 00:47:44,403
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> Calm down!</i>
- <font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING IN FRENCH]</font>

636
00:47:44,487 --> 00:47:47,198
I can't understand
what you're saying.

637
00:47:47,281 --> 00:47:51,160
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING CONTINUES]</font></i>
- Just stay calm, ma'am. I will get you out.

638
00:47:51,243 --> 00:47:53,954
<font color="#6088d2">[SCREAMS]</font>

639
00:47:56,582 --> 00:47:59,168
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font>
The door is jammed!</i>

640
00:47:59,251 --> 00:48:01,462
- <font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING CONTINUES]</font>
- I don't speak French.

641
00:48:01,545 --> 00:48:04,215
<font color="#6088d2">[SCREAMING]</font>

642
00:48:05,341 --> 00:48:07,968
<font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING CONTINUES]</font>

643
00:48:08,135 --> 00:48:11,013
<font color="#6088d2">[THUNDERCLAP]</font>

644
00:48:32,618 --> 00:48:35,329
<font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING CONTINUES]</font>

645
00:48:36,914 --> 00:48:40,126
- Hey, where is Laura?
- <font color="#6088d2">[WOMAN SPEAKING FRENCH]</font>

646
00:48:40,209 --> 00:48:43,587
<i>- She was just right there.</i>
- She's right there! Right there! See?

647
00:48:43,671 --> 00:48:46,173
What... What is she doing?

648
00:48:46,257 --> 00:48:49,093
- Tell them to cover their eyes.
- <font color="#6088d2">[SPEAKING FRENCH]</font>

649
00:48:49,176 --> 00:48:51,387
- <font color="#6088d2">[FRENCH]</font>
- <font color="#6088d2">[GRUNTS]</font>

650
00:48:51,470 --> 00:48:54,515
- <font color="#6088d2">[CHILD SCREAMS]</font>
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[THUNDERCLAP]</font></i>

651
00:49:12,283 --> 00:49:15,453
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> <font color="#6088d2">[ON NEWS]</font> There is a wall of water
coming towards New York City!</i>

652
00:49:15,536 --> 00:49:17,455
<i>Everybody...</i>

653
00:49:18,747 --> 00:49:21,208
<font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING, SCREAMING]</font>

654
00:49:24,962 --> 00:49:27,882
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[WOMAN SCREAMS]</font></i>
- <font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING CONTINUES]</font>

655
00:49:58,996 --> 00:50:01,624
- <font color="#6088d2">[SHOUTING IN FRENCH]</font>
- What's the problem?

656
00:50:01,707 --> 00:50:03,918
She left her bag in the cab.
Their passports.

657
00:50:04,001 --> 00:50:06,170
<i><font color="#bce4f3">OFFICER:</font>
Forget about it!</i>

658
00:50:06,253 --> 00:50:09,048
- I'll get it for her.
- Come on!

659
00:50:14,261 --> 00:50:16,347
Oh, my...

660
00:50:22,394 --> 00:50:24,605
Laura!

661
00:50:29,443 --> 00:50:31,820
Laura!

662
00:50:31,904 --> 00:50:33,906
- No! No!
- No, Sam! Sam, no!

663
00:50:33,989 --> 00:50:38,118
<i>- Laura! Laura! Laura! Come on!</i>
- <font color="#6088d2">[GASPS]</font>

664
00:50:38,202 --> 00:50:41,372
<i>Come! Come on!</i>

665
00:50:42,706 --> 00:50:45,543
- Sam!
- Go!

666
00:51:03,769 --> 00:51:07,064
<i><font color="#6088d2">[DOG BARKING]</font></i>

667
00:51:23,872 --> 00:51:25,791
Professor.

668
00:51:25,874 --> 00:51:28,210
Thank you.

669
00:51:28,294 --> 00:51:30,838
<font color="#6088d2">[CHUCKLES]</font>
Is that Neville's handiwork?

670
00:51:30,921 --> 00:51:33,757
Neville's way beyond
stick figures. He's six already.

671
00:51:33,841 --> 00:51:36,260
- Hmm.
<i>- No. This masterpiece...</i>

672
00:51:36,343 --> 00:51:39,013
belongs to my second
grandson, David.

673
00:51:39,096 --> 00:51:41,390
Can't believe
Neville's six already.

674
00:51:45,060 --> 00:51:47,187
You won't believe
how fast they grow.

675
00:51:49,064 --> 00:51:51,317
Professor, I've got
Jack Hall on the phone.

676
00:51:51,400 --> 00:51:54,361
<i>They've run the data
we've sent them.</i>

677
00:51:55,446 --> 00:51:57,364
Here he is.

678
00:51:59,575 --> 00:52:03,454
Jack, were you able
to re-create the thermal cycle?

679
00:52:03,537 --> 00:52:08,792
Yes. The storm's rotation is pulling super-cooled
air down from the upper troposphere.

680
00:52:11,879 --> 00:52:15,841
<i>But shouldn't the air warm up
before it reaches ground level?</i>

681
00:52:15,924 --> 00:52:20,471
<i>It should, but it doesn't.
The air's descending too rapidly.</i>

682
00:52:20,554 --> 00:52:23,724
Is this
an isolated incident?

683
00:52:26,143 --> 00:52:28,062
I'm afraid not.

684
00:52:28,145 --> 00:52:31,857
We've located two other supercells
in addition to the one over Scotland.

685
00:52:31,940 --> 00:52:36,153
There's one over Northern Canada
and another one over Siberia.

686
00:52:36,236 --> 00:52:39,740
And do we know
their projected path?

687
00:52:39,823 --> 00:52:44,328
<i>Yes. Our previous estimates of six
to eight weeks weren't even close.</i>

688
00:52:44,411 --> 00:52:48,040
<i>This one storm is going
to change the face of our planet.</i>

689
00:52:48,123 --> 00:52:51,251
<i>Here's a projection
of 24 hours out.</i>

690
00:52:56,340 --> 00:52:59,093
This is 48 hours out.

691
00:53:01,178 --> 00:53:03,430
<i>Andin seven to 10 days.</i>

692
00:53:07,101 --> 00:53:11,230
<i>When this storm is over,
we'll be in a new ice age.</i>

693
00:53:16,068 --> 00:53:17,986
My God.

694
00:53:36,255 --> 00:53:40,300
Professor, it's time
you got out of there.

695
00:53:42,136 --> 00:53:45,472
I'm afraid that time
has come and gone, my friend.

696
00:53:50,352 --> 00:53:52,813
What can we do?

697
00:53:55,816 --> 00:53:58,569
Save as many as you can.

698
00:53:58,652 --> 00:54:01,530
<font color="#6088d2">[FEEDBACK ON LINE]</font>

699
00:54:03,657 --> 00:54:06,034
<font color="#6088d2">[DISCONNECT SIGNAL]</font>

700
00:54:09,329 --> 00:54:12,166
<i><font color="#6088d2">[PHONE RINGING]</font></i>

701
00:54:13,500 --> 00:54:17,588
Jack. Something's
happened in New York.

702
00:54:27,723 --> 00:54:30,934
No. The power is out.
I've been in here all day.

703
00:54:31,018 --> 00:54:34,271
- <font color="#bce4f3">OFFICER:</font> Who needs help?
- Over here. Over here.

704
00:54:34,354 --> 00:54:36,732
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]</font></i>
- Hi.

705
00:54:36,815 --> 00:54:39,443
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> Hello.
- <font color="#6088d2">[DOG WHIMPERING]</font></i>

706
00:54:40,736 --> 00:54:43,363
What?

707
00:54:43,447 --> 00:54:48,494
This is the last one.
Enjoy it. Greedy.

708
00:54:48,577 --> 00:54:51,246
<font color="#bce4f3">OPERATOR:</font>
All circuits are busy.

709
00:54:51,330 --> 00:54:54,249
Listen. Thanks
for coming back for me.

710
00:54:55,709 --> 00:54:57,753
It was really brave.

711
00:55:09,932 --> 00:55:12,226
I guess I better
return her bag.

712
00:55:26,114 --> 00:55:28,784
<font color="#6088d2">[SPEAKING FRENCH]</font>

713
00:55:28,867 --> 00:55:33,455
<i>Sam? Just tell her
how you feel.</i>

714
00:55:37,084 --> 00:55:39,002
Yeah.

715
00:55:40,712 --> 00:55:43,173
<i><font color="#6088d2">[DIALING PHONE]</font></i>

716
00:55:43,257 --> 00:55:46,051
Did you reach
your little brother yet?

717
00:55:46,134 --> 00:55:50,806
No. There's still no service.
Damn cell phones.

718
00:55:54,142 --> 00:55:56,353
- Excuse me.
- Yes?

719
00:55:56,436 --> 00:55:59,189
<i>- Are there any payphones on the upper floors?</i>
- No. No.

720
00:55:59,273 --> 00:56:01,900
- But there are some on the mezzanine.
- Great.

721
00:56:01,984 --> 00:56:04,403
- But I think it's underwater.
- Where are you going?

722
00:56:04,486 --> 00:56:08,323
- The power's out.
- Older pay phones draw their
power directly from the line.

723
00:56:08,407 --> 00:56:11,034
<i><font color="#6088d2">[WOMAN ON P.A., INDISTINCT]</font></i>

724
00:56:11,118 --> 00:56:14,663
Oh, God. I've been trying
to reach Sam.

725
00:56:14,746 --> 00:56:19,126
- So have I.
- I kept trying to call you,
but I couldn't get through.

726
00:56:19,209 --> 00:56:21,378
It's been a madhouse
around here. Come on.

727
00:56:26,758 --> 00:56:29,136
Are you sure about this?

728
00:56:31,889 --> 00:56:34,474
Ah. Oh.

729
00:56:36,894 --> 00:56:40,647
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[DIAL TONE]</font></i>
- It works.

730
00:56:45,694 --> 00:56:47,905
I love that picture.

731
00:56:47,988 --> 00:56:50,282
Yeah. So do I.

732
00:56:50,365 --> 00:56:53,702
- Where was that taken?
- Miami.

733
00:56:53,785 --> 00:56:56,538
Well, where was I?
I don't remember that trip.

734
00:56:56,622 --> 00:57:01,585
Sam and I went with my sister.
You were in Alaska,
doing research on your doctorate.

735
00:57:05,130 --> 00:57:08,926
- <font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>
- Remember what he was like
when he was that age?

736
00:57:09,009 --> 00:57:12,012
<font color="#6088d2">[CHUCKLES]</font>
Everything was "one more."

737
00:57:12,095 --> 00:57:15,432
One more bedtime story.
One more ride on my shoulders.

738
00:57:15,515 --> 00:57:18,477
"One more, Daddy."

739
00:57:18,560 --> 00:57:22,773
Jack? Sam's on the phone.
Line four.

740
00:57:22,856 --> 00:57:25,567
- Sam?
- Dad!

741
00:57:25,651 --> 00:57:28,528
- Where are you? Are you all right?
- We're at the public library.

742
00:57:28,612 --> 00:57:32,616
Sam, it's Mom.
I'm so happy you're okay.

743
00:57:32,699 --> 00:57:37,371
Mom, can you call Laura and Brian's parents
and tell them we're all right?

744
00:57:37,454 --> 00:57:39,623
Yes. Of course.

745
00:57:39,706 --> 00:57:43,335
- Sam, what's that noise?
- Sam? Sam?

746
00:57:43,418 --> 00:57:48,507
<font color="#6088d2">[GASPING]</font>
What is going on out there, Dad?

747
00:57:48,590 --> 00:57:52,719
Sam? Sam, listen to me.
Listen very carefully.

748
00:57:52,803 --> 00:57:55,514
Forget what I said
about trying to head south.

749
00:57:55,597 --> 00:57:58,517
It's too late for that.
The storm is just gonna get worse.

750
00:57:58,600 --> 00:58:02,646
It's gonna turn into a massive blizzard
with an eye in the center, like a hurricane.

751
00:58:02,729 --> 00:58:05,399
- Uh-huh.
- The air is gonna be so cold...

752
00:58:05,482 --> 00:58:08,235
you could freeze to death
in seconds.

753
00:58:10,445 --> 00:58:13,824
- Sam?
- What should we do?

754
00:58:13,907 --> 00:58:16,994
Listen to me, son.
Do not go outside.

755
00:58:17,077 --> 00:58:20,747
Just burn whatever you can
to stay warm and try to wait it out.

756
00:58:20,831 --> 00:58:24,251
I will come for you.
Do you understand me? I will come for you.

757
00:58:24,334 --> 00:58:26,837
<font color="#6088d2">[SHIVERING]</font>

758
00:58:26,920 --> 00:58:30,757
Sam! Sam, come back!

759
00:58:30,841 --> 00:58:33,885
<font color="#bce4f3">JACK:</font>
Sam? Sam, did you hear me?

760
00:58:33,969 --> 00:58:36,221
Did you hear me?

761
00:58:37,889 --> 00:58:41,101
Sam?
<font color="#6088d2">[SOBBING]</font>

762
00:58:41,184 --> 00:58:43,687
Tell me he's gonna be okay.

763
00:58:43,770 --> 00:58:47,274
He's gonna be all right. He's gonna be all right.
Do you understand me?

764
00:58:47,357 --> 00:58:50,610
<font color="#6088d2">[SOBBING CONTINUES]</font>

765
00:59:08,295 --> 00:59:11,631
<i><font color="#6088d2">[GASPING]</font></i>

766
00:59:11,715 --> 00:59:14,217
<font color="#6088d2">[SHIVERING, PANTING]</font>

767
00:59:14,301 --> 00:59:17,012
<font color="#6088d2">[SOBBING]</font>
I thought you drowned.

768
00:59:22,017 --> 00:59:26,146
- Let's find some dry clothes for you.
- Yeah.

769
00:59:31,568 --> 00:59:34,446
Where did you store
the arctic gear?

770
00:59:34,529 --> 00:59:36,907
You can't make it
to New York, Jack.

771
00:59:36,990 --> 00:59:39,785
I've walked that far
before in the snow.

772
00:59:39,868 --> 00:59:44,456
<i>This is not the same.
Jack, this is not the same!</i>

773
00:59:44,539 --> 00:59:46,500
<i>Lucy, tell him.</i>

774
00:59:48,168 --> 00:59:50,337
I have to do this.

775
00:59:52,589 --> 00:59:54,508
I know.

776
01:00:00,847 --> 01:00:03,975
My hands are shaking.
Shaking.

777
01:00:04,059 --> 01:00:08,021
That's okay. Here.
Here. Come here.

778
01:00:11,900 --> 01:00:14,277
Wh-Wh-What are you doing?

779
01:00:14,361 --> 01:00:17,322
I'm using my body heat
to warm you.

780
01:00:17,405 --> 01:00:22,327
If we let the blood from your arms and legs
rush back to your heart too quickly...

781
01:00:22,410 --> 01:00:24,788
your heart could fail.

782
01:00:28,542 --> 01:00:32,879
Where... Where did you learn that?
<font color="#6088d2">[SHIVERING]</font>

783
01:00:34,714 --> 01:00:38,135
Some of us were actually
paying attention in health class.

784
01:00:41,263 --> 01:00:43,807
How are you feeling?

785
01:00:45,559 --> 01:00:48,145
Much better.

786
01:00:54,276 --> 01:00:56,820
Frank told me about Sam.

787
01:00:56,903 --> 01:00:59,322
I'm not gonna try
to talk you out of going...

788
01:00:59,406 --> 01:01:02,159
but there's something
I need for you to do first.

789
01:01:02,242 --> 01:01:04,870
You have to explain your results
to the administration.

790
01:01:04,953 --> 01:01:07,122
- I already tried that.
- I know this time will be different.

791
01:01:07,205 --> 01:01:09,958
You're gonna brief
the president directly.

792
01:01:12,544 --> 01:01:14,462
<font color="#bce4f3">OFFICER:</font>
Is that the last of it?

793
01:01:14,546 --> 01:01:17,174
- <font color="#bce4f3">LAURA:</font> Yeah. Pretty much.
- Okay.

794
01:01:17,257 --> 01:01:19,885
We also found this radio,
but I don't think it works.

795
01:01:19,968 --> 01:01:22,596
Let me see it.

796
01:01:22,679 --> 01:01:25,932
<font color="#6088d2">[BARKING]</font>

797
01:01:27,726 --> 01:01:30,228
Buddha, be quiet!

798
01:01:30,312 --> 01:01:33,815
You ain't even supposed
to be in here anyway.

799
01:01:33,899 --> 01:01:38,612
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[BARKING CONTINUES]</font>
- <font color="#6088d2">[LOUD RUMBLING]</font></i>

800
01:01:44,034 --> 01:01:46,661
<i><font color="#6088d2">[RUMBLING CONTINUES]</font></i>

801
01:02:17,317 --> 01:02:20,654
<i><font color="#6088d2">[BARKING CONTINUES]</font></i>

802
01:02:28,495 --> 01:02:29,996
Come on, guys.

803
01:02:36,878 --> 01:02:39,005
Oh, my God.

804
01:02:48,390 --> 01:02:51,017
<i><font color="#6088d2">[GLASS SHATTERING]</font></i>

805
01:03:01,528 --> 01:03:04,281
The basic rule of storms
is that they continue...

806
01:03:04,364 --> 01:03:07,450
until the imbalance
that created them is corrected.

807
01:03:07,534 --> 01:03:11,246
In this case, we're talking
about a global realignment.

808
01:03:11,329 --> 01:03:14,624
The superstorm will
last seven to 10 days.

809
01:03:14,708 --> 01:03:19,796
When it's over, ice and snow will cover
the entire Northern Hemisphere.

810
01:03:19,879 --> 01:03:23,466
<i>The ice and snow
will reflect sunlight.</i>

811
01:03:23,550 --> 01:03:25,635
The earth's atmosphere
will restabilize...

812
01:03:25,719 --> 01:03:30,307
but with an average temperature
close to that of the last ice age.

813
01:03:30,390 --> 01:03:32,392
What can we do about this?

814
01:03:32,475 --> 01:03:35,854
<font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>
Head as far south as possible.

815
01:03:35,937 --> 01:03:38,189
That is not amusing,
Professor.

816
01:03:38,273 --> 01:03:40,775
Where do you suggest
they go?

817
01:03:40,859 --> 01:03:43,778
The farther south they go,
the safer they'll be.

818
01:03:43,862 --> 01:03:47,991
Texas. Parts of Florida that aren't flooded.
Mexico would be best.

819
01:03:48,074 --> 01:03:52,162
<i>Mexico? Maybe you should stick to science
and leave policy to us.</i>

820
01:03:52,245 --> 01:03:55,457
<i>Well, we tried that approach. You didn't
want to hear about the science...</i>

821
01:03:55,540 --> 01:03:58,710
when it could
have made a difference.

822
01:03:58,793 --> 01:04:02,672
What exactly are you
proposing, Professor?

823
01:04:08,011 --> 01:04:13,350
Evacuate everyone
south of that line.

824
01:04:18,104 --> 01:04:21,358
What about the people
in the north?

825
01:04:23,526 --> 01:04:26,112
I'm afraid
it's too late for them.

826
01:04:26,196 --> 01:04:30,950
If they go outside,
the storm will kill them.

827
01:04:33,620 --> 01:04:36,206
<i>At this point...</i>

828
01:04:36,289 --> 01:04:39,417
<i>their best chance
is to stay inside...</i>

829
01:04:39,501 --> 01:04:42,962
try to ride it out...

830
01:04:43,046 --> 01:04:44,964
pray.

831
01:04:49,052 --> 01:04:51,721
What do you think he'll do?

832
01:04:51,805 --> 01:04:54,015
I don't know.

833
01:04:54,099 --> 01:04:56,935
Jack, thanks.

834
01:04:57,018 --> 01:04:58,937
And good luck.

835
01:04:59,020 --> 01:05:00,980
You too.

836
01:05:02,732 --> 01:05:04,692
We're all gonna need it.

837
01:05:07,404 --> 01:05:09,781
We can't evacuate
half the country...

838
01:05:09,864 --> 01:05:12,575
because one scientist
thinks the climate is shifting.

839
01:05:12,659 --> 01:05:15,245
<i>Every minute we delay
is costing lives.</i>

840
01:05:15,328 --> 01:05:17,455
What about the other
half of the country?

841
01:05:17,539 --> 01:05:21,751
If Professor Hall is right, sending troops north
will create more victims.

842
01:05:21,835 --> 01:05:25,046
<i>We need to save the people
we can right now.</i>

843
01:05:25,130 --> 01:05:27,966
<i>We take the same approach
in triage on the battlefield.</i>

844
01:05:28,049 --> 01:05:30,760
Sometimes it's necessary
to make difficult choices!

845
01:05:30,844 --> 01:05:33,805
I don't accept that abandoning
half of the country is necessary.

846
01:05:33,888 --> 01:05:36,808
Maybe if you would've listened
to him sooner, it wouldn't be.

847
01:05:36,891 --> 01:05:40,019
<i>Bullshit. It's easy for him to suggest this plan.
He's safely here in Washington.</i>

848
01:05:40,103 --> 01:05:42,439
His son is in Manhattan.

849
01:05:45,859 --> 01:05:49,362
<i>I just thought you should know that before
you start questioning his motives.</i>

850
01:05:51,656 --> 01:05:53,575
We're going to follow
Hall's plan.

851
01:05:55,743 --> 01:05:58,329
- General.
- Sir.

852
01:05:58,413 --> 01:06:01,958
Give the order for the National Guard
to evacuate the southern states.

853
01:06:02,041 --> 01:06:03,960
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

854
01:06:04,043 --> 01:06:06,379
<i><font color="#6088d2">[DOOR CLOSES]</font></i>

855
01:06:17,182 --> 01:06:20,226
Vivian, uh,
get me my wife.

856
01:06:22,437 --> 01:06:25,231
<i><font color="#6088d2">[WIND HOWLING]</font></i>

857
01:06:27,609 --> 01:06:30,403
<i><font color="#6088d2">[GENERATOR CHUGGING]</font></i>

858
01:06:39,579 --> 01:06:43,124
Sorry, mates, but we're
just about out of petrol.

859
01:06:46,461 --> 01:06:50,048
Hey, is there any chance...

860
01:06:50,131 --> 01:06:54,219
that it will run... on this?

861
01:06:54,302 --> 01:06:57,055
- <font color="#6088d2">[CHUCKLES]</font>
- Are you mad?

862
01:06:57,138 --> 01:06:59,599
That's a 12-year-old scotch.

863
01:07:07,190 --> 01:07:09,484
<font color="#6088d2">[LAUGHS]</font>

864
01:07:21,454 --> 01:07:24,624
Gentlemen. To England.

865
01:07:26,960 --> 01:07:29,003
To mankind.

866
01:07:30,463 --> 01:07:32,423
To Manchester United.

867
01:07:32,507 --> 01:07:35,134
<font color="#6088d2">[ALL LAUGHING]</font>

868
01:07:40,348 --> 01:07:44,978
I just... I just wish I could've seen him
grow up, you know?

869
01:07:49,315 --> 01:07:51,901
The important thing is
he will grow up.

870
01:07:57,115 --> 01:07:59,409
Amen.

871
01:08:15,633 --> 01:08:18,303
Maybe you should have
somebody help you with that.

872
01:08:18,386 --> 01:08:22,140
Sir, I am president
of the electronics club...

873
01:08:22,223 --> 01:08:24,434
the math club
and the chess club.

874
01:08:24,517 --> 01:08:27,437
Now, if there's a bigger nerd
in here, please point him out.

875
01:08:29,272 --> 01:08:32,025
I'll just leave you alone
to work on it.

876
01:08:33,484 --> 01:08:36,863
Come on, Buddha. Come on.
Do your business.

877
01:08:36,946 --> 01:08:39,782
Look. There's nobody around.

878
01:08:39,866 --> 01:08:43,036
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[BUDDHA WHIMPERING]</font></i>
- Okay. You know what?
I'll turn around. I won't look.

879
01:08:43,119 --> 01:08:45,705
- I promise.
- <font color="#6088d2">[BARKING]</font>

880
01:08:45,788 --> 01:08:49,709
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[BARKING CONTINUES]</font></i>
- What?

881
01:08:55,673 --> 01:08:59,177
Hey, man. There's people out there.
I was walking my dog.

882
01:08:59,260 --> 01:09:03,389
There's hundreds of 'em.
They're walkin' on the snow.

883
01:09:06,893 --> 01:09:09,062
<i><font color="#6088d2">[CHATTERING]</font></i>

884
01:09:11,147 --> 01:09:13,191
<i><font color="#bce4f3">OFFICER:</font>
Where are they all going?</i>

885
01:09:13,274 --> 01:09:16,277
<i>They're gettin' out of the city
before it's too late.</i>

886
01:09:18,821 --> 01:09:22,116
All right, everybody.
Quiet down.

887
01:09:22,200 --> 01:09:25,870
When was the last time
anyone got a signal on a cell phone?

888
01:09:25,953 --> 01:09:30,041
I got through to my cousin in Memphis an hour
ago. They're being evacuated to the south.

889
01:09:30,124 --> 01:09:34,420
<i>We should get moving too.
The water's frozen over enough to walk on.</i>

890
01:09:34,504 --> 01:09:37,840
We should get going before
the snow gets too deep.

891
01:09:37,924 --> 01:09:42,178
<i>Everyone, wrap yourselves
up as fast as you can.</i>

892
01:09:42,261 --> 01:09:44,430
- We shouldn't go.
<i>- We're leaving in five minutes.</i>

893
01:09:44,514 --> 01:09:48,267
- Why not, Sam?
- When I talked to my dad, he
told me we should stay inside.

894
01:09:48,351 --> 01:09:51,229
- The storm will kill anybody caught in it.
- Then you have to say something.

895
01:09:51,312 --> 01:09:53,064
I know.

896
01:09:53,147 --> 01:09:56,776
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">OFFICER:</font> Line up. That's it.
- <font color="#6088d2">[CHATTERING]</font></i>

897
01:09:56,859 --> 01:09:59,946
Excuse me, sir.
You're making a mistake.

898
01:10:00,029 --> 01:10:03,324
What? Hey, listen, son. We're all scared here,
but we got no choice.

899
01:10:03,408 --> 01:10:05,451
- That's not it.
- Get ready to go.

900
01:10:05,535 --> 01:10:08,913
If these people go outside,
they will freeze to death!

901
01:10:08,996 --> 01:10:12,375
- Okay. What is this nonsense?
- It's not nonsense, all right?

902
01:10:12,458 --> 01:10:15,253
Look. This storm
is gonna get worse...

903
01:10:15,336 --> 01:10:18,047
and the people who are caught outside,
they will freeze to death.

904
01:10:18,131 --> 01:10:21,092
- Where are you getting this information?
- My father's a climatologist.

905
01:10:21,175 --> 01:10:25,888
- What are you suggesting we do?
- We stay inside, we keep warm,
and we wait it out.

906
01:10:25,972 --> 01:10:28,516
The snow is getting
deeper by the minute.

907
01:10:28,599 --> 01:10:31,602
- We'd be trapped here without food, supplies.
- It's a risk. Yeah.

908
01:10:31,686 --> 01:10:34,355
<i>- An unnecessary risk.
- No, no, no. It's not.</i>

909
01:10:34,439 --> 01:10:38,401
<i>We've wasted enough time talking about this.
Come on, people. Let's go.</i>

910
01:10:38,484 --> 01:10:40,653
Look. Look. Look.
Just look for a second.

911
01:10:40,737 --> 01:10:43,781
<i>- Come on, everybody. Let's get going.
- One second.</i>

912
01:10:43,865 --> 01:10:46,492
The storm is gonna get bad.
It's gonna get really bad.

913
01:10:46,576 --> 01:10:49,662
You're not gonna be able
to survive in it.

914
01:10:49,746 --> 01:10:52,874
<i>Believe me.
Sir, please just stay.</i>

915
01:10:52,957 --> 01:10:55,835
<i>Just stay.</i>

916
01:10:55,918 --> 01:10:58,379
Just don't...

917
01:10:58,463 --> 01:11:00,381
I'm...

918
01:11:03,217 --> 01:11:05,762
<i><font color="#6088d2">[WIND HOWLING]</font></i>

919
01:11:26,699 --> 01:11:28,785
She's set to go.

920
01:11:28,868 --> 01:11:30,953
Come on.
Straight to the back, guys.

921
01:11:31,037 --> 01:11:32,955
<i><font color="#bce4f3">JACK:</font> <font color="#6088d2">[ON PHONE]</font>
It'll be impossible to reach each other.</i>

922
01:11:33,039 --> 01:11:35,833
<i>Leave a message for me
at the American Embassy in Mexico City.</i>

923
01:11:35,917 --> 01:11:37,835
Okay. I will.

924
01:11:37,919 --> 01:11:40,046
I love you.

925
01:11:43,174 --> 01:11:45,968
I love you, Jack.

926
01:11:46,052 --> 01:11:48,721
Tell Sam I love him so much.

927
01:11:50,973 --> 01:11:52,975
God be with you.

928
01:11:53,059 --> 01:11:55,186
<font color="#6088d2">[LINE DISCONNECTS]</font>

929
01:12:00,066 --> 01:12:02,318
- Dr. Hall?
- Yeah.

930
01:12:02,401 --> 01:12:04,695
We haven't been able
to reach Peter's parents.

931
01:12:04,779 --> 01:12:08,199
- I'm gonna try later, okay?
- Okay. Thank you.

932
01:12:15,873 --> 01:12:17,917
I got it.

933
01:12:18,000 --> 01:12:21,295
You're supposed to be
on a bus heading south.

934
01:12:21,379 --> 01:12:24,173
I've been watching
your back for 20 years.

935
01:12:24,257 --> 01:12:26,676
You think I'd let you
go alone?

936
01:12:26,759 --> 01:12:29,679
All these years, I thought
I was watching your back.

937
01:12:29,762 --> 01:12:33,349
- Where are the keys?
- In the truck.

938
01:12:33,432 --> 01:12:35,852
Where do you think
you're going?

939
01:12:35,935 --> 01:12:38,813
Neither one of you
knows how to navigate worth a damn.

940
01:12:38,896 --> 01:12:40,940
Without me, you'll
end up in Cleveland.

941
01:12:42,859 --> 01:12:46,404
<i>I'll try to give you updates on the storm
as it heads your way.</i>

942
01:12:46,487 --> 01:12:49,115
Good luck, Jack.

943
01:12:49,198 --> 01:12:51,117
<i><font color="#6088d2">[ENGINE STARTS]</font></i>

944
01:13:02,336 --> 01:13:05,339
<i><font color="#bce4f3">WOMAN REPORTING:</font>
Breaking news from the U.S.-Mexico border.</i>

945
01:13:05,423 --> 01:13:08,634
Just half an hour ago,
Mexican officials closed the border...

946
01:13:08,718 --> 01:13:12,722
in the light of so many U.S. refugees
who are fleeing south...

947
01:13:12,805 --> 01:13:15,099
<i>in the wake
of the approaching storm.</i>

948
01:13:15,182 --> 01:13:18,686
<i>These people came here
in anticipation of crossing into Mexico.</i>

949
01:13:18,769 --> 01:13:21,647
<i>Instead, they've been met
with closed gates...</i>

950
01:13:21,731 --> 01:13:24,108
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN REPORTING:</font> And now, in a dramatic
reversal of illegal immigration...</i>

951
01:13:24,191 --> 01:13:27,862
thousands of people
are crossing the Rio Grande into Mexico.

952
01:13:27,945 --> 01:13:32,158
<i>The scene that's unfolding here behind me
is one of desperation and frustration.</i>

953
01:13:32,241 --> 01:13:35,536
<i>People have abandoned their
cars, grabbed their belongings...</i>

954
01:13:35,620 --> 01:13:40,207
<i>and they are wading across
the river illegally into Mexico.</i>

955
01:13:42,251 --> 01:13:44,170
Here it is.

956
01:13:44,253 --> 01:13:49,050
Oh, this fireplace probably hasn't been used
in about a hundred years.

957
01:13:51,719 --> 01:13:54,138
All right.

958
01:13:59,226 --> 01:14:02,730
- What are you doing?
- What do you think we were gonna burn?

959
01:14:02,813 --> 01:14:06,275
- You can't burn books.
- No. Absolutely not!

960
01:14:06,359 --> 01:14:09,862
You wanna freeze to death?

961
01:14:11,155 --> 01:14:14,992
- I'll go get some more.
- I'll help you.

962
01:14:15,076 --> 01:14:17,078
I'm going with them.

963
01:14:18,454 --> 01:14:21,749
Okay. Do you have
a cafeteria or a lunchroom?

964
01:14:21,832 --> 01:14:24,335
Just an employees' lounge
with a few vending machines.

965
01:14:24,418 --> 01:14:27,380
<i><font color="#6088d2">[BUDDHA BARKING]</font></i>

966
01:14:32,176 --> 01:14:34,845
We're not gonna last very long
on M&M's and potato chips.

967
01:14:34,929 --> 01:14:38,724
What about the garbage cans? There's always
somethin' to eat in the garbage.

968
01:14:38,808 --> 01:14:40,977
<i><font color="#6088d2">[BUDDHA WHIMPERING]</font></i>

969
01:14:43,980 --> 01:14:46,941
Friedrich Nietzsche.
We cannot burn Friedrich Nietzsche.

970
01:14:47,024 --> 01:14:50,111
He was the most important
thinker of the 19th century.

971
01:14:50,194 --> 01:14:52,989
Oh, please. Nietzsche was a chauvinist pig
who was in love with his sister.

972
01:14:53,072 --> 01:14:56,993
- He was not a chauvinist pig.
- But he was in love with his sister.

973
01:14:57,076 --> 01:14:59,120
<i><font color="#bce4f3">BRIAN:</font>
Uh, excuse me. You guys?</i>

974
01:14:59,203 --> 01:15:03,290
Yeah. There's a whole section on tax law
down here that we can burn.

975
01:15:03,374 --> 01:15:09,046
<i>Afterhours of uncertainty, the traffic
is moving smoothly from the U.S. into Mexico.</i>

976
01:15:09,130 --> 01:15:13,259
This is only possible because the president
was able to negotiate a deal...

977
01:15:13,342 --> 01:15:15,511
to forgive
all Latin American debt...

978
01:15:15,594 --> 01:15:18,389
<i>in exchange
for opening the border.</i>

979
01:15:18,472 --> 01:15:22,143
<i>Now multitudes of American
families are feeling...</i>

980
01:15:22,226 --> 01:15:25,354
<font color="#6088d2">[QUIET READING]</font>

981
01:15:25,438 --> 01:15:28,441
- Lucy.
- <font color="#6088d2">[STOPS READING]</font>

982
01:15:33,320 --> 01:15:36,407
- Is Peter's ambulance here?
- No.

983
01:15:41,746 --> 01:15:43,664
Why?

984
01:15:43,748 --> 01:15:45,666
- They've all gone.
- What?

985
01:15:45,750 --> 01:15:48,127
In the confusion...
I don't know what happened.

986
01:15:48,210 --> 01:15:50,963
People just started
to panic, and they left.

987
01:15:51,047 --> 01:15:54,633
Now, there's a policeman with a snowplow.
He's waiting outside.

988
01:15:54,717 --> 01:15:57,928
Peter can't be moved
in anything but an ambulance.

989
01:15:58,012 --> 01:16:02,600
I called and left a message for the county
ambulance service.

990
01:16:10,483 --> 01:16:12,443
Okay.

991
01:16:14,153 --> 01:16:16,864
You should go,
and I'll stay and wait.

992
01:16:16,947 --> 01:16:19,366
Lucy, no. No.

993
01:16:19,450 --> 01:16:22,828
You should go.
He's not gonna wait forever.

994
01:16:22,912 --> 01:16:24,830
It's okay.

995
01:16:27,333 --> 01:16:29,418
I'm sorry.

996
01:16:29,502 --> 01:16:31,420
It's okay.

997
01:16:31,504 --> 01:16:33,714
All right.

998
01:17:00,366 --> 01:17:03,160
- <font color="#6088d2">[GASPS]</font>
- Are you all right?

999
01:17:03,244 --> 01:17:06,247
Yeah. I'm fine. I just
cut my leg the other day.

1000
01:17:06,330 --> 01:17:09,750
<font color="#6088d2">[RADIO STATIC]</font>

1001
01:17:09,834 --> 01:17:12,169
Did you get a signal?

1002
01:17:12,253 --> 01:17:15,381
- Yeah. For a minute.
- And?

1003
01:17:19,385 --> 01:17:24,140
Man, this storm is everywhere.
It's hit the entire Northern Hemisphere.

1004
01:17:24,223 --> 01:17:27,768
Europe is buried
under 15 feet of snow.

1005
01:17:27,852 --> 01:17:30,312
And they say it's gonna
get just as bad here.

1006
01:17:30,396 --> 01:17:33,649
I mean, I don't think
your dad's gonna make it.

1007
01:17:37,153 --> 01:17:39,071
No. He'll make it.

1008
01:17:43,492 --> 01:17:45,411
He'll make it.

1009
01:17:49,373 --> 01:17:51,292
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> <font color="#6088d2">[ON NEWS]</font>
The White House has ordered...</i>

1010
01:17:51,375 --> 01:17:55,045
the following national disaster
alert for all northern states:

1011
01:17:55,129 --> 01:17:58,174
<i>Continued exposure
to the approaching storm is deadly.</i>

1012
01:17:58,257 --> 01:18:00,634
<i>Remain indoors and take
all measures to stay warm...</i>

1013
01:18:00,718 --> 01:18:03,971
<i>burning any fuel sources
until the storm is over.</i>

1014
01:18:04,054 --> 01:18:06,348
<i>Roads are impassable
across New York State...</i>

1015
01:18:06,432 --> 01:18:09,143
<i>- and as far south as Pennsylvania.</i>
- Where are we?

1016
01:18:09,226 --> 01:18:11,687
<i><font color="#6088d2">[MAN ON NEWS CONTINUES,
INDISTINCT]</font></i>

1017
01:18:11,770 --> 01:18:15,065
Looks like we're
just north of Philadelphia.

1018
01:18:15,149 --> 01:18:18,194
<i><font color="#bce4f3">MAN:</font> <font color="#6088d2">[ON NEWS]</font>
Rescue workers say they have no idea...</i>

1019
01:18:18,277 --> 01:18:20,029
Look out!

1020
01:18:22,740 --> 01:18:25,326
You guys okay?

1021
01:18:25,409 --> 01:18:27,620
- Yeah.
<i>- Yeah.</i>

1022
01:18:33,250 --> 01:18:36,712
<i>- Once again, roads
across the northern states...</i>
- Sorry, boss.

1023
01:18:36,795 --> 01:18:41,717
<i>- Are impassable.</i>
- Unpack the snowshoes.
We're walking from here.

1024
01:18:43,260 --> 01:18:46,430
Come on, men.
Let's get up and get going.

1025
01:18:46,513 --> 01:18:51,685
We've only made it to Brooklyn.
Maybe we should just turn back.

1026
01:18:51,769 --> 01:18:54,396
What for? Half the city's
frozen underwater.

1027
01:18:54,480 --> 01:18:57,274
- There's nothing to go back to.
- It's time to get up. Keep moving.

1028
01:18:57,358 --> 01:19:00,945
- We should've stayed in the library.
- Come on, men.

1029
01:19:01,028 --> 01:19:03,906
Okay, guys.
Let's get moving.

1030
01:19:13,165 --> 01:19:15,417
Wake up.

1031
01:19:32,893 --> 01:19:36,730
- What are you doing?
- Insulatin'.

1032
01:19:36,814 --> 01:19:39,358
Newspaper's best,
but this'll do it.

1033
01:19:39,441 --> 01:19:43,529
You know, you spend some years on
the streets, and you learn how to keep warm.

1034
01:19:43,612 --> 01:19:46,532
Hey.

1035
01:19:51,704 --> 01:19:53,622
Thanks.

1036
01:19:57,251 --> 01:20:01,422
I got one.
Your favorite vacation?

1037
01:20:01,505 --> 01:20:04,008
Besides this one?

1038
01:20:04,091 --> 01:20:06,760
<i><font color="#6088d2">[CHUCKLES]</font>
All right.</i>

1039
01:20:06,844 --> 01:20:11,515
I went to Greenland with my dad
on one of his research trips a few years ago...

1040
01:20:14,143 --> 01:20:18,022
and, uh, the ship broke down
and we got stuck.

1041
01:20:19,023 --> 01:20:21,817
<i>And it rained constantly.</i>

1042
01:20:24,194 --> 01:20:26,739
That sounds really boring.

1043
01:20:27,823 --> 01:20:30,159
It was actually really nice.

1044
01:20:30,242 --> 01:20:33,412
Just me and my dad
hanging out for 10 days.

1045
01:20:39,209 --> 01:20:41,211
<font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>

1046
01:21:21,001 --> 01:21:24,463
<font color="#6088d2">[GRUNTING, SCREAMING]</font>

1047
01:21:37,226 --> 01:21:39,395
<font color="#6088d2">[GROANING, WHIMPERING]</font>

1048
01:21:46,110 --> 01:21:48,028
<i><font color="#bce4f3">JACK:</font>
Frank!</i>

1049
01:21:48,112 --> 01:21:51,490
- Are you all right?
<i>- I'm fine!</i>

1050
01:21:53,242 --> 01:21:55,911
Just dropped in
to do a little shopping.

1051
01:21:55,994 --> 01:21:58,831
<i>I gotta lose this sled.</i>

1052
01:22:15,556 --> 01:22:17,891
Hold on!
We'll pull you up!

1053
01:22:20,144 --> 01:22:23,313
Jason! You gotta
support Frank's weight!

1054
01:22:23,397 --> 01:22:25,691
Okay! I'll try!

1055
01:22:28,402 --> 01:22:30,195
<font color="#6088d2">[GRUNTING]</font>

1056
01:22:32,406 --> 01:22:35,284
Okay! I think
I have his weight now!

1057
01:22:35,367 --> 01:22:37,202
I'm coming to you!

1058
01:22:43,834 --> 01:22:46,211
<i><font color="#6088d2">[GLASS CRACKING]</font></i>

1059
01:22:46,295 --> 01:22:48,255
<font color="#6088d2">[GRUNTING, WHIMPERING]</font>

1060
01:22:49,256 --> 01:22:51,216
The glass is breaking!

1061
01:22:54,303 --> 01:22:56,138
Too much weight!

1062
01:23:00,017 --> 01:23:01,560
It's not gonna hold.

1063
01:23:11,195 --> 01:23:12,613
No! No!

1064
01:23:12,696 --> 01:23:15,949
Frank!
I can get you out!

1065
01:23:17,701 --> 01:23:19,828
<i><font color="#bce4f3">JACK:</font>
Don't do it!</i>

1066
01:23:19,912 --> 01:23:22,414
- No! Frank! Don't!
- Frank, no!

1067
01:23:23,957 --> 01:23:25,709
Frank!

1068
01:24:09,461 --> 01:24:11,630
<i><font color="#bce4f3">WOMAN:</font>
What have you got there?</i>

1069
01:24:11,713 --> 01:24:13,632
A Gutenberg Bible.

1070
01:24:13,715 --> 01:24:16,718
It was in
the rare books room.

1071
01:24:18,220 --> 01:24:20,138
You think
God's gonna save you?

1072
01:24:20,222 --> 01:24:21,682
No.

1073
01:24:21,765 --> 01:24:23,684
I don't believe in God.

1074
01:24:23,767 --> 01:24:26,228
You're holding on
to that bible pretty tight.

1075
01:24:26,311 --> 01:24:29,189
- I'm protecting it.
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[BOOK LANDS ON FIRE]</font></i>

1076
01:24:32,693 --> 01:24:36,196
<i>This bible is the first book
ever printed.</i>

1077
01:24:36,280 --> 01:24:39,199
It represents...

1078
01:24:39,283 --> 01:24:41,994
the dawn
of the Age of Reason.

1079
01:24:42,077 --> 01:24:45,747
<i>As far as I'm concerned, the written word
is mankind's greatest achievement.</i>

1080
01:24:45,831 --> 01:24:48,333
- <font color="#6088d2">[SCOFFS QUIETLY]</font>
<i>- You can laugh.</i>

1081
01:24:49,418 --> 01:24:52,504
But if Western civilization
is finished...

1082
01:24:52,588 --> 01:24:57,050
I'm gonna save at least
one little piece of it.

1083
01:25:20,741 --> 01:25:22,743
<i><font color="#6088d2">[RADIO: CHATTER]</font></i>

1084
01:25:33,045 --> 01:25:35,922
We heard somebody
was left behind.

1085
01:25:36,006 --> 01:25:38,383
- <font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>
<i>- We brought an ambulance.</i>

1086
01:25:38,467 --> 01:25:40,469
Thank God.

1087
01:25:43,055 --> 01:25:45,557
Thank you so much
for coming.

1088
01:25:53,607 --> 01:25:57,110
<font color="#6088d2">[SHIVERING]</font>

1089
01:25:59,821 --> 01:26:01,990
<i><font color="#6088d2">[LAURA COUGHING]</font></i>

1090
01:26:06,578 --> 01:26:08,872
<i>Hey.</i>

1091
01:26:08,955 --> 01:26:11,500
Hey, are you all right?

1092
01:26:11,583 --> 01:26:15,921
- You look like you have a fever or something.
- I'm fine.

1093
01:26:16,004 --> 01:26:18,173
I just can't sleep.

1094
01:26:20,926 --> 01:26:26,181
My mind keeps going over
all those worthless decathlon facts.

1095
01:26:27,849 --> 01:26:29,768
It's pretty stupid, huh?

1096
01:26:29,851 --> 01:26:33,522
No, it's all right. I guess you just haven't
had time to adjust yet.

1097
01:26:35,691 --> 01:26:38,610
How am I supposed
to adjust, Sam?

1098
01:26:38,694 --> 01:26:40,612
Everything
I've ever cared about...

1099
01:26:40,696 --> 01:26:43,407
everything I've worked for...

1100
01:26:43,490 --> 01:26:47,119
has all been preparation
for a future that no longer exists.

1101
01:26:50,580 --> 01:26:54,793
I know you always thought
I took the competition too seriously.

1102
01:26:56,002 --> 01:26:58,088
You were right.

1103
01:26:58,171 --> 01:27:00,090
It was all for nothing.

1104
01:27:00,173 --> 01:27:03,468
<i>No... <font color="#6088d2">[SIGHS]</font>
No, I just...</i>

1105
01:27:03,552 --> 01:27:06,555
I just said that to
avoid admitting the truth.

1106
01:27:07,639 --> 01:27:09,641
The truth about what?

1107
01:27:13,687 --> 01:27:16,398
About why
I joined the team.

1108
01:27:21,987 --> 01:27:24,489
I joined it because of you.

1109
01:27:37,169 --> 01:27:39,171
Hey.

1110
01:27:57,731 --> 01:28:00,108
<i><font color="#6088d2">[RADIO: CHATTER, INDISTINCT]</font></i>

1111
01:28:00,192 --> 01:28:02,235
Get this convoy
moving now.

1112
01:28:04,696 --> 01:28:07,616
<i><font color="#6088d2">[WHISPERING]</font>
I know. I know.</i>

1113
01:28:07,699 --> 01:28:10,243
- Mr. President.
- All right.

1114
01:28:10,327 --> 01:28:13,330
I'm sorry, sir.
We can't wait any longer.

1115
01:28:13,413 --> 01:28:15,665
<i>We're the last ones.</i>

1116
01:28:15,749 --> 01:28:17,751
All right.

1117
01:28:33,183 --> 01:28:35,727
<i><font color="#bce4f3">PILOT:</font>
Mexicali Control, this is Delta 2-6.</i>

1118
01:28:35,811 --> 01:28:38,730
<i>We're carrying an urgent message
for high command.</i>

1119
01:28:38,814 --> 01:28:40,732
<i>Request priority
on landing zone one.</i>

1120
01:28:40,816 --> 01:28:42,984
- <font color="#6088d2">[CHATTERING, SHOUTING]</font>
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[RADIO CHATTER CONTINUES, INDISTINCT]</font></i>

1121
01:28:49,199 --> 01:28:51,117
Sir.

1122
01:28:51,201 --> 01:28:53,703
Thank you, Corporal.
Carry on.

1123
01:29:06,800 --> 01:29:08,802
Madam Secretary?

1124
01:29:18,311 --> 01:29:20,564
Raymond.

1125
01:29:20,647 --> 01:29:23,275
The president's motorcade
got caught in the storm.

1126
01:29:27,988 --> 01:29:29,990
They didn't make it.

1127
01:29:35,954 --> 01:29:38,039
She wouldn't
wake up this morning.

1128
01:29:38,123 --> 01:29:41,543
I-I... I mean, last night she only had a fever.
I don't understand.

1129
01:29:41,626 --> 01:29:43,545
God, she's awfully pale.

1130
01:29:43,628 --> 01:29:46,548
Well, guys, look. None of us has had anything
real to eat in days.

1131
01:29:46,631 --> 01:29:49,718
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">JEREMY:</font> I'm telling you, it's hypothermia.
- How could it be hypothermia?</i>

1132
01:29:49,801 --> 01:29:51,928
- We've all been...
- Maybe it's just the flu, you guys.

1133
01:29:52,012 --> 01:29:54,347
<i>No, no,
it's not the flu.</i>

1134
01:29:55,599 --> 01:29:57,809
Yeah?
And how do you know?

1135
01:29:57,893 --> 01:30:01,313
Books can be good for something other
than burning. Let's go over her symptoms.

1136
01:30:01,396 --> 01:30:04,858
I told you. She has a fever
and a really cold sweat.

1137
01:30:04,941 --> 01:30:06,860
<i><font color="#bce4f3">WOMAN:</font>
How's her pulse?</i>

1138
01:30:06,943 --> 01:30:08,904
It's really fast.

1139
01:30:08,987 --> 01:30:12,240
Did she have any injuries, like a cut
or something that might have gotten infected?

1140
01:30:12,324 --> 01:30:15,994
<i>She was complaining
about a cut on her leg a few days ago.</i>

1141
01:30:16,077 --> 01:30:19,039
<i>I didn't... I didn't
think anything of it.</i>

1142
01:30:23,543 --> 01:30:25,545
<i>Oh, my gosh.</i>

1143
01:30:26,630 --> 01:30:28,548
That's blood poisoning.

1144
01:30:28,632 --> 01:30:32,218
Um, septicemia.
She could go into septic shock.

1145
01:30:32,302 --> 01:30:34,471
I've seen that before.
That can get bad.

1146
01:30:34,554 --> 01:30:36,640
She needs a massive dose
of penicillin...

1147
01:30:36,723 --> 01:30:38,934
or a broad-spectrum
antibiotic immediately...

1148
01:30:39,017 --> 01:30:41,269
or...

1149
01:30:45,231 --> 01:30:47,233
Or what?

1150
01:31:07,671 --> 01:31:10,799
<i>I've never seen anything like it.
There's no point of reference.</i>

1151
01:31:10,882 --> 01:31:12,801
All I can see
is cloud cover.

1152
01:31:12,884 --> 01:31:14,678
What are you doing?

1153
01:31:14,761 --> 01:31:17,973
Taking infrared image
of thermal currents...

1154
01:31:18,056 --> 01:31:20,642
sent to Houston, Korolev...

1155
01:31:20,725 --> 01:31:22,644
your weather service.

1156
01:31:22,727 --> 01:31:24,646
<i><font color="#bce4f3">PARKER:</font>
I'll help you.</i>

1157
01:31:25,772 --> 01:31:27,691
- Tom? Tom, wake up.
- <font color="#6088d2">[GROANS]</font>

1158
01:31:27,774 --> 01:31:30,694
I just received some satellite images
from the space station.

1159
01:31:30,777 --> 01:31:32,779
You'd better take a look.

1160
01:31:44,040 --> 01:31:45,959
How big is this thing?

1161
01:31:46,042 --> 01:31:48,753
The vortex is 50 miles in diameter
and growing.

1162
01:31:48,837 --> 01:31:51,297
<i>The two cells over Europe and Asia
are even bigger.</i>

1163
01:31:51,381 --> 01:31:53,299
<i><font color="#bce4f3">TOM:</font>
Good God.</i>

1164
01:31:53,383 --> 01:31:56,594
This one's gonna hit New York
inside an hour.

1165
01:31:59,014 --> 01:32:01,599
<font color="#6088d2">[GASPING, PANTING]</font>
Jack...

1166
01:32:12,444 --> 01:32:14,362
Jason!

1167
01:32:14,446 --> 01:32:16,156
Are you all right?

1168
01:32:16,239 --> 01:32:22,911
Jason!

1169
01:32:22,912 --> 01:32:24,914
<font color="#6088d2">[PANTING, GASPING]</font>

1170
01:32:27,709 --> 01:32:29,836
<font color="#6088d2">[BARKING]</font>

1171
01:32:34,299 --> 01:32:37,677
- What are you doing?
- There's gotta be medicine on that ship.

1172
01:32:37,761 --> 01:32:40,430
I thought you said
it was too dangerous to go outside.

1173
01:32:40,513 --> 01:32:42,891
I know I did.

1174
01:32:48,813 --> 01:32:50,482
Where'd you find
those chairs?

1175
01:32:51,858 --> 01:32:53,860
Why?

1176
01:32:54,944 --> 01:32:56,696
I'm going with you.

1177
01:32:57,781 --> 01:32:59,657
Me too.

1178
01:33:11,753 --> 01:33:13,755
<font color="#6088d2">[GASPS]</font>

1179
01:33:58,508 --> 01:34:01,094
There!

1180
01:34:01,177 --> 01:34:03,763
- <font color="#6088d2">[LOCK RATTLING]</font>
- Ohh! Come on!

1181
01:34:03,847 --> 01:34:05,932
<i>Damn it!</i>

1182
01:34:06,015 --> 01:34:08,518
- <font color="#6088d2">[GRUNTS LOUDLY]</font>
- <font color="#6088d2">[GROWLING]</font>

1183
01:34:12,939 --> 01:34:16,568
<i><font color="#6088d2">[GRUNTING CONTINUES]</font></i>

1184
01:34:38,047 --> 01:34:40,091
<font color="#6088d2">[YELLS]</font>

1185
01:34:43,178 --> 01:34:45,680
<font color="#6088d2">[PANTING]</font>

1186
01:34:53,605 --> 01:34:56,191
- It's all in Russian. I...
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">SAM:</font> I know.</i>

1187
01:34:56,274 --> 01:34:59,819
- H-H-Hey, guys, I found it.
- What? How do you know?

1188
01:34:59,903 --> 01:35:02,614
Because it says "penicillin"
on the bottom.

1189
01:35:02,697 --> 01:35:05,200
<font color="#6088d2">[GROWLING]</font>

1190
01:35:07,785 --> 01:35:11,623
<i>Wait. This is the mess hall. We should
find some food while we're here.</i>

1191
01:35:11,706 --> 01:35:15,835
- We don't have time.
- None of us are gonna survive
without food, including Laura.

1192
01:35:16,961 --> 01:35:18,963
Okay.

1193
01:35:20,632 --> 01:35:22,592
<font color="#6088d2">[EXHALES, CLEARS THROAT]</font>

1194
01:35:22,675 --> 01:35:24,761
<font color="#bce4f3">J.D.:</font>
Sam, over here!

1195
01:35:24,844 --> 01:35:26,763
What?

1196
01:35:26,846 --> 01:35:29,015
- Bingo.
- <font color="#6088d2">[LAUGHS]</font>

1197
01:35:29,098 --> 01:35:31,059
<i><font color="#6088d2">[SAM LAUGHS]</font></i>

1198
01:35:31,142 --> 01:35:33,144
<i><font color="#6088d2">[GLASS CLATTERING]</font></i>

1199
01:35:35,939 --> 01:35:39,359
- <font color="#6088d2">[INFLATING LOUDLY]</font>
- <font color="#6088d2">[YELLING]</font>

1200
01:35:39,442 --> 01:35:41,611
<i><font color="#bce4f3">SAM:</font>
Brian?</i>

1201
01:35:41,694 --> 01:35:44,364
<i>- <font color="#bce4f3">BRIAN:</font> I'm okay.
- <font color="#bce4f3">J.D.:</font> I What happened?</i>

1202
01:35:44,447 --> 01:35:47,825
Okay, okay. All I did
was open up a cupboard.

1203
01:35:47,909 --> 01:35:51,162
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[QUIET SNARLING]</font></i>
- We can use it. Put food in it.

1204
01:35:51,246 --> 01:35:53,039
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[LOUD SNARL]</font></i>
- <font color="#6088d2">[GASPS]</font>

1205
01:35:53,122 --> 01:35:56,167
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[GROWLING]</font></i>
- <font color="#6088d2">[PANICKED YELLING]</font>

1206
01:35:59,462 --> 01:36:02,674
- <font color="#6088d2">[CONTINUES YELLING]</font>
- <font color="#6088d2">[GRUNTING]</font>

1207
01:36:03,716 --> 01:36:06,302
- Pull him in!
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[WOLF WHIMPERS]</font></i>

1208
01:36:06,386 --> 01:36:09,430
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[WHIMPERING, GROWLING]</font></i>
- You all right?

1209
01:36:13,685 --> 01:36:15,687
<i><font color="#6088d2">[J.D. GROANS]</font>
My leg.</i>

1210
01:36:19,148 --> 01:36:20,483
<i>Here, use this.</i>

1211
01:36:20,566 --> 01:36:24,070
<font color="#6088d2">[SHUDDERING, GROANING]</font>
Oh, yeah. Here. Ohh!

1212
01:36:28,908 --> 01:36:31,327
It should be
over New York by now.

1213
01:36:31,411 --> 01:36:36,416
Satellite readings are showing
a temperature drop of 10 degrees per second.

1214
01:36:52,223 --> 01:36:55,935
<i><font color="#bce4f3">SAM:</font>
You guys, I think we're in the eye of it.</i>

1215
01:36:56,019 --> 01:36:58,896
We gotta get back right now.

1216
01:37:00,231 --> 01:37:02,066
Look,
I'm gonna go outside...

1217
01:37:02,150 --> 01:37:05,153
and I'm gonna lure the wolves
out of the room.

1218
01:37:05,236 --> 01:37:08,740
<i>- When they leave, you lock the door.</i>
- Good luck.

1219
01:37:39,771 --> 01:37:41,522
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[CRUNCH]</font></i>
- <font color="#6088d2">[GROWLING]</font>

1220
01:37:43,858 --> 01:37:46,361
<font color="#6088d2">[YELLING]</font>

1221
01:37:46,444 --> 01:37:49,322
Aah!
<font color="#6088d2">[GASPS]</font>

1222
01:37:49,405 --> 01:37:52,116
<font color="#6088d2">[MUTTERING, GRUNTING]</font>

1223
01:37:54,118 --> 01:37:56,287
<font color="#6088d2">[GROWLING, SNARLING]</font>

1224
01:37:57,872 --> 01:38:00,666
Aah!
<font color="#6088d2">[PANTING, GASPING]</font>

1225
01:38:06,422 --> 01:38:09,384
<i>- <font color="#6088d2">[WOLF WHIMPERS]</font></i>
- <font color="#6088d2">[PANTING]</font>

1226
01:38:12,720 --> 01:38:16,057
<font color="#6088d2">[GROANS]</font>
Brian, hurry!

1227
