Anything I'm forgetting, honey?

1240
01:19:43,140 --> 01:19:44,090
Honey?

1241
01:19:44,780 --> 01:19:45,650
Guilty.

1242
01:19:45,900 --> 01:19:47,690
It took years
for Dekkom to plan this, sir.

1243
01:19:47,780 --> 01:19:49,650
A president's schedule
always changes last minute.

1244
01:19:49,740 --> 01:19:51,970
This is the one day and date
he could be sure wouldn't move.

1245
01:19:52,060 --> 01:19:53,090
Having my brother and I

1246
01:19:53,180 --> 01:19:55,330
lead the investigation
was a setup from the start.

1247
01:19:55,620 --> 01:19:56,570
Think about it.

1248
01:19:56,900 --> 01:19:58,330
He hired us to fail.

1249
01:20:00,300 --> 01:20:00,930
Get down!

1250
01:20:48,660 --> 01:20:50,090
All right, it's saying
we're back in the clear,

1251
01:20:50,340 --> 01:20:51,330
<i>where the four meets the 91!</i>

1252
01:20:55,620 --> 01:20:57,170
Just gotta take care
of a little problem first.

1253
01:21:11,300 --> 01:21:12,620
Hold on!

1254
01:21:13,660 --> 01:21:14,730
No!

1255
01:21:20,340 --> 01:21:21,290
Marry her.

1256
01:21:59,180 --> 01:22:00,290
No. We're fine here.

1257
01:22:00,380 --> 01:22:01,570
<i>A lightning storm in Orlando</i>

1258
01:22:01,660 --> 01:22:03,970
<i>has caused a horrific explosion
at the DNC.</i>

1259
01:22:05,100 --> 01:22:07,770
<i>There is no official word
on the whereabouts of the president...</i>

1260
01:22:08,140 --> 01:22:09,890
I don't know. I don't know.

1261
01:22:11,020 --> 01:22:13,210
I just can't get in touch
with Jake.

1262
01:22:13,540 --> 01:22:16,450
<i>And we have reports now of explosions
on the space station.</i>

1263
01:22:16,780 --> 01:22:20,090
Honey, the Orlando storm is getting
really close to your dad's place.

1264
01:22:20,380 --> 01:22:23,890
I can't get through to him.
Has he texted you?

1265
01:22:24,100 --> 01:22:25,130
He's not there.

1266
01:22:27,180 --> 01:22:28,050
He's there.

1267
01:22:29,940 --> 01:22:32,250
<i>Of a major issue on the space station.</i>

1268
01:22:37,260 --> 01:22:41,170
<i>Attention all crews.
Now loading final shuttle.</i>

1269
01:22:47,140 --> 01:22:51,290
<i>Please board your designated
evacuation shuttles immediately.</i>

1270
01:22:51,500 --> 01:22:54,250
<i>Shuttle launch sequence initiated.</i>

1271
01:22:54,740 --> 01:22:56,090
Jake.

1272
01:22:56,620 --> 01:22:58,410
- I'm not coming.
- What?

1273
01:22:58,780 --> 01:23:00,850
When my brother gets those kill codes,

1274
01:23:01,100 --> 01:23:02,370
someone has to be here
to execute the program.

1275
01:23:02,460 --> 01:23:03,810
No. We need to go.

1276
01:23:03,900 --> 01:23:05,300
We haven't heard from him in hours.

1277
01:23:05,580 --> 01:23:06,610
I trust him.

1278
01:23:06,940 --> 01:23:09,450
You know the reboot
has to be done manually.

1279
01:23:09,820 --> 01:23:10,930
Then I stay. I'm the commander.

1280
01:23:11,180 --> 01:23:12,210
No.

1281
01:23:13,180 --> 01:23:15,610
I'm the only one my brother
will trust with the codes,

1282
01:23:16,820 --> 01:23:18,040
so I need your HoloFrame.

1283
01:23:23,100 --> 01:23:25,290
You have to insert it manually
at the core of the mainframe.

1284
01:23:27,380 --> 01:23:28,450
You can find it, yes?

1285
01:23:29,300 --> 01:23:30,290
- Yes.
- Good.

1286
01:23:34,300 --> 01:23:35,290
Goodbye, Ute.

1287
01:23:37,180 --> 01:23:39,050
<i>Auf Wiedersehen,</i> Jake.

1288
01:23:48,700 --> 01:23:49,770
<i>Pull over here.</i>

1289
01:23:50,260 --> 01:23:52,570
The president's beacon shows him
heading right towards us.

1290
01:23:57,180 --> 01:23:58,690
You really wanna drive back into that?

1291
01:23:59,100 --> 01:24:03,170
Yeah, right after it passes,
I'll be the sole survivor,

1292
01:24:03,580 --> 01:24:06,930
ready to be sworn in as
the next President of the United States.

1293
01:24:18,220 --> 01:24:19,540
Here they come.

1294
01:24:26,420 --> 01:24:27,170
Fire.

1295
01:24:54,540 --> 01:24:57,100
You thought the president was the only
one who could be tracked?

1296
01:25:06,180 --> 01:25:07,660
- How in hell did you--
- How?

1297
01:25:08,500 --> 01:25:11,610
Because I'm the goddamn President
of the United States of America.

1298
01:25:11,860 --> 01:25:13,490
You're done, Leonard.

1299
01:25:19,620 --> 01:25:20,650
He's all yours.

1300
01:25:26,060 --> 01:25:27,050
Wait, wait! Wait a minute.

1301
01:25:27,420 --> 01:25:29,410
I've given you an opportunity,
Mr. President.

1302
01:25:29,700 --> 01:25:31,100
You should take it.

1303
01:25:31,380 --> 01:25:33,770
An opportunity? Let him go!

1304
01:25:34,060 --> 01:25:34,970
It's genocide, Leonard!

1305
01:25:35,260 --> 01:25:37,980
You say genocide,
I say preemptive strike.

1306
01:25:38,220 --> 01:25:39,410
You've lost your mind!

1307
01:25:39,700 --> 01:25:42,420
Tomorrow the sun will rise.
All our enemies will be gone.

1308
01:25:43,140 --> 01:25:45,330
Wiped away as if by the hand of God.

1309
01:25:47,300 --> 01:25:48,650
Why would you do this?

1310
01:25:48,940 --> 01:25:50,690
Because no one else would.

1311
01:25:50,980 --> 01:25:52,890
I'm turning the clock back to 1945,

1312
01:25:53,140 --> 01:25:57,450
when America was a shining city on a
hill, not a bank disguised as a country.

1313
01:25:57,700 --> 01:25:58,970
By playing God?

1314
01:25:59,260 --> 01:26:01,650
What the hell is Dutch Boy
if not playing God?

1315
01:26:02,060 --> 01:26:03,570
Ask Max. He knows.

1316
01:26:03,820 --> 01:26:05,610
Science is all about playing God.

1317
01:26:05,940 --> 01:26:08,130
Sometimes God doesn't play so nice.

1318
01:26:08,940 --> 01:26:10,850
Yeah, well,
you know what my brother would say?

1319
01:26:11,100 --> 01:26:11,890
What?

1320
01:26:19,060 --> 01:26:20,210
Get him outta here!

1321
01:26:22,620 --> 01:26:23,570
Let's go, Lawson!

1322
01:26:25,940 --> 01:26:27,730
That's my fiancé.

1323
01:27:23,740 --> 01:27:25,690
Get the president to cover! Hurry!

1324
01:27:33,420 --> 01:27:34,970
Mr. President.

1325
01:27:35,260 --> 01:27:36,090
We got the kill codes.

1326
01:27:36,340 --> 01:27:38,250
You'll have to hurry.
The station is in full shutdown.

1327
01:27:38,500 --> 01:27:39,530
What about the crew?

1328
01:27:39,940 --> 01:27:40,730
Safe.

1329
01:27:40,860 --> 01:27:42,810
But Jake decided to stay.

1330
01:27:43,100 --> 01:27:45,050
To reboot the satellites.

1331
01:27:46,260 --> 01:27:47,610
Your brother is waiting for you.

1332
01:27:49,140 --> 01:27:50,730
Come on.

1333
01:27:53,620 --> 01:27:55,020
<i>Virtual conference initiating.</i>

1334
01:27:55,100 --> 01:27:56,290
Hey.

1335
01:27:58,780 --> 01:27:59,610
<i>Jake.</i>

1336
01:28:00,420 --> 01:28:01,490
<i>Jake, it was Dekkom.</i>

1337
01:28:02,580 --> 01:28:04,410
Well, I did say I might be wrong.

1338
01:28:05,140 --> 01:28:06,210
<i>Mr. President.</i>

1339
01:28:08,300 --> 01:28:09,130
How's Hannah?

1340
01:28:09,380 --> 01:28:10,410
Oh, she's good. She's safe.

1341
01:28:10,700 --> 01:28:11,920
<i>Atlanta wasn't hit.</i>

1342
01:28:12,700 --> 01:28:13,610
<i>Thank God.</i>

1343
01:28:15,180 --> 01:28:18,050
<i>Identity verified.
Shutdown protocol transfer initiating.</i>

1344
01:28:18,420 --> 01:28:19,850
It's gonna take 60 seconds to upload.

1345
01:28:20,500 --> 01:28:21,690
How long till the self-destruct?

1346
01:28:22,300 --> 01:28:23,130
Eight minutes,

1347
01:28:23,820 --> 01:28:24,610
give or take.

1348
01:28:24,980 --> 01:28:25,850
<i>Mr. Lawson,</i>

1349
01:28:26,900 --> 01:28:29,090
<i>we thank you for your sacrifice.</i>

1350
01:28:36,060 --> 01:28:37,690
<i>Wait. What the hell's going on?</i>

1351
01:28:37,980 --> 01:28:39,330
You've done your part, Max.

1352
01:28:39,660 --> 01:28:40,810
Jake, what is going on?

1353
01:28:41,140 --> 01:28:42,410
Now it's time for me to do mine.

1354
01:28:44,980 --> 01:28:46,170
No, no, no.

1355
01:28:46,700 --> 01:28:48,850
The kill codes don't stop
the self-destruct, do they?

1356
01:28:50,660 --> 01:28:51,490
Do they?

1357
01:28:52,860 --> 01:28:53,690
No,

1358
01:28:54,220 --> 01:28:55,290
only the geostorm.

1359
01:28:55,660 --> 01:28:58,090
The station self-destruct
can't be reversed.

1360
01:28:59,620 --> 01:29:02,180
Come on, come on.
There must be a way, huh?

1361
01:29:02,900 --> 01:29:05,210
Come on. It's all my fault.
I'm the one who put you up there!

1362
01:29:05,300 --> 01:29:06,330
Hey, it's okay.

1363
01:29:08,060 --> 01:29:10,250
I wanted to go. It was my choice.

1364
01:29:12,220 --> 01:29:13,970
God knows,

1365
01:29:14,300 --> 01:29:15,970
I haven't always made the right ones.

1366
01:29:18,740 --> 01:29:20,330
You know, you were right,
little brother.

1367
01:29:23,420 --> 01:29:25,210
I was supposed to look after you.

1368
01:29:28,580 --> 01:29:30,130
But you looked after me.

1369
01:29:34,780 --> 01:29:35,890
Can you forgive me?

1370
01:29:37,100 --> 01:29:38,320
Yeah, always.

1371
01:29:40,820 --> 01:29:42,170
Look after my little girl.

1372
01:29:44,100 --> 01:29:45,500
Stay in her life.

1373
01:29:46,340 --> 01:29:47,330
I will.

1374
01:29:50,700 --> 01:29:52,330
We should've done this
a long time ago, huh?

1375
01:29:53,100 --> 01:29:53,890
Yeah.

1376
01:29:55,780 --> 01:29:57,000
You're a good man, Jake.

1377
01:29:58,580 --> 01:29:59,650
I'll see you, kiddo.

1378
01:30:01,860 --> 01:30:03,010
<i>Transfer complete.</i>

1379
01:30:09,860 --> 01:30:13,900
<i>Time to geostorm: 5 minutes, 51 seconds.</i>

1380
01:30:36,940 --> 01:30:39,370
<i>Warning. Core rotation has terminated.</i>

1381
01:30:42,580 --> 01:30:44,570
<i>We don't know
what's happening up there.</i>

1382
01:30:44,940 --> 01:30:48,770
<i>We just know the station has suffered
a devastating accident of some kind.</i>

1383
01:30:49,340 --> 01:30:52,330
<i>We're being told now
it is beyond repair or salvation.</i>

1384
01:30:53,580 --> 01:30:54,370
Honey.

1385
01:30:54,820 --> 01:30:55,970
He's coming back.

1386
01:30:57,420 --> 01:30:58,410
He promised me.

1387
01:30:58,780 --> 01:31:01,530
<i>We will keep you updated
with any new developments.</i>

1388
01:31:22,660 --> 01:31:25,650
<i>Self-destruct entering phase four.</i>

1389
01:31:40,380 --> 01:31:42,330
<i>Code invalid.</i>

1390
01:31:45,820 --> 01:31:46,890
<i>Code invalid.</i>

1391
01:31:48,380 --> 01:31:49,290
<i>Need a hand?</i>

1392
01:31:54,380 --> 01:31:55,370
<i>Wrong door.</i>

1393
01:32:00,100 --> 01:32:01,010
<i>What're you doing here?</i>

1394
01:32:01,700 --> 01:32:03,530
<i>I told you. I live here.</i>

1395
01:32:16,340 --> 01:32:19,410
<i>Time to geostorm: 1 minute, 40 seconds.</i>

1396
01:32:33,220 --> 01:32:34,850
<i>Uploading kill codes.</i>

1397
01:32:51,740 --> 01:32:54,050
<i>Satellite shutdown in process.</i>

1398
01:32:57,740 --> 01:33:00,570
<i>When the last satellite
cycles down, let me know.</i>

1399
01:33:01,220 --> 01:33:03,780
<i>I'll manually reboot the entire system.</i>

1400
01:33:03,940 --> 01:33:06,850
<i>- That should flush out the virus.
- Okay.</i>

1401
01:33:29,660 --> 01:33:30,650
<i>Five to go.</i>

1402
01:33:36,540 --> 01:33:37,330
<i>Three.</i>

1403
01:33:37,620 --> 01:33:38,970
<i>- Come on, baby.
- Two.</i>

1404
01:33:41,060 --> 01:33:42,610
<i>And one.</i>

1405
01:33:44,700 --> 01:33:47,090
<i>Manual reboot activated.</i>

1406
01:34:08,460 --> 01:34:09,890
<i>Status: rebooting.</i>

1407
01:34:10,460 --> 01:34:12,730
<i>The net is back up.
The virus is gone.</i>

1408
01:34:13,780 --> 01:34:17,170
<i>Transferring control of the net
back to NASA.</i>

1409
01:34:30,860 --> 01:34:31,610
<i>Jake!</i>

1410
01:34:40,900 --> 01:34:41,850
<i>I've got you!</i>

1411
01:34:42,460 --> 01:34:46,010
<i>Warning.
Self-destruct entering final stage.</i>

1412
01:34:54,660 --> 01:34:55,690
<i>Best seat in the house.</i>

1413
01:35:06,300 --> 01:35:07,090
<i>Ute,</i>

1414
01:35:09,900 --> 01:35:11,250
<i>do you believe in a Hail Mary?</i>

1415
01:35:13,420 --> 01:35:15,730
<i>Follow me. We gotta get
to the satellite.</i>

1416
01:35:55,140 --> 01:35:56,290
<i>I've got you.</i>

1417
01:36:01,740 --> 01:36:04,730
<i>We've gotta get away as far as we can
before the final detonation.</i>

1418
01:36:06,260 --> 01:36:07,170
<i>Dock releasing.</i>

1419
01:36:47,220 --> 01:36:50,290
<i>And it appears
we have lost the space station.</i>

1420
01:36:50,700 --> 01:36:53,730
<i>A tragic ending
for the two heroes still aboard.</i>

1421
01:37:09,100 --> 01:37:10,290
<i>Hey, Max, take a look.</i>

1422
01:37:13,620 --> 01:37:15,690
I'm picking up exhaust flares,

1423
01:37:16,060 --> 01:37:19,250
<i>and they're pulsing in a Mayday pattern.</i>

1424
01:37:27,900 --> 01:37:29,930
See if we can turn
one of the shuttles around.

1425
01:37:39,980 --> 01:37:42,050
<i>Hopefully, someone sees this.</i>

1426
01:37:45,980 --> 01:37:47,380
<i>Fingers crossed.</i>

1427
01:38:20,540 --> 01:38:22,610
<i>Hernandez, you son of a bitch!</i>

1428
01:38:23,380 --> 01:38:24,410
<i>Thank the Mexican.</i>

1429
01:38:42,580 --> 01:38:44,970
Yes! Come here. Yes!

1430
01:39:17,460 --> 01:39:18,940
<i>A miracle indeed.</i>

1431
01:39:19,660 --> 01:39:23,170
<i>The shuttle you see is bringing home
all the ISS crew members</i>

1432
01:39:23,300 --> 01:39:24,810
<i>who remained on the station.</i>

1433
01:39:39,540 --> 01:39:43,010
Hi, Jake. I'm Sarah, Max's fiancée.

1434
01:39:43,740 --> 01:39:45,170
Oh, welcome to the family.

1435
01:39:45,500 --> 01:39:47,610
Well done, well done, both of you.

1436
01:39:48,700 --> 01:39:50,250
Sorry I doubted you, Mr. President.

1437
01:39:50,500 --> 01:39:53,220
Yeah, well, you were wrong, Jake, again.

1438
01:39:53,300 --> 01:39:55,610
Well, how many times
do I have to tell you?

1439
01:39:56,140 --> 01:39:57,130
Never listen to me.

1440
01:40:05,940 --> 01:40:07,450
God, it's good to have you back, man.

1441
01:40:07,780 --> 01:40:08,930
Good to be back.

1442
01:40:34,860 --> 01:40:36,690
It's a nice place
you got here, Jake.

1443
01:40:37,700 --> 01:40:38,570
Thank you.

1444
01:40:40,140 --> 01:40:41,620
So when you heading back up?

1445
01:40:42,820 --> 01:40:44,040
- In a week.
- Yeah?

1446
01:40:44,660 --> 01:40:46,140
Yeah, a lot of work left.

1447
01:40:47,300 --> 01:40:48,890
But I'll be back.

1448
01:40:50,700 --> 01:40:51,850
I know.

1449
01:41:02,100 --> 01:41:03,810
- This sucks.
- Yeah, seriously, this is so boring.

1450
01:41:03,940 --> 01:41:05,930
You know what?
I can't do this for another second.

1451
01:41:06,580 --> 01:41:07,850
Now, why'd you make us do this
in the first place?

1452
01:41:08,100 --> 01:41:09,850
I don't know.
I was trying to relive a moment.

1453
01:41:10,100 --> 01:41:11,690
A moment? What moment?

1454
01:41:11,940 --> 01:41:14,730
We never went fishing with Dad.
You made that whole story up.

1455
01:41:15,020 --> 01:41:16,570
Yeah, but that was a good story,
though, huh?

1456
01:41:16,940 --> 01:41:18,160
I mean, you gotta give me that.

1457
01:41:18,380 --> 01:41:20,050
I mean, it had a moral and everything.

1458
01:41:20,140 --> 01:41:22,050
Moral? What moral?

1459
01:41:26,300 --> 01:41:27,730
<i>You can't undo the past.</i>

1460
01:41:28,020 --> 01:41:29,930
<i>All you can do is face what's ahead.</i>

1461
01:41:30,820 --> 01:41:34,010
<i>NASA maintained the satellites
while we rebuilt the space station.</i>

1462
01:41:34,820 --> 01:41:39,330
<i>We made it safer, made it stronger.
It belongs to all of us now.</i>

1463
01:41:39,940 --> 01:41:41,850
<i>One planet, one people.</i>

1464
01:41:42,900 --> 01:41:47,850
<i>And as long as we remember that
we share one future, we will survive.</i>


1
00:01:15,105 --> 00:01:16,774
OLD WOMAN:
Well, my dad was a farmer.

2
00:01:18,209 --> 00:01:20,511
Um... Like everybody else
back then.

3
00:01:22,812 --> 00:01:24,715
Of course,
he didn't start that way.

4
00:01:30,788 --> 00:01:32,548
MAN ON RADIO: Computer
says you're too tight.

5
00:01:32,723 --> 00:01:34,358
Nah, I got this.

6
00:01:34,391 --> 00:01:35,593
Crossing the Straits.

7
00:01:38,195 --> 00:01:39,863
- Shutting it down, Cooper.
- Whoa!

8
00:01:39,897 --> 00:01:41,298
(POWERING DOWN)

9
00:01:41,331 --> 00:01:42,700
Shutting it all down.

10
00:01:42,733 --> 00:01:43,768
No, I need power up!

11
00:01:46,604 --> 00:01:48,148
- FEMALE COMPUTER VOICE: Eject!
- (COOPER SCREAMING)

12
00:01:48,172 --> 00:01:49,372
YOUNG MURPH: Dad?

13
00:01:55,813 --> 00:01:58,515
Sorry, Murph.
Go back to bed, babe.

14
00:01:58,548 --> 00:01:59,817
I thought you were the ghost.

15
00:01:59,850 --> 00:02:00,851
No.

16
00:02:02,853 --> 00:02:05,155
There are no such things
as ghosts, babe.

17
00:02:05,189 --> 00:02:06,857
Grandpa says you can get ghosts.

18
00:02:08,825 --> 00:02:10,636
Yeah, maybe that's 'cause
Grandpa's a little too close

19
00:02:10,660 --> 00:02:13,630
to being one himself.
Back to bed.

20
00:02:13,663 --> 00:02:15,332
Were you dreaming
about the crash?

21
00:02:16,934 --> 00:02:18,903
Get your butt back in bed,
Murph. (LAUGHS)

22
00:02:46,262 --> 00:02:47,531
OLD MURPH: The wheat had died.

23
00:02:48,632 --> 00:02:50,668
The blight came
and we had to burn it.

24
00:02:51,802 --> 00:02:54,638
And we still had corn.
We had acres of corn.

25
00:02:54,672 --> 00:02:56,607
But, uh, mostly we had dust.

26
00:02:59,610 --> 00:03:00,653
OLD WOMAN 1:
I guess I can't describe it.

27
00:03:00,677 --> 00:03:02,112
It was just constant.

28
00:03:02,146 --> 00:03:04,414
Just that steady blow

29
00:03:04,448 --> 00:03:05,816
of dirt.

30
00:03:08,352 --> 00:03:11,454
OLD WOMAN 2: We wore
little strips of sheet

31
00:03:11,488 --> 00:03:14,358
sometimes over
our nose and mouth

32
00:03:14,391 --> 00:03:16,560
so that we wouldn't breathe
so much of it.

33
00:03:18,495 --> 00:03:19,539
OLD MAN: Well,
when we set the table,

34
00:03:19,563 --> 00:03:20,897
we always set the plate

35
00:03:20,931 --> 00:03:22,198
upside-down.

36
00:03:22,232 --> 00:03:24,034
Glasses or cups,
whatever it was,

37
00:03:24,068 --> 00:03:25,102
upside-down.

38
00:03:30,707 --> 00:03:33,443
Shake a leg!
Murph, get a move on!

39
00:03:33,477 --> 00:03:35,054
COOPER: Tom, 4:00 today,
you and me in the barn,

40
00:03:35,078 --> 00:03:36,847
Herbicide Resistance 101.

41
00:03:36,880 --> 00:03:38,582
- Check?
- Yes, sir.

42
00:03:38,615 --> 00:03:39,893
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER ON RADIO)
- (DONALD HUMMING)

43
00:03:39,917 --> 00:03:41,185
Not at the table, Murph.

44
00:03:42,219 --> 00:03:43,854
Dad, can you fix this?

45
00:03:45,789 --> 00:03:47,033
COOPER: What the heck
did you do to my lander?

46
00:03:47,057 --> 00:03:48,425
Wasn't me.

47
00:03:48,459 --> 00:03:50,492
Let me guess.
It was your ghost?

48
00:03:50,527 --> 00:03:51,694
It knocked it off my shelf.

49
00:03:51,728 --> 00:03:53,263
It keeps on knocking books off.

50
00:03:53,296 --> 00:03:54,574
TOM: No such thing as ghosts,
dumb-ass.

51
00:03:54,598 --> 00:03:55,733
- Hey.
- I looked it up.

52
00:03:55,766 --> 00:03:57,034
It's called a poltergeist.

53
00:03:57,067 --> 00:03:58,434
Dad, tell her.

54
00:03:58,469 --> 00:04:00,737
Well, it's not
very scientific, Murph.

55
00:04:00,771 --> 00:04:03,273
You said science was about
admitting what we don't know.

56
00:04:03,306 --> 00:04:04,746
- She's got you there.
- COOPER: Hey.

57
00:04:05,275 --> 00:04:06,710
Start looking after our stuff.

58
00:04:08,245 --> 00:04:09,546
Coop.

59
00:04:12,716 --> 00:04:14,517
All right, Murph,
you want to talk science?

60
00:04:15,819 --> 00:04:17,596
Don't just tell me that
you're afraid of some ghost.

61
00:04:17,620 --> 00:04:19,255
No, you got to go further.

62
00:04:19,289 --> 00:04:20,700
You got to record
the facts, analyze,

63
00:04:20,724 --> 00:04:22,392
get to the how and the why,

64
00:04:22,426 --> 00:04:25,029
then present your conclusions.
Deal?

65
00:04:26,063 --> 00:04:27,097
- Deal.
- All right.

66
00:04:30,200 --> 00:04:31,244
Y'all have a good day at school.

67
00:04:31,268 --> 00:04:32,736
DONALD: Hold up.

68
00:04:32,770 --> 00:04:35,238
Parent-teacher conferences.
Parent.

69
00:04:35,272 --> 00:04:36,841
Not grandparent.

70
00:04:37,340 --> 00:04:38,576
(HONKING HORN)

71
00:04:39,309 --> 00:04:40,977
Slow down, turbo!

72
00:04:42,546 --> 00:04:44,314
That's not a dust storm.

73
00:04:44,348 --> 00:04:45,628
Nelson's torching
his whole crop.

74
00:04:45,882 --> 00:04:47,451
Blight?

75
00:04:47,485 --> 00:04:49,553
They're saying it's
the last harvest for okra.

76
00:04:50,254 --> 00:04:51,489
Ever.

77
00:04:53,757 --> 00:04:56,526
He should've planted corn
like the rest of us.

78
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:57,904
Now, you be nice
to that Ms. Hanley.

79
00:04:57,928 --> 00:04:59,296
She's single.

80
00:04:59,329 --> 00:05:00,965
What's that supposed to mean?

81
00:05:00,998 --> 00:05:02,365
Repopulating the Earth.

82
00:05:02,399 --> 00:05:04,535
Start pulling your weight,
young man.

83
00:05:04,568 --> 00:05:06,804
Well, why don't you start
minding your own business,

84
00:05:06,837 --> 00:05:07,905
old man.

85
00:05:15,579 --> 00:05:16,914
All right, Murph,
give me second.

86
00:05:18,949 --> 00:05:19,950
Uh-huh.

87
00:05:20,417 --> 00:05:21,751
Third.

88
00:05:22,253 --> 00:05:23,553
(GEARS GRINDING)

89
00:05:23,587 --> 00:05:25,322
- Find a gear, dumb-ass.
- Grind it!

90
00:05:25,355 --> 00:05:26,422
Shut it, Tom!

91
00:05:26,456 --> 00:05:27,590
(TIRE HISSING)

92
00:05:27,624 --> 00:05:28,792
What'd you do, Murph?

93
00:05:28,825 --> 00:05:30,160
Aw, she didn't do nothin'.

94
00:05:30,193 --> 00:05:31,428
Blew a tire is all.

95
00:05:31,462 --> 00:05:32,663
Murphy's Law.

96
00:05:33,396 --> 00:05:34,564
Shut up!

97
00:05:34,597 --> 00:05:35,900
Grab the spare, Tom.

98
00:05:35,933 --> 00:05:36,967
That is the spare.

99
00:05:39,469 --> 00:05:40,771
COOPER: Get the patch kit!

100
00:05:42,472 --> 00:05:44,208
TOM: How am I supposed
to patch it out here?

101
00:05:44,241 --> 00:05:45,709
COOPER:
You got to figure it out.

102
00:05:45,743 --> 00:05:47,343
I'm not always gonna be here
to help you.

103
00:05:55,852 --> 00:05:58,188
What's going on, Murph?

104
00:05:58,222 --> 00:06:01,258
Why did you and Mom name me
after something that's bad?

105
00:06:01,291 --> 00:06:02,560
Well, we didn't.

106
00:06:03,027 --> 00:06:04,261
Murphy's Law?

107
00:06:05,795 --> 00:06:10,000
Murphy's Law doesn't mean that
something bad will happen.

108
00:06:10,033 --> 00:06:13,570
What it means is whatever
can happen will happen.

109
00:06:13,603 --> 00:06:15,673
And that sounded
just fine with us.

110
00:06:20,077 --> 00:06:21,078
Whoa!

111
00:06:22,045 --> 00:06:23,180
Get in.

112
00:06:24,714 --> 00:06:26,050
Get in, let's go.

113
00:06:27,550 --> 00:06:28,686
What about the flat tire?

114
00:06:28,719 --> 00:06:29,920
(ENGINE STARTING)

115
00:06:32,456 --> 00:06:33,823
Yeah.

116
00:06:47,904 --> 00:06:49,473
It's an Indian Air Force drone.

117
00:06:49,506 --> 00:06:52,142
Solar cells could power
an entire farm.

118
00:06:52,175 --> 00:06:53,310
Take the wheel, Tom.

119
00:06:59,116 --> 00:07:00,951
Go, go, go!

120
00:07:02,219 --> 00:07:03,621
Keep that aimed right at it.

121
00:07:11,695 --> 00:07:13,897
Faster, Tom. I'm losing it.

122
00:07:14,598 --> 00:07:15,833
Right at it.

123
00:07:17,401 --> 00:07:18,402
Stay on it.

124
00:07:20,203 --> 00:07:21,205
Here we go. Here we go.

125
00:07:23,507 --> 00:07:24,708
Whoa!

126
00:07:30,146 --> 00:07:31,649
Nice one, Tom.

127
00:07:38,121 --> 00:07:40,057
Dad?

128
00:07:40,090 --> 00:07:42,426
I almost got it.
Don't stop. Don't stop!

129
00:07:43,126 --> 00:07:44,128
Dad!

130
00:07:44,427 --> 00:07:45,662
Tom!

131
00:07:50,567 --> 00:07:52,369
Why? You told me
to keep driving.

132
00:07:53,670 --> 00:07:55,238
Well, I guess that
answers the old,

133
00:07:55,271 --> 00:07:57,775
"If I asked you to
drive off a cliff" scenario.

134
00:08:01,144 --> 00:08:02,479
We lost it.

135
00:08:02,513 --> 00:08:03,814
No, we didn't.

136
00:08:16,693 --> 00:08:18,128
Want to give it a whirl?

137
00:08:24,100 --> 00:08:25,703
This...

138
00:08:31,140 --> 00:08:32,142
Go.

139
00:08:33,443 --> 00:08:36,080
Let's lay her down
right there at the edge
of the reservoir.

140
00:08:40,484 --> 00:08:42,085
Nicely done.

141
00:08:45,321 --> 00:08:47,356
TOM: How long you think
it's been up there?

142
00:08:47,390 --> 00:08:49,893
Delhi Mission Control
went down, same as ours,

143
00:08:49,926 --> 00:08:51,261
- 10 years ago.
- Oh!

144
00:08:52,229 --> 00:08:53,964
So for 10 years?

145
00:08:57,401 --> 00:08:58,445
Why did it come down so low?

146
00:08:58,469 --> 00:09:00,003
I don't know.

147
00:09:00,036 --> 00:09:01,571
Maybe the sun cooked its brain

148
00:09:01,605 --> 00:09:02,649
or it was looking for something.

149
00:09:02,673 --> 00:09:03,873
What?

150
00:09:03,906 --> 00:09:05,775
Give me a large flatblade.

151
00:09:05,809 --> 00:09:08,112
Maybe some kind of signal?
I don't know.

152
00:09:13,583 --> 00:09:14,885
What are you gonna do with it?

153
00:09:16,220 --> 00:09:19,122
I'm gonna give it something
socially responsible to do,

154
00:09:19,156 --> 00:09:21,091
(PANTING)
like drive a combine.

155
00:09:21,858 --> 00:09:23,193
Can't we just let it go?

156
00:09:25,662 --> 00:09:27,131
It wasn't hurting anybody.

157
00:09:29,098 --> 00:09:31,735
This thing needs to learn
how to adapt, Murph,

158
00:09:31,768 --> 00:09:33,137
like the rest of us.

159
00:09:38,208 --> 00:09:39,619
COOPER: So how's this work?
You guys come with?

160
00:09:39,643 --> 00:09:41,278
TOM: I've got class.

161
00:09:41,311 --> 00:09:43,313
This one needs to wait.

162
00:09:45,182 --> 00:09:46,349
What did you do?

163
00:09:46,382 --> 00:09:47,894
They'll tell you about it
when you get in there.

164
00:09:47,918 --> 00:09:49,185
Am I gonna be mad?

165
00:09:49,219 --> 00:09:50,420
Not with me.

166
00:09:50,453 --> 00:09:51,788
Just please try not to.

167
00:09:51,822 --> 00:09:53,322
Hey, relax.

168
00:09:54,858 --> 00:09:56,160
I got this.

169
00:10:00,530 --> 00:10:02,199
Little late, Coop.

170
00:10:02,232 --> 00:10:03,900
Yeah, we had a flat.

171
00:10:03,934 --> 00:10:05,568
And I guess you had to stop off

172
00:10:05,602 --> 00:10:07,704
at the Asian
fighter plane store.

173
00:10:07,738 --> 00:10:11,374
No, actually, sir, that's a...
That's a surveillance drone.

174
00:10:11,407 --> 00:10:13,911
With outstanding solar cells.
It's Indian.

175
00:10:14,478 --> 00:10:15,579
Take a seat.

176
00:10:16,813 --> 00:10:18,248
So, uh...

177
00:10:19,116 --> 00:10:22,318
We got Tom's scores back.

178
00:10:22,352 --> 00:10:24,888
He's going to make
an excellent farmer.

179
00:10:24,921 --> 00:10:28,224
Yeah, he's got
a knack for it.
What about college?

180
00:10:28,258 --> 00:10:30,694
Well, the university
only takes a handful.

181
00:10:30,727 --> 00:10:31,871
They don't really have
the resources to...

182
00:10:31,895 --> 00:10:34,297
I still pay my taxes.

183
00:10:34,330 --> 00:10:37,000
Where's that money go?
There's no more armies.

184
00:10:37,033 --> 00:10:40,003
Well, it doesn't go
to the university.

185
00:10:40,036 --> 00:10:41,871
Look, Coop,
you have to be realistic.

186
00:10:41,905 --> 00:10:44,274
You're ruling my son out
for college now?

187
00:10:44,875 --> 00:10:46,275
The kid's 15.

188
00:10:46,309 --> 00:10:48,312
Tom's score simply
isn't high enough.

189
00:10:49,713 --> 00:10:51,448
What's your waistline?
About 32?

190
00:10:51,948 --> 00:10:53,983
About a 33 inseam?

191
00:10:54,016 --> 00:10:55,885
I'm not sure I see
what you're getting at.

192
00:10:55,918 --> 00:10:56,996
You're telling me
it takes two numbers

193
00:10:57,020 --> 00:10:58,288
to measure your own ass,

194
00:10:58,321 --> 00:11:00,157
but only one to measure
my son's future?

195
00:11:00,691 --> 00:11:02,659
(SIGHS) Come on.

196
00:11:02,693 --> 00:11:04,594
You're a well-educated man,
Coop.

197
00:11:04,628 --> 00:11:05,863
And a trained pilot.

198
00:11:05,864 --> 00:11:07,097
And an engineer.

199
00:11:07,130 --> 00:11:12,302
Okay, well, right now
we don't need
more engineers.

200
00:11:12,335 --> 00:11:14,838
We didn't run out of
television screens
and planes.

201
00:11:14,871 --> 00:11:16,973
We ran out of food.

202
00:11:17,007 --> 00:11:20,077
The world needs farmers.
Good farmers, like you.

203
00:11:20,110 --> 00:11:21,378
And Tom.

204
00:11:21,411 --> 00:11:22,412
Uneducated farmers.

205
00:11:23,780 --> 00:11:25,748
We're a caretaker
generation, Coop.

206
00:11:25,781 --> 00:11:27,817
And things are getting better.

207
00:11:27,851 --> 00:11:29,429
Maybe your grandkids
will get to be engineers...

208
00:11:29,453 --> 00:11:30,520
Are we done here, sir?

209
00:11:32,088 --> 00:11:33,123
No.

210
00:11:34,057 --> 00:11:36,960
Ms. Hanley's here
to talk about Murph.

211
00:11:36,993 --> 00:11:39,495
MS. HANLEY: Murph is a great
kid. She's really bright.

212
00:11:39,529 --> 00:11:41,963
But she's been having
a little trouble lately.

213
00:11:41,998 --> 00:11:43,676
She brought this in
to show the other students.

214
00:11:43,700 --> 00:11:45,268
The section
on the lunar landings.

215
00:11:45,301 --> 00:11:48,204
Yeah, it's one
of my old textbooks.

216
00:11:48,237 --> 00:11:50,540
She always loved the pictures.

217
00:11:50,573 --> 00:11:51,975
It's an old federal textbook.

218
00:11:52,008 --> 00:11:54,210
We've replaced them
with the corrected versions.

219
00:11:54,243 --> 00:11:55,978
Corrected?

220
00:11:56,012 --> 00:11:57,747
Explaining how
the Apollo missions
were faked

221
00:11:57,780 --> 00:11:59,416
to bankrupt the Soviet Union.

222
00:12:06,389 --> 00:12:08,158
You don't believe
we went to the moon?

223
00:12:09,626 --> 00:12:11,995
I believe it was a brilliant
piece of propaganda.

224
00:12:12,028 --> 00:12:14,397
That the Soviets bankrupted
themselves pouring resources

225
00:12:14,430 --> 00:12:16,900
into rockets
and other useless machines.

226
00:12:16,933 --> 00:12:18,301
"Useless machines."

227
00:12:18,334 --> 00:12:20,136
And if we don't want
a repeat of the excess

228
00:12:20,170 --> 00:12:22,806
and wastefulness
of the 20th century, then

229
00:12:22,839 --> 00:12:24,641
we need to teach our kids
about this planet,

230
00:12:24,674 --> 00:12:26,143
not tales of leaving it.

231
00:12:27,210 --> 00:12:28,778
You know, one of those
useless machines

232
00:12:28,812 --> 00:12:31,681
they used to make
was called an MRI.

233
00:12:31,715 --> 00:12:33,416
And if we had any of those left,

234
00:12:33,449 --> 00:12:34,951
the doctors would've
been able to find

235
00:12:34,984 --> 00:12:36,787
the cyst in my wife's brain

236
00:12:36,820 --> 00:12:39,089
before she died
instead of afterwards.

237
00:12:39,122 --> 00:12:40,333
And then she'd have been
the one sitting here,

238
00:12:40,357 --> 00:12:42,192
listening to this instead of me,

239
00:12:42,225 --> 00:12:43,536
which would have
been a good thing,

240
00:12:43,560 --> 00:12:45,095
'cause she was always

241
00:12:45,829 --> 00:12:47,197
the calmer one.

242
00:12:48,131 --> 00:12:49,967
I'm sorry about your wife,
Mr. Cooper.

243
00:12:51,601 --> 00:12:53,803
But Murph got into a fistfight

244
00:12:53,836 --> 00:12:55,081
with several of
her classmates over this

245
00:12:55,105 --> 00:12:57,039
Apollo nonsense.

246
00:12:57,073 --> 00:12:58,117
So we thought it would be best

247
00:12:58,141 --> 00:12:59,543
to bring you in
and see what ideas

248
00:12:59,576 --> 00:13:01,020
you might have for
dealing with her behavior

249
00:13:01,044 --> 00:13:02,078
on the homefront.

250
00:13:02,111 --> 00:13:03,645
All right. (INHALES)

251
00:13:03,680 --> 00:13:06,949
Yeah, you know what? Um...
There's a game tomorrow night.

252
00:13:06,983 --> 00:13:09,285
She's going through
a bit of a baseball phase.

253
00:13:09,319 --> 00:13:11,364
Her favorite team is playing,
and there's gonna be candy

254
00:13:11,388 --> 00:13:13,090
and soda...

255
00:13:16,258 --> 00:13:18,028
I think I'll take her to that.

256
00:13:21,431 --> 00:13:22,466
(WHISTLING)

257
00:13:23,433 --> 00:13:24,500
How'd it go?

258
00:13:25,601 --> 00:13:27,970
I got you suspended.

259
00:13:28,004 --> 00:13:29,284
- What?
- BOOTS ON RADIO: Cooper.

260
00:13:30,973 --> 00:13:32,509
This is Cooper, go.

261
00:13:32,542 --> 00:13:35,311
Coop, those combines
you rebuilt went haywire.

262
00:13:35,344 --> 00:13:38,115
Uh, just reset the controllers.

263
00:13:38,148 --> 00:13:40,283
I did that.
You should
come take a look.

264
00:14:00,603 --> 00:14:02,415
BOOTS: One by one they've been
peeling off the fields

265
00:14:02,439 --> 00:14:03,607
and heading over.

266
00:14:03,640 --> 00:14:05,308
Something's interfering
with the compass.

267
00:14:06,976 --> 00:14:09,212
Magnetism or some such.

268
00:14:27,597 --> 00:14:28,598
(CLATTERING)

269
00:14:52,455 --> 00:14:54,255
YOUNG MURPH: Nothing special
about which book.

270
00:14:54,657 --> 00:14:56,593
I've been working on it,
like you said.

271
00:14:57,661 --> 00:14:58,728
I counted the spaces.

272
00:14:58,761 --> 00:14:59,796
Why?

273
00:15:02,332 --> 00:15:04,012
In case the ghost
is trying to communicate.

274
00:15:04,934 --> 00:15:06,336
I'm trying Morse.

275
00:15:06,936 --> 00:15:08,205
Morse?

276
00:15:08,605 --> 00:15:10,139
Yeah.

277
00:15:10,173 --> 00:15:11,474
Dots and dashes, used...

278
00:15:11,507 --> 00:15:13,075
I know what
Morse code is, Murph.

279
00:15:13,109 --> 00:15:14,543
I just don't think
your bookshelf's

280
00:15:14,578 --> 00:15:15,645
trying to talk to you.

281
00:15:27,590 --> 00:15:30,093
COOPER: Had to reset every
compass clock and GPS

282
00:15:30,126 --> 00:15:32,028
to offset for the anomaly.

283
00:15:32,061 --> 00:15:33,463
DONALD: Which is?

284
00:15:33,497 --> 00:15:34,498
I don't know.

285
00:15:36,499 --> 00:15:38,935
If the house was built
on magnetic ore,

286
00:15:38,969 --> 00:15:40,179
we'd have seen this
the first time

287
00:15:40,203 --> 00:15:41,638
we switched on the tractor.

288
00:15:44,707 --> 00:15:47,777
I hear your meeting at
the school didn't go so well.

289
00:15:47,810 --> 00:15:49,779
(SCOFFS) You heard?

290
00:15:51,280 --> 00:15:53,617
It's like we've forgotten
who we are, Donald.

291
00:15:55,552 --> 00:15:58,721
Explorers, pioneers,
not caretakers.

292
00:16:00,723 --> 00:16:02,224
When I was a kid,

293
00:16:02,258 --> 00:16:03,727
it felt like they made

294
00:16:03,760 --> 00:16:05,327
something new every day.

295
00:16:05,361 --> 00:16:08,997
Some gadget or idea.

296
00:16:09,031 --> 00:16:10,767
Like every day was Christmas.

297
00:16:10,800 --> 00:16:13,270
But six billion people...

298
00:16:13,869 --> 00:16:15,605
Just try to imagine that.

299
00:16:17,107 --> 00:16:19,609
And every last one of them
trying to have it all.

300
00:16:21,644 --> 00:16:23,044
(SIGHS)

301
00:16:23,079 --> 00:16:24,814
This world isn't so bad.

302
00:16:27,316 --> 00:16:29,418
And Tom will do just fine.

303
00:16:29,452 --> 00:16:31,386
You're the one
who doesn't belong.

304
00:16:31,420 --> 00:16:33,823
Born 40 years too late,
or 40 years too early.

305
00:16:35,157 --> 00:16:37,427
My daughter knew it,
God bless her.

306
00:16:38,594 --> 00:16:41,731
And your kids know it.
Especially Murph.

307
00:16:41,764 --> 00:16:45,168
Well, we used to look up
in the sky and wonder

308
00:16:45,201 --> 00:16:47,404
at our place in the stars.

309
00:16:49,973 --> 00:16:51,641
Now we just look down

310
00:16:51,674 --> 00:16:54,978
and worry about
our place in the dirt.

311
00:16:55,011 --> 00:16:58,248
Cooper,
you were good at something

312
00:16:58,281 --> 00:17:00,383
and you never got a chance
to do anything with it.

313
00:17:01,117 --> 00:17:02,452
I'm sorry.

314
00:17:04,654 --> 00:17:09,058
You didn't expect this dirt
that was giving you this food

315
00:17:09,091 --> 00:17:12,395
to turn on you like that
and destroy you.

316
00:17:12,428 --> 00:17:16,866
In April, I believe I'm right,
15th of April, I think.

317
00:17:16,900 --> 00:17:19,602
'Cause this happened
about 1:30, when that thing

318
00:17:19,635 --> 00:17:21,971
came off the top of that canyon.

319
00:17:22,005 --> 00:17:23,239
(CROWD CHEERING)

320
00:17:23,271 --> 00:17:24,907
In my day,
we had real ballplayers.

321
00:17:25,441 --> 00:17:27,610
Who are these bums?

322
00:17:27,643 --> 00:17:30,246
COOPER: Well, in my day,
people were too busy

323
00:17:30,279 --> 00:17:32,615
fighting over food
to even play baseball.

324
00:17:32,649 --> 00:17:35,619
Popcorn at a ballgame
is unnatural.

325
00:17:35,652 --> 00:17:37,654
I want a hot dog.

326
00:17:37,687 --> 00:17:39,589
School says you're gonna
follow in my footsteps.

327
00:17:40,556 --> 00:17:42,258
- I think that's great.
- (SCOFFS)

328
00:17:42,291 --> 00:17:43,958
You think that's great?

329
00:17:43,993 --> 00:17:45,427
You hate farming, Dad.

330
00:17:46,262 --> 00:17:47,496
Grandpa said.

331
00:17:47,964 --> 00:17:50,200
Grandpa said, huh?

332
00:17:50,233 --> 00:17:52,769
Listen, all that matters is
how you feel about it.

333
00:17:52,802 --> 00:17:54,304
I like what you do.

334
00:17:55,038 --> 00:17:56,406
I like our farm.

335
00:17:57,306 --> 00:17:58,351
You're gonna be great at it.

336
00:17:58,375 --> 00:17:59,608
(CROWD CHEERING)

337
00:18:07,083 --> 00:18:08,652
(SIREN BLARING)

338
00:18:11,788 --> 00:18:12,955
Let's get out of here.

339
00:18:20,496 --> 00:18:22,365
COOPER:
All right, it's a doozy.

340
00:18:23,232 --> 00:18:24,801
Uh, gang, let's mask up.

341
00:18:28,438 --> 00:18:30,307
- Tom? Murph? Check?
- CHILDREN: Yep.

342
00:19:23,926 --> 00:19:26,129
Murph, Tom,
you guys shut your windows?

343
00:19:30,700 --> 00:19:31,735
Murph!

344
00:19:53,222 --> 00:19:54,456
YOUNG MURPH: The ghost.

345
00:19:55,958 --> 00:19:57,093
Grab your pillow.

346
00:19:58,227 --> 00:19:59,796
You're sleeping in with Tom.

347
00:20:54,950 --> 00:20:56,453
It's not a ghost.

348
00:21:02,091 --> 00:21:03,131
(WHISPERING) It's gravity.

349
00:21:05,795 --> 00:21:08,097
DONALD: I'm dropping Tom,
then heading to town.

350
00:21:08,130 --> 00:21:10,266
You want to clean that up

351
00:21:10,299 --> 00:21:11,968
when you're finished
praying to it?

352
00:21:37,627 --> 00:21:39,662
It's not Morse, Murph.
It's binary.

353
00:21:40,363 --> 00:21:42,165
Thick is one, thin is zero.

354
00:21:46,903 --> 00:21:48,004
Coordinates.

355
00:21:50,773 --> 00:21:51,774
Nope.

356
00:21:52,141 --> 00:21:53,243
Mmm-mmm.

357
00:21:54,577 --> 00:21:55,778
Here we go.

358
00:21:57,446 --> 00:21:58,715
Thirty-three.

359
00:22:01,917 --> 00:22:02,919
That's it.

360
00:22:04,186 --> 00:22:06,021
- I can't miss this!
- (SIGHS)

361
00:22:06,054 --> 00:22:08,892
Grandpa will be back
in a couple hours, Murph.

362
00:22:09,992 --> 00:22:12,295
But you don't know
what you're gonna find.

363
00:22:13,429 --> 00:22:14,764
And that

364
00:22:16,132 --> 00:22:17,901
is why I can't take you.

365
00:22:24,107 --> 00:22:25,108
Murph?

366
00:22:27,510 --> 00:22:28,787
Grandpa will be home in a while.

367
00:22:28,811 --> 00:22:30,747
Tell him I'll call him
on the radio.

368
00:22:36,986 --> 00:22:38,021
- (YELPS)
- Jeez!

369
00:22:39,221 --> 00:22:40,256
What are you doing?

370
00:22:40,289 --> 00:22:41,557
(LAUGHING)

371
00:22:41,590 --> 00:22:43,892
Oh, you think
this is funny?
Huh?

372
00:22:43,926 --> 00:22:45,962
You wouldn't be here
if it wasn't for me.

373
00:22:48,097 --> 00:22:49,131
Make yourself useful.

374
00:22:49,164 --> 00:22:50,166
(CONTINUES LAUGHING)

375
00:23:53,429 --> 00:23:54,631
(SOFTLY) Hey, Murph?

376
00:23:56,299 --> 00:23:57,333
Murph!

377
00:24:01,037 --> 00:24:03,039
I think this is
the end of the road.

378
00:24:06,475 --> 00:24:08,111
Didn't you bring
the bolt cutters?

379
00:24:09,378 --> 00:24:10,413
That's my girl.

380
00:24:38,408 --> 00:24:40,151
- MALE GUARD: Step away from the fence!
- No, no, no.

381
00:24:40,175 --> 00:24:41,743
Don't shoot! Don't shoot!
I'm not armed.

382
00:24:41,777 --> 00:24:43,212
My daughter's in the car.

383
00:24:43,245 --> 00:24:44,880
(TASING)

384
00:24:44,913 --> 00:24:46,233
(MECHANICAL FOOTSTEPS
APPROACHING)

385
00:24:49,084 --> 00:24:50,724
- MALE GUARD: Don't be afraid.
- (SCREAMS)

386
00:25:03,532 --> 00:25:05,234
TARS: How did you
find this place?

387
00:25:06,235 --> 00:25:08,004
Where's my daughter?

388
00:25:08,037 --> 00:25:09,347
TARS: You had
the coordinates
for this facility

389
00:25:09,371 --> 00:25:10,672
marked on your map.

390
00:25:10,706 --> 00:25:11,950
Where did you get
those coordinates?

391
00:25:11,974 --> 00:25:13,408
(SHOUTING)
Where's my daughter?

392
00:25:13,443 --> 00:25:14,619
Don't make me
take you down again.

393
00:25:14,643 --> 00:25:16,879
Sit down!

394
00:25:16,912 --> 00:25:19,015
Oh, you still think
you're a Marine, pal?

395
00:25:19,048 --> 00:25:22,050
Marines don't exist anymore.

396
00:25:22,084 --> 00:25:25,421
And I got grunts like you
mowing my grass.

397
00:25:25,455 --> 00:25:27,155
Where did you find
those coordinates?

398
00:25:27,189 --> 00:25:30,092
But you don't look
much like a lawnmower.

399
00:25:30,125 --> 00:25:32,762
Think I'll turn you into an
overqualified vacuum cleaner.

400
00:25:32,795 --> 00:25:33,996
WOMAN: No, you won't.

401
00:25:35,764 --> 00:25:37,333
TARS, back down, please.

402
00:25:39,334 --> 00:25:42,939
You know, you're taking a risk
using ex-military as security.

403
00:25:42,972 --> 00:25:46,775
They're old,
and their control units
are unpredictable.

404
00:25:46,808 --> 00:25:48,411
It's what the government
could spare.

405
00:25:49,011 --> 00:25:50,311
(PANTING)

406
00:25:50,346 --> 00:25:51,447
Who are you?

407
00:25:52,014 --> 00:25:53,783
Dr. Brand.

408
00:25:53,816 --> 00:25:56,352
I knew a Dr. Brand once.
He was a professor.

409
00:25:56,385 --> 00:25:58,454
What makes you think I'm not?

410
00:25:58,487 --> 00:26:00,323
Oh, wasn't near as cute, either.

411
00:26:00,789 --> 00:26:02,023
Please, Dr. Brand.

412
00:26:02,058 --> 00:26:03,418
I don't have
any idea what this is.

413
00:26:04,460 --> 00:26:06,796
Now I'm scared for
my daughter and
I want her by my side.

414
00:26:06,829 --> 00:26:08,096
You give me that,

415
00:26:08,130 --> 00:26:09,690
I'll tell you anything
you want to know.

416
00:26:12,635 --> 00:26:13,970
Get the principals

417
00:26:14,003 --> 00:26:15,723
and the girl in
the conference room, please.

418
00:26:16,939 --> 00:26:18,241
Your daughter is fine.

419
00:26:18,741 --> 00:26:19,876
Bright kid.

420
00:26:20,576 --> 00:26:22,712
Must have a very smart mother.

421
00:26:22,745 --> 00:26:25,314
It's pretty clear
you don't want any visitors.

422
00:26:25,348 --> 00:26:26,958
So why don't you
just let us back up
from your fence

423
00:26:26,982 --> 00:26:29,351
and we'll be on our way? Huh?

424
00:26:29,385 --> 00:26:30,619
It's not that simple.

425
00:26:30,653 --> 00:26:32,154
Well, sure, it is.

426
00:26:32,187 --> 00:26:33,822
I don't know anything about you.

427
00:26:33,855 --> 00:26:35,791
I don't know
anything about this place.

428
00:26:36,659 --> 00:26:37,860
Yes, you do.

429
00:26:43,532 --> 00:26:44,532
Dad!

430
00:26:47,402 --> 00:26:48,402
Hello, Cooper.

431
00:26:49,906 --> 00:26:50,906
Professor Brand.

432
00:26:52,809 --> 00:26:55,277
WILLIAMS: Explain to me
how you found this facility.

433
00:26:55,310 --> 00:26:57,111
Kind of an accident.
We stumbled upon it.

434
00:26:57,146 --> 00:26:58,981
We were on a salvage run...

435
00:26:59,014 --> 00:27:01,784
You're sitting in the
best-kept secret in the world.

436
00:27:01,817 --> 00:27:05,621
Nobody stumbles in here.
Nobody stumbles out.

437
00:27:05,654 --> 00:27:06,974
PROFESSOR BRAND:
Cooper... Please.

438
00:27:07,656 --> 00:27:09,457
Cooperate with these people.

439
00:27:09,492 --> 00:27:10,492
Look.

440
00:27:11,993 --> 00:27:14,129
It's kind of hard to explain.

441
00:27:14,163 --> 00:27:18,000
We learned these coordinates
from an anomaly.

442
00:27:18,768 --> 00:27:20,302
What sort of anomaly?

443
00:27:20,336 --> 00:27:22,338
I hesitate to
term it supernatural,

444
00:27:22,371 --> 00:27:23,982
(CHUCKLES) but it definitely
wasn't scientific.

445
00:27:24,006 --> 00:27:26,408
You're going to have to be
specific, Mr. Cooper.

446
00:27:26,441 --> 00:27:27,743
Right now.

447
00:27:27,777 --> 00:27:28,945
It was gravity.

448
00:27:32,448 --> 00:27:33,448
DOYLE: Um...

449
00:27:34,216 --> 00:27:35,818
What sort of
gravitational anomaly?

450
00:27:35,851 --> 00:27:37,286
- Where was this?
- COOPER: Hey.

451
00:27:37,319 --> 00:27:38,486
Now I'm real happy

452
00:27:38,520 --> 00:27:40,889
'cause you're excited
about gravity, bud,

453
00:27:40,923 --> 00:27:42,334
but you're not getting
any answers from us

454
00:27:42,358 --> 00:27:43,559
until I get assurances.

455
00:27:43,592 --> 00:27:45,094
- Assurances?
- Yeah.

456
00:27:46,195 --> 00:27:47,963
Like that we're
getting out of here.

457
00:27:47,996 --> 00:27:49,636
And I don't mean
in the trunk of some car.

458
00:27:49,665 --> 00:27:51,166
(ALL LAUGHING)

459
00:27:52,134 --> 00:27:54,435
Don't you know who we are, Coop?

460
00:27:54,469 --> 00:27:55,971
No, Professor, I don't.

461
00:27:56,005 --> 00:27:57,685
BRAND: You know my father,
Professor Brand.

462
00:27:58,440 --> 00:27:59,508
We're NASA.

463
00:28:01,477 --> 00:28:02,711
NASA?

464
00:28:02,745 --> 00:28:04,045
PROFESSOR BRAND: NASA.

465
00:28:04,079 --> 00:28:05,647
The same NASA you flew for.

466
00:28:17,125 --> 00:28:18,926
COOPER: I heard
they shut you down, sir,

467
00:28:18,961 --> 00:28:21,063
for refusing to drop bombs
from the stratosphere

468
00:28:21,097 --> 00:28:23,165
onto starving people.

469
00:28:23,199 --> 00:28:25,601
When they realized that
killing other people was

470
00:28:25,635 --> 00:28:28,671
not a long-term solution,
then they needed us back.

471
00:28:28,704 --> 00:28:29,805
In secret.

472
00:28:29,806 --> 00:28:30,906
Why secret?

473
00:28:30,939 --> 00:28:32,641
Because public opinion
wouldn't allow

474
00:28:32,674 --> 00:28:35,077
spending on space exploration.

475
00:28:35,110 --> 00:28:37,150
Not when you're struggling
to put food on the table.

476
00:28:38,580 --> 00:28:40,349
Blight.

477
00:28:40,382 --> 00:28:44,020
Wheat seven years ago.
Okra this year.

478
00:28:44,953 --> 00:28:47,156
Now there's just corn.

479
00:28:47,189 --> 00:28:49,090
And we're growing
more than we ever have.

480
00:28:49,124 --> 00:28:51,226
But like the potatoes in Ireland

481
00:28:51,260 --> 00:28:53,061
and the wheat in the Dust Bowl,

482
00:28:53,762 --> 00:28:56,165
the corn will die.

483
00:28:56,899 --> 00:28:58,034
Soon.

484
00:29:03,873 --> 00:29:08,110
We'll find a way, Professor.
We always have.

485
00:29:08,143 --> 00:29:11,579
Driven by the unshakeable
faith the Earth is ours.

486
00:29:12,448 --> 00:29:14,150
Well, not just ours, no.

487
00:29:14,816 --> 00:29:16,185
But it is our home.

488
00:29:17,887 --> 00:29:21,190
Earth's atmosphere
is 80% nitrogen.

489
00:29:21,223 --> 00:29:22,991
We don't even breathe nitrogen.

490
00:29:23,024 --> 00:29:25,327
Blight does.
And as it thrives,

491
00:29:25,360 --> 00:29:28,597
our air gets
less and less oxygen.

492
00:29:28,630 --> 00:29:30,065
The last people to starve

493
00:29:30,099 --> 00:29:32,233
will be the first to suffocate.

494
00:29:32,267 --> 00:29:34,203
And your daughter's generation

495
00:29:36,105 --> 00:29:38,373
will be the last
to survive on Earth.

496
00:29:38,406 --> 00:29:40,175
BRAND: Murph is feeling
a little tired.

497
00:29:40,209 --> 00:29:42,289
I was wondering if she could
take a nap in my office.

498
00:29:42,445 --> 00:29:43,646
Yeah. Thank you.

499
00:29:46,582 --> 00:29:47,583
Okay.

500
00:29:48,817 --> 00:29:50,152
Now you need to tell me

501
00:29:50,186 --> 00:29:53,021
what your plan is
to save the world.

502
00:29:53,055 --> 00:29:55,123
We're not meant
to save the world.

503
00:29:55,157 --> 00:29:56,325
We're meant to leave it.

504
00:30:02,365 --> 00:30:03,799
COOPER: Rangers.

505
00:30:03,833 --> 00:30:05,210
PROFESSOR BRAND:
The last components

506
00:30:05,234 --> 00:30:08,870
of our one versatile ship
in orbit, the Endurance.

507
00:30:08,904 --> 00:30:10,373
Our final expedition.

508
00:30:11,440 --> 00:30:14,110
You sent people out there
looking for a new home?

509
00:30:14,910 --> 00:30:16,645
The Lazarus missions.

510
00:30:16,678 --> 00:30:17,879
Oh, that sounds cheerful.

511
00:30:17,913 --> 00:30:19,982
Lazarus came back from the dead.

512
00:30:20,015 --> 00:30:21,695
Sure, but he had to die
in the first place.

513
00:30:22,484 --> 00:30:24,053
There's not a planet
in our solar system

514
00:30:24,086 --> 00:30:25,520
that could sustain life

515
00:30:25,554 --> 00:30:28,223
and the nearest star's
over 1,000 years away.

516
00:30:28,257 --> 00:30:30,493
And that doesn't even
qualify as futile.

517
00:30:32,260 --> 00:30:33,462
Where'd you send 'em?

518
00:30:33,962 --> 00:30:35,897
Cooper,

519
00:30:35,931 --> 00:30:38,567
I can't tell you any more
unless you agree

520
00:30:38,600 --> 00:30:40,836
to pilot this craft.

521
00:30:40,870 --> 00:30:42,270
You're the best pilot
we ever had.

522
00:30:42,304 --> 00:30:44,272
I barely left the stratosphere.

523
00:30:44,306 --> 00:30:46,541
This team never
left the simulator.

524
00:30:46,575 --> 00:30:48,077
We need a pilot,

525
00:30:48,110 --> 00:30:50,679
and this is the mission
that you were trained for.

526
00:30:50,712 --> 00:30:51,814
Without even knowing it?

527
00:30:53,382 --> 00:30:55,617
An hour ago, you didn't even
know I was alive.

528
00:30:55,651 --> 00:30:57,253
You were going anyway.

529
00:30:57,719 --> 00:30:59,721
We had no choice.

530
00:30:59,755 --> 00:31:01,223
But something sent you here.

531
00:31:01,657 --> 00:31:02,924
They chose you.

532
00:31:02,958 --> 00:31:04,126
Who's "they"?

533
00:31:12,300 --> 00:31:13,836
How long would I be gone?

534
00:31:14,803 --> 00:31:16,105
Hard to know.

535
00:31:16,572 --> 00:31:17,573
Years?

536
00:31:18,374 --> 00:31:19,708
I've got kids, Professor.

537
00:31:20,776 --> 00:31:22,378
Get out there and save them.

538
00:31:25,981 --> 00:31:27,683
Who's "they"?

539
00:31:27,716 --> 00:31:29,985
We started detecting
gravitational anomalies

540
00:31:30,018 --> 00:31:31,920
almost 50 years ago.

541
00:31:31,954 --> 00:31:33,888
Mostly small distortions
to our instruments

542
00:31:33,922 --> 00:31:35,557
in the upper atmosphere.

543
00:31:35,591 --> 00:31:38,461
In fact, I believe
you encountered one yourself.

544
00:31:39,261 --> 00:31:41,196
Yeah, over the Straits.

545
00:31:42,130 --> 00:31:43,432
My crash.

546
00:31:43,465 --> 00:31:44,800
Something tripped
my fly-by-wire.

547
00:31:45,367 --> 00:31:46,534
Exactly.

548
00:31:47,770 --> 00:31:52,441
But of all these anomalies,
the most significant is this.

549
00:31:52,475 --> 00:31:53,475
Out near Saturn,

550
00:31:54,910 --> 00:31:56,679
a disturbance of spacetime.

551
00:31:58,880 --> 00:32:00,682
Is that a wormhole?

552
00:32:00,715 --> 00:32:02,217
It appeared 48 years ago.

553
00:32:02,250 --> 00:32:04,320
And it leads where?

554
00:32:04,920 --> 00:32:06,489
Another galaxy.

555
00:32:08,390 --> 00:32:10,759
A wormhole's not a naturally
occurring phenomenon.

556
00:32:10,792 --> 00:32:11,861
Someone placed it there.

557
00:32:13,028 --> 00:32:14,996
- "They"?
- Mmm-hmm.

558
00:32:15,030 --> 00:32:16,965
And whoever they are,

559
00:32:16,999 --> 00:32:19,501
they appear to be
looking out for us.

560
00:32:19,534 --> 00:32:22,337
That wormhole
lets us travel
to other stars.

561
00:32:22,371 --> 00:32:24,406
It came along
right as we needed it.

562
00:32:24,440 --> 00:32:26,008
They've put potentially
habitable worlds

563
00:32:26,041 --> 00:32:27,541
right within our reach.

564
00:32:27,575 --> 00:32:29,912
Twelve, in fact,
from our initial probes.

565
00:32:29,945 --> 00:32:31,063
You sent probes into that?

566
00:32:31,064 --> 00:32:32,181
Mmm-hmm.

567
00:32:32,214 --> 00:32:34,849
We sent people into it.
Ten years ago.

568
00:32:36,385 --> 00:32:38,520
The Lazarus missions.

569
00:32:38,553 --> 00:32:40,121
PROFESSOR BRAND:
Twelve possible worlds,

570
00:32:40,155 --> 00:32:41,790
12 Ranger launches carrying

571
00:32:42,825 --> 00:32:45,260
the bravest humans ever to live,

572
00:32:45,294 --> 00:32:48,163
led by the remarkable
Dr. Mann.

573
00:32:48,197 --> 00:32:49,598
Each person's landing pod

574
00:32:49,631 --> 00:32:51,533
had enough life support
for two years.

575
00:32:51,567 --> 00:32:53,535
But they could
use hibernation
to stretch that,

576
00:32:53,569 --> 00:32:55,369
making observations on organics

577
00:32:55,404 --> 00:32:57,071
over a decade or more.

578
00:32:57,105 --> 00:32:59,307
Their mission was
to assess their world,

579
00:32:59,341 --> 00:33:01,176
and if it showed potential,

580
00:33:01,209 --> 00:33:02,778
then they could
send out a signal,

581
00:33:02,811 --> 00:33:05,680
bed down for the long nap,
wait to be rescued.

582
00:33:05,713 --> 00:33:07,616
And what if the world
didn't show promise?

583
00:33:08,317 --> 00:33:09,585
Hence the bravery.

584
00:33:10,752 --> 00:33:12,887
You don't have the resources
to visit all 12.

585
00:33:13,388 --> 00:33:14,388
No.

586
00:33:15,658 --> 00:33:18,394
Data transmission back through
the wormhole is rudimentary.

587
00:33:18,427 --> 00:33:20,562
Simple binary pings
on an annual basis

588
00:33:20,596 --> 00:33:23,499
give us some clue as to
which worlds have potential.

589
00:33:23,532 --> 00:33:25,767
And one system shows promise.

590
00:33:25,801 --> 00:33:27,970
One. That's a bit of
a long shot, isn't it?

591
00:33:29,204 --> 00:33:32,273
One system with
three potential worlds?

592
00:33:32,307 --> 00:33:33,709
(CHUCKLES)
No long shot.

593
00:33:35,944 --> 00:33:36,944
Okay.

594
00:33:37,946 --> 00:33:39,982
So if we find a home,

595
00:33:42,817 --> 00:33:44,053
then what?

596
00:33:44,086 --> 00:33:45,921
That's the long shot.

597
00:33:46,621 --> 00:33:50,458
There's a Plan A and a Plan B.

598
00:33:50,491 --> 00:33:52,060
Did you notice anything strange

599
00:33:52,093 --> 00:33:53,093
about the launch chamber?

600
00:34:05,307 --> 00:34:08,410
COOPER: This entire facility's
a centrifuge.

601
00:34:08,443 --> 00:34:11,013
Some kind of vehicle.
A space station?

602
00:34:11,046 --> 00:34:13,181
PROFESSOR BRAND: Both. Plan A.

603
00:34:13,214 --> 00:34:15,484
How do you get it
off the ground?

604
00:34:15,517 --> 00:34:19,521
The first gravitational
anomalies changed everything.

605
00:34:19,553 --> 00:34:24,057
Suddenly we knew that
harnessing gravity was real.

606
00:34:24,091 --> 00:34:26,628
So I started working on a theory

607
00:34:26,662 --> 00:34:29,097
and we started
building this station.

608
00:34:29,131 --> 00:34:30,899
But you haven't solved it yet.

609
00:34:32,267 --> 00:34:33,569
That's why there's Plan B.

610
00:34:34,301 --> 00:34:36,370
The problem is gravity.

611
00:34:36,404 --> 00:34:39,074
How to get a viable amount of
human life off the planet.

612
00:34:39,108 --> 00:34:40,841
This is one way.

613
00:34:40,875 --> 00:34:43,445
Plan B: a population bomb.

614
00:34:43,477 --> 00:34:46,080
Over 5,000 fertilized eggs

615
00:34:46,115 --> 00:34:48,283
weighing in at
just under 900 kilos.

616
00:34:49,151 --> 00:34:50,886
Well, how would you raise 'em?

617
00:34:50,919 --> 00:34:53,354
With equipment on board,
we incubate the first 10.

618
00:34:53,388 --> 00:34:55,390
After that, with surrogacy,

619
00:34:55,423 --> 00:34:56,992
the growth becomes exponential.

620
00:34:57,960 --> 00:34:59,494
Within 30 years,

621
00:34:59,528 --> 00:35:01,363
we could have
a colony of hundreds.

622
00:35:01,396 --> 00:35:03,164
The real difficulty
with colonization

623
00:35:03,198 --> 00:35:04,466
is genetic diversity.

624
00:35:05,300 --> 00:35:07,536
This takes care of that.

625
00:35:07,569 --> 00:35:09,471
But what about
the people here?
You just...

626
00:35:10,005 --> 00:35:11,073
You give up on 'em?

627
00:35:11,873 --> 00:35:12,941
My kids?

628
00:35:14,109 --> 00:35:16,945
That's why Plan A
is a lot more fun.

629
00:35:19,348 --> 00:35:20,949
How far have you got?

630
00:35:20,982 --> 00:35:22,350
Almost there.

631
00:35:22,384 --> 00:35:24,620
You're asking me
to hang everything

632
00:35:25,887 --> 00:35:27,556
on an almost.

633
00:35:27,589 --> 00:35:29,758
I'm asking you to trust me.

634
00:35:31,726 --> 00:35:33,061
(SIGHS)

635
00:35:33,094 --> 00:35:34,595
Find us a new home.

636
00:35:35,530 --> 00:35:38,266
And by the time you return,

637
00:35:38,300 --> 00:35:40,568
I will have solved
the problem of gravity.

638
00:35:41,770 --> 00:35:43,105
I give you my word.

639
00:35:55,984 --> 00:35:57,119
YOUNG MURPH: Go away!

640
00:36:05,293 --> 00:36:06,628
(SIGHING)

641
00:36:08,030 --> 00:36:09,464
Murph.

642
00:36:09,497 --> 00:36:12,368
Go! If you're leaving,
just go.

643
00:36:15,637 --> 00:36:17,940
DONALD: This world was never
enough for you, was it, Coop?

644
00:36:19,074 --> 00:36:20,608
What, because heading out there

645
00:36:20,642 --> 00:36:22,611
is what I feel like
I was born to do?

646
00:36:23,545 --> 00:36:25,380
And it excites me?

647
00:36:26,381 --> 00:36:28,817
No, that does not make it wrong.

648
00:36:28,850 --> 00:36:30,619
DONALD: It might.

649
00:36:30,652 --> 00:36:33,155
Don't trust the right thing
done for the wrong reason.

650
00:36:34,489 --> 00:36:36,591
The why of the thing,
that's the foundation.

651
00:36:36,624 --> 00:36:38,627
And the foundation's solid.

652
00:36:42,263 --> 00:36:44,432
We farmers,
we sit here every year

653
00:36:44,466 --> 00:36:47,101
when the rains fail and we say,

654
00:36:47,135 --> 00:36:48,170
"Next year."

655
00:36:49,404 --> 00:36:51,006
Well, next year
ain't gonna save us,

656
00:36:51,039 --> 00:36:52,674
nor the one after that.

657
00:36:53,575 --> 00:36:55,077
This world's a treasure, Donald,

658
00:36:55,110 --> 00:36:57,646
but it's been telling us
to leave for a while now.

659
00:37:02,550 --> 00:37:04,318
Mankind was born on Earth,

660
00:37:04,352 --> 00:37:06,121
it was never meant to die here.

661
00:37:09,458 --> 00:37:10,825
Tom will be all right,

662
00:37:10,858 --> 00:37:12,728
but you got to
make things right
with Murph.

663
00:37:12,761 --> 00:37:13,762
I will.

664
00:37:15,063 --> 00:37:17,865
Without making promises
you don't know you can keep.

665
00:37:28,643 --> 00:37:30,546
You have to talk to me, Murph.

666
00:37:33,247 --> 00:37:35,650
I need to fix this before I go.

667
00:37:35,684 --> 00:37:38,086
Then I'll keep it broken
so you have to stay.

668
00:37:40,222 --> 00:37:42,524
After you kids came along,
your mom,

669
00:37:42,557 --> 00:37:44,827
she said something to me
I never quite understood.

670
00:37:45,260 --> 00:37:46,829
She said, "Now,

671
00:37:48,930 --> 00:37:53,101
"we're just here to be
memories for our kids."

672
00:37:58,740 --> 00:38:00,809
And I think now I understand
what she meant.

673
00:38:04,679 --> 00:38:05,912
Once you're a parent,

674
00:38:05,947 --> 00:38:08,217
you're the ghost
of your children's future.

675
00:38:09,751 --> 00:38:11,854
(SNIFFLES) You said
ghosts didn't exist.

676
00:38:18,693 --> 00:38:20,028
That's right, Murph.

677
00:38:23,398 --> 00:38:24,666
Murph, look at me.

678
00:38:27,835 --> 00:38:30,038
I can't be your ghost right now.

679
00:38:32,174 --> 00:38:33,942
I need to exist.

680
00:38:35,610 --> 00:38:37,579
They chose me.

681
00:38:38,413 --> 00:38:39,947
Murph, they chose me.

682
00:38:39,981 --> 00:38:42,117
You saw. You're the one
who led me to 'em.

683
00:38:44,986 --> 00:38:47,222
That's exactly why you can't go.

684
00:38:50,792 --> 00:38:53,161
I figured out the message.

685
00:38:53,194 --> 00:38:55,597
One word. Know what it is?

686
00:38:56,464 --> 00:38:57,766
"Stay."

687
00:38:58,300 --> 00:38:59,568
It says, "Stay," Dad.

688
00:38:59,601 --> 00:39:00,736
(WHISPERS) Murph.

689
00:39:01,603 --> 00:39:03,704
You don't believe me.

690
00:39:03,738 --> 00:39:06,674
Look at the books!
Look at this. It says, "Stay."

691
00:39:06,708 --> 00:39:09,311
Why... You're not listening!
It says, "Stay!"

692
00:39:10,078 --> 00:39:11,879
No, I'm coming back.

693
00:39:11,913 --> 00:39:13,081
When?

694
00:39:16,818 --> 00:39:17,920
(SNIFFLES)

695
00:39:18,953 --> 00:39:20,322
(KISSES)

696
00:39:26,428 --> 00:39:29,597
One for you, one for me.

697
00:39:29,631 --> 00:39:32,834
When I'm up there
in hypersleep, or...
(SNIFFLES)

698
00:39:32,868 --> 00:39:35,070
Or traveling
near the speed of light,

699
00:39:36,338 --> 00:39:39,007
or near a black hole,

700
00:39:39,040 --> 00:39:43,145
time's gonna change for me.
It's gonna run more slowly.

701
00:39:45,046 --> 00:39:46,682
When we get back,

702
00:39:47,816 --> 00:39:49,617
we're gonna compare.

703
00:39:49,650 --> 00:39:51,062
YOUNG MURPH: Time will
run differently for us?

704
00:39:51,086 --> 00:39:52,086
(WHISPERS) Yeah.

705
00:39:53,121 --> 00:39:54,555
By the time I get back,

706
00:39:54,589 --> 00:39:57,726
we might even be
the same age, you and me.

707
00:39:58,326 --> 00:40:00,329
"What?" Imagine that!

708
00:40:05,133 --> 00:40:06,635
Aw, Murph...

709
00:40:06,668 --> 00:40:08,936
You have no idea
when you're coming back.

710
00:40:10,906 --> 00:40:12,174
- No idea at all!
- (CLATTERS)

711
00:40:12,841 --> 00:40:14,376
- Murphy...
- (SOBBING)

712
00:40:15,710 --> 00:40:17,645
Murph, don't make me
leave like this.

713
00:40:17,679 --> 00:40:19,780
Come on, Murph!

714
00:40:19,814 --> 00:40:21,917
Don't make me leave
like this, Murph!

715
00:40:25,519 --> 00:40:27,122
(YOUNG MURPH
CONTINUES SOBBING)

716
00:40:29,958 --> 00:40:31,258
Hey...

717
00:40:31,293 --> 00:40:33,094
I love you.

718
00:40:33,128 --> 00:40:35,662
Forever. You hear me?

719
00:40:35,697 --> 00:40:38,400
I love you forever.
And I'm coming back.

720
00:40:44,372 --> 00:40:45,774
I'm coming back.

721
00:41:04,058 --> 00:41:05,326
How'd it go?

722
00:41:05,360 --> 00:41:06,427
COOPER: It went fine.

723
00:41:06,460 --> 00:41:07,763
Just fine.

724
00:41:15,103 --> 00:41:16,103
I love you, Tom.

725
00:41:16,704 --> 00:41:17,721
Travel safe, yeah?

726
00:41:17,722 --> 00:41:18,738
Yeah.

727
00:41:18,773 --> 00:41:20,453
You look after our place
for me, all right?

728
00:41:21,175 --> 00:41:22,175
- All right?
- Uh-huh.

729
00:41:27,682 --> 00:41:29,093
Hey, can I use your truck
while you're gone?

730
00:41:29,117 --> 00:41:30,786
You mean your truck?

731
00:41:32,053 --> 00:41:33,889
I'll make sure
they bring it back.

732
00:41:34,756 --> 00:41:35,957
(ENGINE STARTS)

733
00:41:35,991 --> 00:41:37,793
Look after my kids, Donald!

734
00:41:50,672 --> 00:41:52,240
TARS: Go for
main engine start.

735
00:41:52,273 --> 00:41:53,909
T minus 10...

736
00:41:54,542 --> 00:41:55,643
Dad!

737
00:41:55,676 --> 00:41:56,878
Nine...

738
00:41:56,911 --> 00:41:58,046
Dad!

739
00:41:58,780 --> 00:41:59,781
Eight,

740
00:42:01,316 --> 00:42:02,283
seven...

741
00:42:02,316 --> 00:42:03,452
Dad!

742
00:42:04,019 --> 00:42:05,019
Six,

743
00:42:06,521 --> 00:42:09,157
five, main engine start, four,

744
00:42:10,591 --> 00:42:11,793
three,

745
00:42:12,360 --> 00:42:13,360
two,

746
00:42:14,696 --> 00:42:16,364
one. Booster ignition and...

747
00:42:17,331 --> 00:42:18,365
Lift off.

748
00:42:25,840 --> 00:42:27,976
All engines look good.
Beginning roll program.

749
00:42:32,713 --> 00:42:35,217
Prepare for
stage one separation.

750
00:42:35,649 --> 00:42:36,649
Stage one.

751
00:42:42,657 --> 00:42:44,359
There is Mach 1.

752
00:42:45,494 --> 00:42:46,928
Everybody good?

753
00:42:46,962 --> 00:42:49,131
Plenty of slaves
for my robot colony?

754
00:42:51,099 --> 00:42:52,767
They gave him a humor setting,

755
00:42:52,800 --> 00:42:54,736
so he'd fit in better
with his unit.

756
00:42:54,769 --> 00:42:56,604
He thinks it relaxes us.

757
00:42:56,638 --> 00:42:59,207
A giant sarcastic robot.

758
00:43:00,341 --> 00:43:01,910
What a great idea!

759
00:43:01,943 --> 00:43:03,019
TARS: I have a cue light
I can use

760
00:43:03,043 --> 00:43:04,546
when I'm joking if you like.

761
00:43:04,579 --> 00:43:06,113
That'd probably help.

762
00:43:06,147 --> 00:43:07,825
Yeah, you can use it to find
your way back into the ship

763
00:43:07,849 --> 00:43:09,351
after I blow you
out the airlock.

764
00:43:10,918 --> 00:43:12,420
What's your humor setting, TARS?

765
00:43:12,454 --> 00:43:13,955
That's 100%.

766
00:43:13,988 --> 00:43:16,390
Let's bring it on down
to 75, please.

767
00:43:16,424 --> 00:43:17,959
TARS: Stage two separation.

768
00:43:28,837 --> 00:43:31,239
COOPER:
All feeds going manual.

769
00:43:31,272 --> 00:43:32,340
DOYLE: Going manual.

770
00:43:35,076 --> 00:43:36,653
Deactivate probe heater
one, two and three.

771
00:43:36,677 --> 00:43:37,845
DOYLE: Check.

772
00:43:43,785 --> 00:43:45,053
Taking control.

773
00:43:45,086 --> 00:43:46,421
TARS: This is handover to you.

774
00:43:50,792 --> 00:43:51,793
DOYLE: ADF check.

775
00:43:51,826 --> 00:43:53,428
COOPER: Over.

776
00:43:53,461 --> 00:43:57,131
Pull thrusters back.
Fuel cells one,
two, three.

777
00:43:57,165 --> 00:43:58,500
DOYLE: 100%.

778
00:43:58,533 --> 00:43:59,601
COOPER: Ex-mites.

779
00:44:09,611 --> 00:44:11,112
It's hard leaving everything.

780
00:44:11,646 --> 00:44:15,016
My kids. Your father.

781
00:44:15,049 --> 00:44:17,352
We're going to be spending
a lot of time together.

782
00:44:17,385 --> 00:44:18,786
We should learn to talk.

783
00:44:18,820 --> 00:44:20,155
And when not to.

784
00:44:22,490 --> 00:44:24,359
Just being honest.

785
00:44:24,392 --> 00:44:27,062
I don't think
you need to be that honest.

786
00:44:27,095 --> 00:44:29,130
Hey, TARS, what's
your honesty parameter?

787
00:44:29,563 --> 00:44:30,664
90%.

788
00:44:30,698 --> 00:44:32,400
90%?

789
00:44:32,433 --> 00:44:35,637
Absolute honesty isn't
always the most diplomatic,

790
00:44:35,670 --> 00:44:37,972
nor the safest form
of communication
with emotional beings.

791
00:44:38,373 --> 00:44:39,507
Okay.

792
00:44:40,108 --> 00:44:42,577
90% it is, Dr. Brand.

793
00:44:46,781 --> 00:44:48,316
We are coming up
on the Endurance.

794
00:44:48,349 --> 00:44:49,517
Twelve minutes out.

795
00:45:06,901 --> 00:45:08,670
Okay. Taking control.

796
00:45:12,707 --> 00:45:15,176
Approaching module port,
500 meters.

797
00:45:28,122 --> 00:45:29,224
It's all you, Doyle.

798
00:45:48,043 --> 00:45:50,245
Nice and easy, Doyle.
Nice and easy.

799
00:45:55,616 --> 00:45:56,951
I'm feeling good.

800
00:45:56,984 --> 00:45:58,119
Take us home.

801
00:46:05,760 --> 00:46:07,128
Lock?

802
00:46:07,162 --> 00:46:08,729
- Target locked.
- DOYLE: Target locked.

803
00:46:08,763 --> 00:46:10,464
- COOPER: Well done.
- Okay, helmets on.

804
00:46:10,497 --> 00:46:11,497
Good job.

805
00:46:44,966 --> 00:46:46,734
Door's not charging.

806
00:46:46,768 --> 00:46:48,236
Never mind.

807
00:47:11,325 --> 00:47:12,627
Cooper, you should have control.

808
00:47:13,094 --> 00:47:14,496
Control here.

809
00:47:16,230 --> 00:47:18,533
Communication with
ring module active.

810
00:47:25,506 --> 00:47:26,541
(WHISPERS) Oh, wow.

811
00:47:32,613 --> 00:47:33,613
TARS: That's initiate.

812
00:47:39,954 --> 00:47:41,255
(BRAND SIGHS)

813
00:47:41,288 --> 00:47:42,524
COOPER: Are we ready to spin?

