1066
01:02:57,571 --> 01:02:59,573
No, no, no, it's not that.
It's time.

1067
01:02:59,606 --> 01:03:01,642
The gravity on that planet
will slow our clock

1068
01:03:01,675 --> 01:03:03,744
compared to Earth's drastically.

1069
01:03:04,711 --> 01:03:06,212
How bad?

1070
01:03:06,246 --> 01:03:09,416
Every hour we spend
on that planet will be

1071
01:03:10,583 --> 01:03:12,452
seven years back on Earth.

1072
01:03:13,620 --> 01:03:15,022
(WHISPERS) Jesus!

1073
01:03:15,055 --> 01:03:16,390
Well, that's relativity, folks.

1074
01:03:18,191 --> 01:03:20,694
Well, we can't just
drop down there without...

1075
01:03:20,727 --> 01:03:22,762
Cooper, we have a mission.

1076
01:03:22,795 --> 01:03:23,973
Yeah, Doyle, we have a mission,

1077
01:03:23,997 --> 01:03:25,565
and our mission Plan A is

1078
01:03:25,598 --> 01:03:27,400
to find a planet that
can habitate the people

1079
01:03:27,433 --> 01:03:29,035
that are living
on the Earth right now.

1080
01:03:29,068 --> 01:03:30,446
You can't just think
about your family.

1081
01:03:30,470 --> 01:03:31,881
Now, you have to think
bigger than that, all right?

1082
01:03:31,905 --> 01:03:33,307
I am thinking about my family

1083
01:03:33,340 --> 01:03:35,175
and millions of
other families, okay?

1084
01:03:35,209 --> 01:03:37,343
Plan A does not work
if the people on Earth

1085
01:03:37,377 --> 01:03:39,046
are dead by the time
we pull it off.

1086
01:03:40,580 --> 01:03:42,782
No. It doesn't.

1087
01:03:42,816 --> 01:03:44,051
That's why there's a Plan B.

1088
01:03:46,086 --> 01:03:48,054
Okay. Cooper's right.

1089
01:03:48,088 --> 01:03:49,632
We need to think about time
as a resource,

1090
01:03:49,656 --> 01:03:50,891
just like oxygen and food.

1091
01:03:50,924 --> 01:03:52,244
Going down there
is gonna cost us.

1092
01:03:54,027 --> 01:03:55,195
All right, look.

1093
01:03:56,830 --> 01:03:58,698
Dr. Mann's data
is promising, right,

1094
01:03:58,732 --> 01:04:00,476
but it's going to take us
months to get there.

1095
01:04:00,500 --> 01:04:02,703
And Edmunds', it's even further.

1096
01:04:02,736 --> 01:04:03,904
Now Miller hasn't sent much,

1097
01:04:03,937 --> 01:04:05,247
but what she has sent
is very promising.

1098
01:04:05,271 --> 01:04:06,906
It's water, it's organics...

1099
01:04:06,939 --> 01:04:07,984
You don't find that every day.

1100
01:04:08,008 --> 01:04:09,576
No, you don't.

1101
01:04:09,610 --> 01:04:12,079
And just think
about the resources,
including time,

1102
01:04:12,112 --> 01:04:14,181
that would be spent
trying to get back here.

1103
01:04:15,449 --> 01:04:17,083
- Romilly?
- Yeah.

1104
01:04:17,117 --> 01:04:19,285
How far off from Miller's
planet do we have to be

1105
01:04:19,318 --> 01:04:21,555
to stay out of the time shift?

1106
01:04:21,588 --> 01:04:22,823
Just back from the cusp.

1107
01:04:23,490 --> 01:04:24,858
Which is here,

1108
01:04:24,892 --> 01:04:26,102
just outside of Miller's planet.

1109
01:04:26,126 --> 01:04:27,694
- ROMILLY: Right.
- Okay.

1110
01:04:29,129 --> 01:04:32,232
Here's Gargantua.
Here's Miller's planet.

1111
01:04:32,265 --> 01:04:33,933
Instead of taking the Endurance

1112
01:04:33,967 --> 01:04:35,210
into orbit
around Miller's planet,

1113
01:04:35,234 --> 01:04:36,736
which would conserve fuel,

1114
01:04:36,770 --> 01:04:38,471
but we would lose a lot of time,

1115
01:04:38,505 --> 01:04:41,407
what if we take a wider orbit
around Gargantua,

1116
01:04:41,441 --> 01:04:42,909
parallel with Miller's planet,

1117
01:04:42,943 --> 01:04:45,278
outside of this time shift,
to here?

1118
01:04:45,311 --> 01:04:46,780
Then we take the Ranger down,

1119
01:04:46,813 --> 01:04:48,382
we get Miller,
we get her samples.

1120
01:04:48,415 --> 01:04:49,950
We come back,
we analyze, we debrief.

1121
01:04:49,983 --> 01:04:51,351
We're in, we're out.

1122
01:04:51,385 --> 01:04:53,753
We lose a little fuel,
but we save a lot of time.

1123
01:04:53,787 --> 01:04:55,555
- That'll work.
- That's good.

1124
01:04:55,589 --> 01:04:56,966
There's not gonna be time
for monkey business

1125
01:04:56,990 --> 01:04:58,358
or chit-chat down there.

1126
01:04:58,392 --> 01:05:01,328
So, TARS, you should
definitely stay here.

1127
01:05:01,361 --> 01:05:03,964
CASE, you're with me.
Anyone else can stay.

1128
01:05:03,997 --> 01:05:05,932
If we're talking
about a couple years,

1129
01:05:05,965 --> 01:05:07,510
I could use the time
to research gravity.

1130
01:05:07,534 --> 01:05:09,169
Observations from the wormhole,

1131
01:05:09,202 --> 01:05:10,804
that's gold to Professor Brand.

1132
01:05:10,838 --> 01:05:12,539
TARS, factor an orbit
of Gargantua.

1133
01:05:12,572 --> 01:05:14,775
Conserve fuel,
minimize thrusting,

1134
01:05:14,808 --> 01:05:17,043
but make sure we stay
in range of Miller's planet.

1135
01:05:17,077 --> 01:05:18,378
You got it?

1136
01:05:18,411 --> 01:05:19,912
TARS: I wouldn't
leave you behind,

1137
01:05:19,946 --> 01:05:20,946
Dr. Brand.

1138
01:05:25,952 --> 01:05:27,287
- COOPER: You ready, CASE?
- Yup.

1139
01:05:28,354 --> 01:05:30,056
You don't say much, do you?

1140
01:05:30,089 --> 01:05:31,891
TARS talks plenty
for both of us.

1141
01:05:31,924 --> 01:05:32,893
(BEEPING)

1142
01:05:32,926 --> 01:05:33,926
Detach.

1143
01:05:41,701 --> 01:05:43,245
- (RATTLING)
- Romilly, are you reading these forces?

1144
01:05:43,269 --> 01:05:44,349
ROMILLY: It's unbelievable.

1145
01:05:47,808 --> 01:05:49,576
A literal heart of darkness.

1146
01:05:54,180 --> 01:05:56,984
If we could just see
the collapsed star inside

1147
01:05:57,017 --> 01:06:00,120
the singularity,
yeah, we'd solve gravity.

1148
01:06:00,153 --> 01:06:01,621
And we can't
get anything from it?

1149
01:06:01,654 --> 01:06:03,156
ROMILLY: Nothing
escapes that horizon.

1150
01:06:03,190 --> 01:06:05,124
Not even light.

1151
01:06:05,158 --> 01:06:07,060
Oh, the answer's there,
just no way to see it.

1152
01:06:07,093 --> 01:06:08,328
There's Miller's planet.

1153
01:06:11,197 --> 01:06:12,465
Good-bye, Ranger.

1154
01:06:25,545 --> 01:06:27,512
CASE: This is fast
for atmospheric entry.

1155
01:06:27,547 --> 01:06:28,891
Should we use
the thrusters to slow?

1156
01:06:28,915 --> 01:06:30,750
No.

1157
01:06:30,784 --> 01:06:32,619
No, I'm gonna use
the Ranger's aerodynamics

1158
01:06:32,652 --> 01:06:33,987
to save some fuel.

1159
01:06:34,021 --> 01:06:35,354
CASE: Air brake?

1160
01:06:35,388 --> 01:06:36,665
We want to get down fast,
don't we?

1161
01:06:36,689 --> 01:06:38,592
Actually, we want to
get there in one piece.

1162
01:06:38,958 --> 01:06:40,226
Hang on.

1163
01:06:40,260 --> 01:06:41,828
CASE: Brand, Doyle, get ready.

1164
01:06:48,668 --> 01:06:49,970
(PANTING)

1165
01:06:51,137 --> 01:06:52,573
(BEEPING)

1166
01:06:58,078 --> 01:06:59,379
CASE: We should ease!

1167
01:06:59,412 --> 01:07:00,489
COOPER: Hands where I can
see 'em, CASE.

1168
01:07:00,513 --> 01:07:01,814
The only time I ever went down

1169
01:07:01,848 --> 01:07:04,317
was when a machine was
easing at the wrong time.

1170
01:07:04,350 --> 01:07:05,862
- CASE: A little caution...
- Can get you killed,

1171
01:07:05,886 --> 01:07:07,186
Just like reckless driving.

1172
01:07:07,220 --> 01:07:08,264
DOYLE: Cooper,
it's too damn fast!

1173
01:07:08,288 --> 01:07:09,456
I got this.

1174
01:07:14,494 --> 01:07:15,872
CASE: Should I disable
the feedback?

1175
01:07:15,896 --> 01:07:17,831
No. No,
I need to feel the air.

1176
01:07:22,269 --> 01:07:23,470
Here we go.

1177
01:07:26,372 --> 01:07:27,608
DOYLE: It's just water!

1178
01:07:28,007 --> 01:07:29,175
(PANTING)

1179
01:07:29,209 --> 01:07:30,611
The stuff of life.

1180
01:07:31,244 --> 01:07:32,979
CASE: 1,200 meters.

1181
01:07:33,012 --> 01:07:34,280
Do we have a fix on the beacon?

1182
01:07:34,314 --> 01:07:36,049
CASE: Got it!
Can you maneuver?

1183
01:07:36,082 --> 01:07:38,051
I'm gonna need to
shave some speed.

1184
01:07:38,084 --> 01:07:39,362
I'm gonna spiral down
on top of it.

1185
01:07:39,386 --> 01:07:40,386
Everybody hang on!

1186
01:07:42,822 --> 01:07:43,822
CASE: 700.

1187
01:07:46,126 --> 01:07:47,861
On my cue, CASE. On my cue.

1188
01:07:51,698 --> 01:07:52,866
CASE: 500 meters.

1189
01:07:55,902 --> 01:07:57,504
(BRAND PANTING)

1190
01:08:02,476 --> 01:08:03,477
Fire!

1191
01:08:17,090 --> 01:08:18,090
Very graceful.

1192
01:08:18,191 --> 01:08:19,293
No.

1193
01:08:20,059 --> 01:08:21,894
But very... Efficient.

1194
01:08:24,798 --> 01:08:26,933
What are you waiting for?
Let's go!

1195
01:08:26,965 --> 01:08:29,169
Go, go, go, go, go!

1196
01:08:29,202 --> 01:08:31,003
Seven years per hour here.

1197
01:08:31,037 --> 01:08:32,306
Let's make it count!

1198
01:08:46,820 --> 01:08:48,088
(BRAND PANTING)

1199
01:08:58,764 --> 01:08:59,764
CASE: This way.

1200
01:09:02,769 --> 01:09:04,404
About 200 meters.

1201
01:09:14,146 --> 01:09:15,581
The gravity's punishing.

1202
01:09:16,782 --> 01:09:19,017
Been floating through space
too long?

1203
01:09:19,050 --> 01:09:20,754
CASE: 130% Earth gravity.

1204
01:09:21,220 --> 01:09:22,923
Come on.

1205
01:09:22,956 --> 01:09:24,796
- (BRAND GRUNTING ON RADIO)
- Come on, come on.

1206
01:09:26,059 --> 01:09:27,393
There's nothing here.

1207
01:09:27,427 --> 01:09:28,594
CASE: Should be right here.

1208
01:09:30,664 --> 01:09:33,500
If the signal's coming
from here...

1209
01:09:43,143 --> 01:09:44,143
Her beacon.

1210
01:09:52,519 --> 01:09:53,620
DOYLE: Wreckage.

1211
01:09:54,387 --> 01:09:55,455
Where's the rest?

1212
01:09:56,188 --> 01:09:57,490
BRAND: Towards the mountains!

1213
01:10:01,294 --> 01:10:02,929
Those aren't mountains.

1214
01:10:04,964 --> 01:10:06,265
They're waves.

1215
01:10:06,299 --> 01:10:07,768
What? What?

1216
01:10:11,604 --> 01:10:14,874
Oh, shit. Oh, shit. Oh, shit.

1217
01:10:14,908 --> 01:10:16,575
COOPER: That one's
moving away from us.

1218
01:10:23,383 --> 01:10:24,785
BRAND: We need the recorder.

1219
01:10:35,295 --> 01:10:37,697
Brand, Doyle,
back to the Ranger now!

1220
01:10:37,730 --> 01:10:41,034
BRAND: We're not leaving
without her data.

1221
01:10:41,067 --> 01:10:42,402
COOPER: Get back here now!

1222
01:10:42,435 --> 01:10:44,303
We do not have time!

1223
01:10:44,337 --> 01:10:45,538
A second wave is coming!

1224
01:10:45,571 --> 01:10:46,811
We're in the middle of a swell.

1225
01:10:48,207 --> 01:10:49,775
BRAND: No, I got it.

1226
01:10:49,809 --> 01:10:51,645
Get your ass
back to the Ranger, now!

1227
01:10:52,145 --> 01:10:53,647
(BRAND GRUNTING)

1228
01:10:56,716 --> 01:10:58,084
Brand, get back here, now!

1229
01:10:58,918 --> 01:11:00,987
(GASPS)

1230
01:11:01,021 --> 01:11:03,021
BRAND: No, Cooper, go.
Cooper, go. I can't make it.

1231
01:11:03,156 --> 01:11:04,291
Go!

1232
01:11:04,324 --> 01:11:05,324
CASE, go get her.

1233
01:11:10,630 --> 01:11:11,597
Go!

1234
01:11:11,631 --> 01:11:12,631
Get up! Get up, Brand!

1235
01:11:13,499 --> 01:11:14,868
DOYLE: Go, go! Go!

1236
01:11:16,336 --> 01:11:17,536
I'm not gonna make it!

1237
01:11:17,570 --> 01:11:19,105
Yes, you are. Yes, you are!

1238
01:11:23,008 --> 01:11:24,211
(GRUNTING)

1239
01:11:26,646 --> 01:11:28,515
Come on, CASE has her!
Get back here, Doyle!

1240
01:11:30,282 --> 01:11:31,417
(BRAND CONTINUES GRUNTING)

1241
01:11:31,451 --> 01:11:32,486
Come on, Brand!

1242
01:11:35,288 --> 01:11:36,288
Get to the hatch!

1243
01:11:38,124 --> 01:11:39,493
(PANTING)

1244
01:11:41,127 --> 01:11:42,596
Go, go! Go!

1245
01:11:44,964 --> 01:11:45,964
(BEEPING)

1246
01:11:48,367 --> 01:11:50,203
COOPER: Shit.

1247
01:11:50,236 --> 01:11:51,705
Manually overriding
inside hatch!

1248
01:11:55,341 --> 01:11:56,341
Cooper! Wait!

1249
01:11:57,510 --> 01:11:59,646
Cooper, wait! Wait! Stop it!

1250
01:12:03,950 --> 01:12:05,251
COOPER: The engines
are flooded!

1251
01:12:05,284 --> 01:12:07,287
I'm gonna have to shut her down.

1252
01:12:12,091 --> 01:12:13,226
(BRAND SCREAMING)

1253
01:12:14,193 --> 01:12:15,193
(GRUNTS)

1254
01:12:32,912 --> 01:12:34,648
(BRAND GASPS)

1255
01:12:38,250 --> 01:12:39,250
(GASPING)

1256
01:12:40,953 --> 01:12:41,953
Holy shit.

1257
01:12:46,893 --> 01:12:48,133
- Hang on!
- (CONTINUES GASPING)

1258
01:12:52,532 --> 01:12:53,867
(SCREAMING)

1259
01:12:56,068 --> 01:12:57,137
(GRUNTS)

1260
01:13:00,506 --> 01:13:01,807
(BOTH PANTING)

1261
01:13:19,359 --> 01:13:20,825
CASE, what's the problem?

1262
01:13:20,860 --> 01:13:22,929
CASE: Too waterlogged.
Let it drain.

1263
01:13:24,097 --> 01:13:25,664
God damn it!

1264
01:13:25,698 --> 01:13:26,866
I told you to leave me!

1265
01:13:26,867 --> 01:13:28,034
And I told you...

1266
01:13:28,068 --> 01:13:29,252
Why didn't you leave me?

1267
01:13:29,253 --> 01:13:30,436
To get your ass back here!

1268
01:13:30,470 --> 01:13:31,705
The difference is one of us

1269
01:13:31,738 --> 01:13:32,815
was thinking
about the mission, Brand!

1270
01:13:32,839 --> 01:13:34,941
You were thinking about
getting home.

1271
01:13:36,976 --> 01:13:39,445
I was trying to do
the right thing!

1272
01:13:39,479 --> 01:13:41,114
Can you tell that to Doyle?

1273
01:13:41,447 --> 01:13:43,382
(GASPING)

1274
01:13:43,416 --> 01:13:44,526
COOPER: CASE, how much time?

1275
01:13:44,550 --> 01:13:45,685
45 to an hour.

1276
01:13:46,052 --> 01:13:47,686
(GASPS)

1277
01:13:47,720 --> 01:13:48,920
COOPER:
The stuff of life, huh?

1278
01:13:49,923 --> 01:13:51,203
What's this gonna
cost us, Brand?

1279
01:13:52,158 --> 01:13:53,994
A lot. Decades.

1280
01:13:58,531 --> 01:13:59,833
(GROANS)

1281
01:14:01,501 --> 01:14:02,669
What happened to Miller?

1282
01:14:03,636 --> 01:14:05,838
Judging by the wreckage,

1283
01:14:05,871 --> 01:14:08,375
she was broken up by a wave
soon after impact.

1284
01:14:09,476 --> 01:14:10,753
How's the wreckage
stayed together

1285
01:14:10,777 --> 01:14:11,878
after all these years, huh?

1286
01:14:13,412 --> 01:14:15,115
Because of the time slippage.

1287
01:14:16,650 --> 01:14:20,754
On this planet's time,
she just landed hours ago.

1288
01:14:21,921 --> 01:14:24,490
She probably just died
minutes ago.

1289
01:14:24,524 --> 01:14:26,769
CASE: The data Doyle received
was just the initial status,

1290
01:14:26,793 --> 01:14:28,794
echoing endlessly.

1291
01:14:28,828 --> 01:14:30,129
Oh, we are not
prepared for this.

1292
01:14:33,533 --> 01:14:37,035
You eggheads have the survival
skills of a Boy Scout troop.

1293
01:14:37,070 --> 01:14:38,771
Well, we got this far
on our brains,

1294
01:14:38,804 --> 01:14:40,506
farther than any human
in history.

1295
01:14:40,540 --> 01:14:42,408
Well, not far enough!

1296
01:14:42,442 --> 01:14:43,909
And now we're stuck here

1297
01:14:43,943 --> 01:14:45,863
till there won't be anyone
left on Earth to save.

1298
01:14:49,048 --> 01:14:51,184
I'm counting every minute,
same as you, Cooper.

1299
01:14:56,422 --> 01:14:57,891
Is there any possibility...

1300
01:14:58,357 --> 01:14:59,859
I don't know...

1301
01:14:59,892 --> 01:15:02,161
Some kind of way we can maybe
all jump in a black hole?

1302
01:15:02,194 --> 01:15:03,263
Gain back the years?

1303
01:15:03,296 --> 01:15:04,564
(SCOFFS)

1304
01:15:04,597 --> 01:15:06,399
Don't shake your head at me.

1305
01:15:06,432 --> 01:15:08,435
Time is relative, okay?

1306
01:15:08,468 --> 01:15:11,071
It can stretch
and it can squeeze, but

1307
01:15:11,971 --> 01:15:14,406
it can't run backwards.
It just can't.

1308
01:15:14,440 --> 01:15:17,476
The only thing that can move
across dimensions, like time,

1309
01:15:17,510 --> 01:15:18,510
is gravity.

1310
01:15:21,147 --> 01:15:22,182
Okay.

1311
01:15:24,750 --> 01:15:28,721
The beings that led us here,
they communicate

1312
01:15:28,754 --> 01:15:29,822
through gravity, right?

1313
01:15:29,823 --> 01:15:30,890
(WHISPERS) Yes.

1314
01:15:30,923 --> 01:15:32,643
Could they be talking to us
from the future?

1315
01:15:33,493 --> 01:15:34,759
Maybe.

1316
01:15:34,793 --> 01:15:35,795
Okay. If they can...

1317
01:15:37,196 --> 01:15:40,900
"They" are beings
of five dimensions.

1318
01:15:40,933 --> 01:15:43,903
To them, time might be
another physical dimension.

1319
01:15:44,203 --> 01:15:45,937
To them,

1320
01:15:45,971 --> 01:15:47,906
the past might be a canyon

1321
01:15:47,940 --> 01:15:50,576
that they can climb into
and the future,

1322
01:15:50,610 --> 01:15:53,246
a mountain they can climb up.
But to us, it's not, okay?

1323
01:15:54,780 --> 01:15:56,916
Look, Cooper, I screwed up.
I'm sorry.

1324
01:15:59,352 --> 01:16:01,053
But you knew about relativity.

1325
01:16:01,087 --> 01:16:02,087
Oh...

1326
01:16:04,090 --> 01:16:05,125
Brand...

1327
01:16:05,825 --> 01:16:07,193
(INHALES DEEPLY)

1328
01:16:10,396 --> 01:16:12,965
My daughter was 10 years old.

1329
01:16:12,998 --> 01:16:14,209
I couldn't teach her
Einstein's theories

1330
01:16:14,233 --> 01:16:16,235
before I left.

1331
01:16:16,269 --> 01:16:18,629
Couldn't you have told her you
were going to save the world?

1332
01:16:19,238 --> 01:16:20,238
No.

1333
01:16:21,974 --> 01:16:24,410
When you become a parent,

1334
01:16:24,444 --> 01:16:25,684
one thing becomes really clear.

1335
01:16:27,914 --> 01:16:29,024
And that is that
you want to make sure

1336
01:16:29,048 --> 01:16:30,283
your children feel safe.

1337
01:16:32,118 --> 01:16:34,020
And it rules out
telling a 10-year-old

1338
01:16:34,053 --> 01:16:35,488
that the world is ending.

1339
01:16:37,723 --> 01:16:38,723
CASE: Cooper?

1340
01:16:39,458 --> 01:16:41,161
(RUMBLING FROM OUTSIDE)

1341
01:16:43,462 --> 01:16:44,507
How long for the engines, CASE?

1342
01:16:44,531 --> 01:16:45,698
A minute or two.

1343
01:16:45,731 --> 01:16:46,842
COOPER: Well,
we don't have it.

1344
01:16:46,866 --> 01:16:48,001
Helmets on!

1345
01:16:51,937 --> 01:16:54,073
Brand, co-pilot, you're up.

1346
01:16:54,106 --> 01:16:56,675
CASE, blow the cabin oxygen
through the main thrusters!

1347
01:16:56,709 --> 01:16:58,611
- We're gonna spark it.
- Roger that.

1348
01:16:58,644 --> 01:16:59,846
- Locked.
- Depressurizing.

1349
01:17:06,051 --> 01:17:07,491
- Engines up!
- (ENGINES POWERING UP)

1350
01:17:35,882 --> 01:17:37,350
Hello, Rom.

1351
01:17:37,950 --> 01:17:39,452
I've waited years.

1352
01:17:40,786 --> 01:17:42,355
How many...
How many years?

1353
01:17:44,523 --> 01:17:45,858
ROMILLY: By now it must be...

1354
01:17:45,891 --> 01:17:49,094
TARS: 23 years,
four months, eight days.

1355
01:17:53,466 --> 01:17:54,466
Doyle?

1356
01:18:01,273 --> 01:18:03,977
I thought I was prepared.
I knew the theory.

1357
01:18:05,645 --> 01:18:06,845
(WHISPERS)
Reality's different.

1358
01:18:07,813 --> 01:18:08,915
ROMILLY: And Miller?

1359
01:18:10,850 --> 01:18:11,970
There's nothing here for us.

1360
01:18:15,688 --> 01:18:16,923
(SOFTLY)
Why didn't you sleep?

1361
01:18:17,957 --> 01:18:20,493
Oh, I had a couple of stretches.

1362
01:18:20,526 --> 01:18:22,662
But I stopped believing
you were coming back.

1363
01:18:22,695 --> 01:18:26,131
And something seemed wrong
about dreaming my life away.

1364
01:18:26,165 --> 01:18:29,835
I learned what I could
from the black hole,

1365
01:18:29,869 --> 01:18:32,271
but I couldn't send anything
to your father.

1366
01:18:32,304 --> 01:18:34,573
We've been receiving,
but nothing gets out.

1367
01:18:34,606 --> 01:18:35,641
BRAND: Is he alive?

1368
01:18:35,674 --> 01:18:36,642
Oh, yeah.

1369
01:18:36,676 --> 01:18:37,776
Yeah?

1370
01:18:37,810 --> 01:18:38,977
Yeah.

1371
01:18:42,147 --> 01:18:44,851
ROMILLY: We've got years
of messages stored.

1372
01:18:44,884 --> 01:18:46,619
Cooper.

1373
01:18:46,652 --> 01:18:49,389
MALE AUTOMATED VOICE:
Messages span 23 years.

1374
01:18:51,724 --> 01:18:53,159
Play it from the beginning.

1375
01:18:56,429 --> 01:18:58,031
YOUNG TOM: Hey, Dad.

1376
01:18:58,898 --> 01:19:01,167
Checking in. Saying hi.

1377
01:19:02,234 --> 01:19:03,234
Um...

1378
01:19:04,136 --> 01:19:05,571
Finished second in school.

1379
01:19:07,607 --> 01:19:10,242
Miss Kurling's
still giving me C's though.

1380
01:19:10,276 --> 01:19:12,712
Pulled me down,
but second's not bad.

1381
01:19:14,013 --> 01:19:16,049
Grandpa attended the ceremony.

1382
01:19:17,583 --> 01:19:18,817
Um...

1383
01:19:18,851 --> 01:19:19,986
Oh.

1384
01:19:20,920 --> 01:19:22,754
I met another girl, Dad.

1385
01:19:22,788 --> 01:19:24,057
I, uh...

1386
01:19:25,324 --> 01:19:27,192
I really think this is the one.

1387
01:19:28,661 --> 01:19:31,330
Name's Lois.
That's her right there.

1388
01:19:31,364 --> 01:19:32,598
(COOPER SOBBING)

1389
01:19:34,166 --> 01:19:36,035
Murphy stole Grandpa's car.

1390
01:19:37,169 --> 01:19:39,439
She crashed it.
She's okay, though.

1391
01:19:39,972 --> 01:19:41,074
Hey, Dad.

1392
01:19:42,375 --> 01:19:43,443
Look at this!

1393
01:19:44,543 --> 01:19:45,712
You're a grandpa.

1394
01:19:47,246 --> 01:19:48,748
His name's Jesse.

1395
01:19:49,748 --> 01:19:51,250
I wanted to call him Coop,

1396
01:19:51,284 --> 01:19:55,254
but Lois says, uh,
maybe next time.

1397
01:19:55,287 --> 01:19:57,065
Donald says he's already
earned the "great" part,

1398
01:19:57,089 --> 01:19:59,225
so we just leave it at that.

1399
01:20:01,093 --> 01:20:02,428
Just hold him.

1400
01:20:02,462 --> 01:20:03,696
(JESSE GURGLING)

1401
01:20:03,729 --> 01:20:05,097
LOIS: Oh, dear.

1402
01:20:05,131 --> 01:20:07,298
Say "Bye-bye, Grandpa."

1403
01:20:07,333 --> 01:20:09,402
- Bye-bye, Grandpa. It's okay.
- (JESSE FUSSING)

1404
01:20:09,435 --> 01:20:11,637
Sorry it's been a while.
It's, uh...

1405
01:20:13,406 --> 01:20:14,406
(SOFTLY) Just...

1406
01:20:16,642 --> 01:20:18,378
What with Jesse and all.

1407
01:20:21,546 --> 01:20:22,548
Uh...

1408
01:20:25,084 --> 01:20:28,121
Grandpa died last week.

1409
01:20:28,154 --> 01:20:30,656
We buried him out in the
back forty next to Mom and...

1410
01:20:31,623 --> 01:20:32,623
Jesse.

1411
01:20:34,126 --> 01:20:36,596
Which is where we would have
buried you if you'd ever

1412
01:20:37,529 --> 01:20:38,798
come back.

1413
01:20:40,532 --> 01:20:43,669
Murph was there at the funeral.

1414
01:20:43,703 --> 01:20:46,138
We don't see her that much,
but she came for that.

1415
01:20:49,541 --> 01:20:51,611
You aren't listening to this,
I know that.

1416
01:20:55,081 --> 01:20:57,550
All these messages
are just, like,

1417
01:20:59,051 --> 01:21:02,422
drifting out there
in the darkness.

1418
01:21:03,722 --> 01:21:05,725
Lois says that, uh,

1419
01:21:06,825 --> 01:21:09,362
I have to let you go.

1420
01:21:09,828 --> 01:21:11,531
And, uh...

1421
01:21:11,963 --> 01:21:13,066
So...

1422
01:21:16,735 --> 01:21:19,472
I guess I'm letting you go.

1423
01:21:20,907 --> 01:21:23,909
I don't know where you are, Dad,

1424
01:21:23,942 --> 01:21:26,379
but I hope
that you're at peace and...

1425
01:21:28,180 --> 01:21:29,281
Good-bye.

1426
01:21:42,928 --> 01:21:44,163
Hey, Dad.

1427
01:21:47,066 --> 01:21:48,334
(WHISPERS) Hey, Murph.

1428
01:21:48,367 --> 01:21:50,236
You son of a bitch.

1429
01:21:54,373 --> 01:21:57,042
I never made one of these
when you were still responding

1430
01:21:57,075 --> 01:21:58,811
because I was so mad at you
for leaving.

1431
01:22:02,181 --> 01:22:04,116
And then when you went quiet,

1432
01:22:07,186 --> 01:22:08,564
it seemed like I should
live with that decision.

1433
01:22:08,588 --> 01:22:09,588
And I have.

1434
01:22:14,159 --> 01:22:16,429
But today's my birthday.

1435
01:22:20,432 --> 01:22:23,436
And it's a special one,
because you told me...

1436
01:22:23,469 --> 01:22:24,537
(SIGHS)

1437
01:22:27,673 --> 01:22:29,975
You once told me that
when you came back,

1438
01:22:30,008 --> 01:22:31,677
we might be the same age.

1439
01:22:33,712 --> 01:22:36,714
And today I'm the age
you were when you left.

1440
01:22:36,748 --> 01:22:37,850
(SOBBING)

1441
01:22:39,852 --> 01:22:42,522
So it would be a real good
time for you to come back.

1442
01:22:46,359 --> 01:22:48,160
(SWITCHES CAMERA OFF)

1443
01:22:50,095 --> 01:22:51,397
(SNIFFLES)

1444
01:22:56,268 --> 01:22:58,404
I didn't mean to intrude.

1445
01:22:58,437 --> 01:23:01,240
It's just that I've never
seen you in here before.

1446
01:23:01,273 --> 01:23:03,242
I've never been in here before.

1447
01:23:05,410 --> 01:23:07,947
PROFESSOR BRAND:
I talk to Amelia all the time.

1448
01:23:08,713 --> 01:23:09,815
It helps.

1449
01:23:10,783 --> 01:23:12,017
I'm glad you've started.

1450
01:23:12,050 --> 01:23:13,953
MURPH: I haven't.

1451
01:23:13,986 --> 01:23:16,388
I just had something
I needed to get out.

1452
01:23:16,422 --> 01:23:17,799
PROFESSOR BRAND: I know
they're still out there.

1453
01:23:17,823 --> 01:23:19,324
MURPH: I know.

1454
01:23:19,357 --> 01:23:21,927
There are so many reasons
their communications

1455
01:23:21,960 --> 01:23:23,120
might not be getting through.

1456
01:23:23,662 --> 01:23:24,662
I know, Professor.

1457
01:23:25,564 --> 01:23:28,234
I'm not sure
what I'm more afraid of.

1458
01:23:29,702 --> 01:23:31,704
Them never coming back,

1459
01:23:33,238 --> 01:23:36,240
or coming back
to find we've failed.

1460
01:23:36,275 --> 01:23:37,476
Then let's succeed.

1461
01:23:38,778 --> 01:23:39,778
So...

1462
01:23:40,512 --> 01:23:42,648
Back to the fourth iteration.

1463
01:23:42,681 --> 01:23:44,950
Let's run it through
some new fields.

1464
01:23:44,983 --> 01:23:46,352
With respect, Professor,

1465
01:23:46,385 --> 01:23:48,420
we've tried that
hundreds of times.

1466
01:23:48,454 --> 01:23:51,824
It only has to work once, Murph.

1467
01:23:55,594 --> 01:23:59,532
Every rivet that
they strike could
have been a bullet.

1468
01:23:59,565 --> 01:24:01,633
We've done well
for the world here,

1469
01:24:01,667 --> 01:24:04,002
whether or not
we crack the equation

1470
01:24:04,035 --> 01:24:06,539
before I kick the bucket.

1471
01:24:06,572 --> 01:24:08,073
Don't be morbid, Professor.

1472
01:24:08,106 --> 01:24:09,275
I'm not afraid of death.

1473
01:24:10,142 --> 01:24:11,744
I'm an old physicist.

1474
01:24:13,145 --> 01:24:14,680
I'm afraid of time.

1475
01:24:22,021 --> 01:24:23,021
MURPH: Time.

1476
01:24:25,224 --> 01:24:26,726
You're afraid of time.

1477
01:24:29,662 --> 01:24:31,663
For years, we've been
trying to solve the equation

1478
01:24:31,697 --> 01:24:32,874
without changing
the underlying assumption

1479
01:24:32,898 --> 01:24:34,400
about time.

1480
01:24:34,433 --> 01:24:36,401
- And?
- And that means

1481
01:24:36,435 --> 01:24:41,140
Each iteration is an attempt
to prove its own proof.

1482
01:24:41,173 --> 01:24:43,275
It's recursive.
It's nonsensical.

1483
01:24:43,309 --> 01:24:45,277
Are you calling my life's work

1484
01:24:45,311 --> 01:24:47,346
nonsense, Murph?

1485
01:24:47,379 --> 01:24:49,214
No, I'm saying
you've been trying to

1486
01:24:49,247 --> 01:24:50,481
finish it with one arm...

1487
01:24:50,515 --> 01:24:52,884
No, with both arms
tied behind your back.

1488
01:24:55,320 --> 01:24:57,056
And I don't understand why.

1489
01:24:58,257 --> 01:24:59,892
I'm an old man, Murph.

1490
01:25:01,227 --> 01:25:03,962
Can we take this point up
at another time?

1491
01:25:03,995 --> 01:25:05,765
I want to talk to my daughter.

1492
01:25:08,434 --> 01:25:11,003
PROFESSOR BRAND: Stepping out
into the universe,

1493
01:25:11,037 --> 01:25:14,407
we must confront the reality
of interstellar travel.

1494
01:25:15,607 --> 01:25:20,546
We must reach far beyond
our own lifespans.

1495
01:25:20,579 --> 01:25:25,051
We must think not as
individuals but as a species.

1496
01:25:28,254 --> 01:25:31,424
"Do not go gentle
into that good night."

1497
01:25:33,225 --> 01:25:34,493
COOPER: TARS
kept the Endurance

1498
01:25:34,526 --> 01:25:35,894
right where we needed her.

1499
01:25:35,927 --> 01:25:38,997
But the trip took years longer
than we anticipated.

1500
01:25:39,030 --> 01:25:42,067
We no longer have the fuel
to visit both prospects, so...

1501
01:25:42,735 --> 01:25:43,936
We have to choose.

1502
01:25:45,237 --> 01:25:46,372
But how?

1503
01:25:47,505 --> 01:25:48,974
They're both promising.

1504
01:25:50,642 --> 01:25:52,545
Edmunds' data is better,

1505
01:25:52,578 --> 01:25:55,481
but Dr. Mann is the one
still transmitting.

1506
01:25:55,514 --> 01:25:56,648
We've no reason to suspect

1507
01:25:56,681 --> 01:25:58,084
Edmunds' data would have soured.

1508
01:25:59,585 --> 01:26:02,020
His world has key elements
to sustain human life.

1509
01:26:02,054 --> 01:26:03,455
As does Dr. Mann's.

1510
01:26:03,488 --> 01:26:04,990
Cooper, this is my field.

1511
01:26:06,225 --> 01:26:07,225
And...

1512
01:26:08,527 --> 01:26:10,496
I really believe Edmunds'
is the better prospect.

1513
01:26:10,529 --> 01:26:11,864
Why?

1514
01:26:11,897 --> 01:26:13,132
Gargantua, that's why.

1515
01:26:15,200 --> 01:26:19,204
Look at Miller's planet.
Hydrocarbons, organics, yes.

1516
01:26:19,238 --> 01:26:22,406
But no life. Sterile.

1517
01:26:22,440 --> 01:26:23,840
We'll find the same thing
on Mann's.

1518
01:26:24,109 --> 01:26:26,044
Because of the black hole?

1519
01:26:26,078 --> 01:26:27,212
BRAND: Murphy's Law.

1520
01:26:27,246 --> 01:26:29,515
Whatever can happen will happen.

1521
01:26:29,548 --> 01:26:31,816
Accident is the first
building block of evolution.

1522
01:26:31,850 --> 01:26:33,161
But when you're orbiting
a black hole,

1523
01:26:33,185 --> 01:26:34,753
not enough can happen.

1524
01:26:34,786 --> 01:26:37,389
It sucks in asteroids
and comets,

1525
01:26:37,422 --> 01:26:39,458
other events which would
otherwise reach you.

1526
01:26:39,491 --> 01:26:41,026
We need to go further afield.

1527
01:26:41,994 --> 01:26:43,963
You once said that Dr. Mann

1528
01:26:45,430 --> 01:26:47,199
was the best of us.

1529
01:26:47,232 --> 01:26:49,068
He's remarkable.

1530
01:26:49,101 --> 01:26:50,341
We're only here because of him.

1531
01:26:51,036 --> 01:26:53,004
And yet here he is.

1532
01:26:53,038 --> 01:26:54,640
He's on the ground,

1533
01:26:54,673 --> 01:26:57,209
and he's sending a very
unambiguous message,

1534
01:26:57,242 --> 01:27:00,045
telling us to
come to his planet.

1535
01:27:00,079 --> 01:27:04,483
Granted, but Edmunds' data
is more promising.

1536
01:27:05,084 --> 01:27:06,184
We should vote.

1537
01:27:06,217 --> 01:27:07,419
Well, if we're going to vote,

1538
01:27:07,453 --> 01:27:08,773
there's something
you should know.

1539
01:27:09,388 --> 01:27:10,923
Brand?

1540
01:27:10,956 --> 01:27:12,091
He has a right to know.

1541
01:27:13,158 --> 01:27:14,493
That has nothing to do with it.

1542
01:27:14,859 --> 01:27:16,195
What does?

1543
01:27:16,228 --> 01:27:18,063
She's in love with Wolf Edmunds.

1544
01:27:18,097 --> 01:27:19,164
ROMILLY: Is that true?

1545
01:27:19,197 --> 01:27:20,466
Yes.

1546
01:27:23,902 --> 01:27:26,205
And that makes me
want to follow my heart.

1547
01:27:29,708 --> 01:27:31,676
But maybe we've spent too long

1548
01:27:31,710 --> 01:27:33,545
trying to figure all this out
with theory.

1549
01:27:33,579 --> 01:27:35,213
You're a scientist, Brand.

1550
01:27:35,247 --> 01:27:36,582
So listen to me

1551
01:27:37,750 --> 01:27:41,219
when I say that love isn't
something we invented.

1552
01:27:41,253 --> 01:27:43,255
It's (SIGHS)

1553
01:27:43,289 --> 01:27:45,491
observable, powerful.

1554
01:27:47,659 --> 01:27:49,628
It has to mean something.

1555
01:27:49,661 --> 01:27:52,163
Love has meaning, yes.
Social utility,

1556
01:27:52,197 --> 01:27:54,033
social bonding, child rearing...

1557
01:27:54,066 --> 01:27:56,168
We love people who have died.

1558
01:27:56,202 --> 01:27:57,562
Where's the social utility
in that?

1559
01:27:58,270 --> 01:27:59,704
None.

1560
01:27:59,738 --> 01:28:03,307
Maybe it means something more,
something we can't

1561
01:28:03,342 --> 01:28:05,744
yet understand.

1562
01:28:05,778 --> 01:28:08,848
Maybe it's some evidence,
some...

1563
01:28:10,315 --> 01:28:12,551
artifact of a higher dimension

1564
01:28:12,584 --> 01:28:14,786
that we can't
consciously perceive.

1565
01:28:14,819 --> 01:28:17,289
I'm drawn across the universe

1566
01:28:17,322 --> 01:28:19,624
to someone I haven't seen
in a decade,

1567
01:28:19,658 --> 01:28:22,928
who I know is probably dead.

1568
01:28:22,962 --> 01:28:26,498
Love is the one thing
we're capable of perceiving

1569
01:28:26,531 --> 01:28:28,934
that transcends dimensions
of time and space.

1570
01:28:31,236 --> 01:28:32,671
Maybe we should trust that,

1571
01:28:32,704 --> 01:28:34,607
even if we can't
understand it yet.

1572
01:28:40,378 --> 01:28:41,747
All right, Cooper...

1573
01:28:43,915 --> 01:28:44,950
Yes,

1574
01:28:46,818 --> 01:28:49,522
the tiniest possibility of
seeing Wolf again excites me.

1575
01:28:50,589 --> 01:28:51,957
That doesn't mean I'm wrong.

1576
01:28:52,991 --> 01:28:54,760
Honestly, Amelia,

1577
01:28:56,895 --> 01:28:57,895
it might.

1578
01:29:01,900 --> 01:29:02,900
(SOBS)

1579
01:29:04,970 --> 01:29:07,540
TARS, chart a course
for Dr. Mann's.

1580
01:29:24,790 --> 01:29:27,626
We'll lose about a third
again. But next year...

1581
01:29:27,660 --> 01:29:28,761
(CLICKS TONGUE)

1582
01:29:29,928 --> 01:29:31,529
Next year I'm gonna work
Nelson's farm

1583
01:29:31,563 --> 01:29:32,631
and I'll make it up.

1584
01:29:33,665 --> 01:29:35,134
What happened to Nelson?

1585
01:29:41,506 --> 01:29:42,717
LOIS: Murph,
have you eaten enough?

1586
01:29:42,741 --> 01:29:43,918
Would you like
some more souffle?

1587
01:29:43,942 --> 01:29:46,845
No, no. I'm full, thanks.
It was delicious.

1588
01:29:47,979 --> 01:29:49,815
Coop, finish your fritter,
please.

1589
01:29:52,250 --> 01:29:53,952
Will you spend the night?

1590
01:29:53,985 --> 01:29:56,254
Your room is exactly
as you left it. It's ready.

1591
01:29:56,287 --> 01:29:57,722
I need to get back.
(SNIFFLES)

1592
01:29:57,756 --> 01:29:58,833
LOIS: My sewing machine
is in there,

1593
01:29:58,857 --> 01:30:00,191
but there's plenty of...

1594
01:30:00,225 --> 01:30:01,259
I need to...

1595
01:30:04,363 --> 01:30:05,363
Too many memories.

1596
01:30:05,397 --> 01:30:06,698
TOM: Well...

1597
01:30:06,731 --> 01:30:08,300
We might have
something for that.

1598
01:30:08,333 --> 01:30:09,333
Hey, Coop.

1599
01:30:14,406 --> 01:30:16,175
(COOP COUGHING)

1600
01:30:17,108 --> 01:30:18,108
The dust.

1601
01:30:20,946 --> 01:30:22,380
Lois, I have a friend who...

1602
01:30:22,414 --> 01:30:23,848
(COOP COUGHING)

1603
01:30:23,882 --> 01:30:24,962
could look at his lungs.

1604
01:30:43,569 --> 01:30:44,803
COOPER: Amelia, I'm sorry.

1605
01:30:44,836 --> 01:30:46,305
You were just being objective.

1606
01:30:46,338 --> 01:30:47,773
Unless you're punishing me

1607
01:30:47,806 --> 01:30:49,975
for screwing up
on Miller's planet.

1608
01:30:50,008 --> 01:30:52,011
No, this wasn't
a personal decision.

1609
01:30:52,811 --> 01:30:54,145
If you're wrong,

1610
01:30:54,179 --> 01:30:57,148
you will have a very personal
decision to make.

1611
01:30:57,182 --> 01:31:00,552
Your fuel calculations are
based on a return journey.

1612
01:31:00,585 --> 01:31:02,721
Strike out on Mann's planet,

1613
01:31:02,754 --> 01:31:04,756
and we'll have to decide
whether to return home

1614
01:31:04,790 --> 01:31:07,259
or push on to Edmunds'
with Plan B.

1615
01:31:07,292 --> 01:31:11,296
Starting a colony
could save us
from extinction.

1616
01:31:11,330 --> 01:31:12,731
You might have to decide between

1617
01:31:12,764 --> 01:31:14,565
seeing your children again

1618
01:31:14,599 --> 01:31:16,101
and the future
of the human race.

1619
01:31:17,836 --> 01:31:19,236
I trust you'll be
as objective then.

1620
01:31:26,277 --> 01:31:28,513
He's been asking for you
since he came to.

1621
01:31:28,546 --> 01:31:29,847
We were trying to reach you.

1622
01:31:32,784 --> 01:31:33,784
MURPH: (WHISPERS)
Hey.

1623
01:31:35,921 --> 01:31:36,921
Murph.

1624
01:31:37,922 --> 01:31:39,223
Hi. I'm here, Professor.

1625
01:31:40,325 --> 01:31:42,894
(WEAKLY) I let them all down.

1626
01:31:42,927 --> 01:31:46,031
No, you got us so far!
Real close.

1627
01:31:48,066 --> 01:31:50,102
I'll finish what you started.

1628
01:31:50,135 --> 01:31:52,037
Good, good, Murph.

1629
01:31:54,539 --> 01:31:56,475
You had faith

1630
01:31:58,110 --> 01:31:59,110
all those...

1631
01:32:00,379 --> 01:32:01,947
All those years.

1632
01:32:03,615 --> 01:32:04,717
I...

1633
01:32:05,350 --> 01:32:07,352
I asked you to have faith.

1634
01:32:09,521 --> 01:32:11,990
I wanted you to believe

1635
01:32:13,725 --> 01:32:15,360
that your father...

1636
01:32:18,663 --> 01:32:20,132
would come back.

1637
01:32:20,532 --> 01:32:21,734
I do, Professor.

1638
01:32:23,435 --> 01:32:24,837
Forgive me, Murph.

1639
01:32:25,737 --> 01:32:27,473
There's nothing to forgive.

1640
01:32:30,341 --> 01:32:31,341
I...

1641
01:32:32,077 --> 01:32:33,746
I lied, Murph.

1642
01:32:36,281 --> 01:32:37,883
I lied to you.

1643
01:32:44,422 --> 01:32:47,392
There was no need for him

1644
01:32:48,827 --> 01:32:50,395
to come back.

1645
01:32:53,565 --> 01:32:56,401
There is no...
No way to help us.

1646
01:32:57,735 --> 01:32:58,837
But Plan A...

1647
01:32:59,538 --> 01:33:02,406
All this. All these people.

1648
01:33:03,642 --> 01:33:05,277
And the equation.

1649
01:33:09,614 --> 01:33:11,116
Did my father know?

1650
01:33:15,220 --> 01:33:16,555
Did he leave me?

1651
01:33:20,625 --> 01:33:21,625
Do

1652
01:33:23,127 --> 01:33:24,163
Not

1653
01:33:25,130 --> 01:33:26,131
go

1654
01:33:27,732 --> 01:33:29,168
Gentle...

1655
01:33:31,402 --> 01:33:32,402
No.

1656
01:33:34,172 --> 01:33:35,172
No!

1657
01:33:36,408 --> 01:33:37,976
You can't leave.

1658
01:33:38,409 --> 01:33:39,444
You... No.

1659
01:33:41,079 --> 01:33:42,681
MURPH: Dr. Brand,
I'm sorry to tell

1660
01:33:42,714 --> 01:33:45,384
that your father died today.
He had no pain.

1661
01:33:45,918 --> 01:33:47,451
He was at peace.

1662
01:33:48,654 --> 01:33:50,522
I'm very sorry for your loss.
(SNIFFLES)

1663
01:34:03,001 --> 01:34:04,469
Brand, did you know?

1664
01:34:07,105 --> 01:34:08,574
He told you, right?

1665
01:34:09,274 --> 01:34:10,342
(BITTER LAUGH)

1666
01:34:11,776 --> 01:34:12,945
You knew.

1667
01:34:15,080 --> 01:34:16,548
This was all a sham.

1668
01:34:21,386 --> 01:34:23,422
You left us here.

1669
01:34:24,923 --> 01:34:26,325
To suffocate.

1670
01:34:28,626 --> 01:34:29,928
To starve.

1671
01:34:54,352 --> 01:34:55,587
(BEEPING)

1672
01:34:57,489 --> 01:34:58,522
COOPER: Frozen cloud.

1673
01:35:48,373 --> 01:35:49,708
(UNLOCKING)

1674
01:37:11,022 --> 01:37:12,524
(COUGHS)

1675
01:37:14,959 --> 01:37:16,528
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1676
01:37:19,397 --> 01:37:21,199
(SOBBING)

1677
01:37:23,000 --> 01:37:24,636
It's okay.

1678
01:37:24,669 --> 01:37:26,138
It's okay.

1679
01:37:32,810 --> 01:37:34,245
It's okay.

1680
01:37:39,917 --> 01:37:41,553
Pray you never learn

1681
01:37:43,288 --> 01:37:46,158
just how good it can be
to see another face.

1682
01:37:55,200 --> 01:37:57,635
I hadn't a lot of hope
to begin with, but...

1683
01:37:57,668 --> 01:37:59,538
After so long, I had none.

1684
01:38:01,539 --> 01:38:04,142
My supplies were
completely exhausted.

1685
01:38:06,411 --> 01:38:07,879
The last time I went to sleep,

1686
01:38:07,912 --> 01:38:09,714
I didn't even set a waking date.

1687
01:38:14,119 --> 01:38:16,321
You have literally
raised me from the dead.

1688
01:38:17,455 --> 01:38:18,857
- Lazarus.
- Hmm.

1689
01:38:20,725 --> 01:38:22,259
What about the others?

1690
01:38:22,293 --> 01:38:23,695
I'm afraid you're it, sir.

1691
01:38:24,629 --> 01:38:26,798
So far, surely.

1692
01:38:27,932 --> 01:38:30,935
No, our present situation
is that there's very little

1693
01:38:30,968 --> 01:38:32,404
chance of rescuing any others.

1694
01:38:36,340 --> 01:38:38,276
BRAND: Dr. Mann. Dr. Mann?

1695
01:38:39,644 --> 01:38:40,879
Tell us about your world.

1696
01:38:42,380 --> 01:38:43,380
(SNIFFLES)

1697
01:38:44,582 --> 01:38:46,218
Our world, we hope.

1698
01:38:50,288 --> 01:38:52,357
Our world, uh, is cold,

1699
01:38:52,824 --> 01:38:53,859
stark,

1700
01:38:55,926 --> 01:38:57,495
but undeniably beautiful.

1701
01:39:00,298 --> 01:39:03,235
The days are 67 hours long,
cold.

1702
01:39:07,539 --> 01:39:09,074
The nights are

1703
01:39:09,107 --> 01:39:11,309
67 far colder hours.

1704
01:39:17,616 --> 01:39:22,119
The gravity is a very, very
pleasant 80% of the Earth's.

1705
01:39:22,153 --> 01:39:25,389
Now, up here where I landed,
the water is alkali,

1706
01:39:25,423 --> 01:39:27,392
and the air has too much
ammonia in it to breathe

1707
01:39:27,425 --> 01:39:28,993
for more than
just a few minutes,

1708
01:39:29,026 --> 01:39:30,862
but down at the surface...

1709
01:39:30,895 --> 01:39:32,897
And there is a surface.

1710
01:39:33,798 --> 01:39:35,800
The chlorine dissipates.

1711
01:39:35,833 --> 01:39:38,036
The ammonia gives way
to crystalline hydrocarbons

1712
01:39:38,069 --> 01:39:39,337
and breathable air.

1713
01:39:39,771 --> 01:39:41,706
To organics.

1714
01:39:41,739 --> 01:39:43,607
Possibly, even to life.

1715
01:39:45,009 --> 01:39:47,378
We might be sharing this world.

1716
01:39:47,412 --> 01:39:49,580
These readings
are from the surface?

1717
01:39:49,613 --> 01:39:53,017
Over the years,
I've dropped various probes.

1718
01:39:53,050 --> 01:39:54,361
COOPER: How far
have you explored?

1719
01:39:54,385 --> 01:39:56,521
I've mounted
several major expeditions.

1720
01:39:56,554 --> 01:39:58,222
But with oxygen
in limited supply,

1721
01:39:58,256 --> 01:40:00,624
KIPP there really did
most of the legwork.

1722
01:40:00,659 --> 01:40:02,227
TARS: What went wrong
with him, sir?

1723
01:40:02,260 --> 01:40:03,661
DR. MANN: Degeneration.

1724
01:40:03,694 --> 01:40:05,696
He misidentified
the first organics we found

1725
01:40:05,730 --> 01:40:07,298
as ammonia crystals.

1726
01:40:07,332 --> 01:40:08,866
He struggled on for a time,

1727
01:40:08,900 --> 01:40:11,602
but ultimately
I decommissioned him

1728
01:40:11,636 --> 01:40:14,338
and used his power source
to keep the mission going.

1729
01:40:14,371 --> 01:40:17,008
I thought I was alone
before I shut him down!

1730
01:40:17,041 --> 01:40:18,561
TARS: Would you like me
to look at him?

1731
01:40:19,310 --> 01:40:22,180
No. No.
He needs a human touch.

1732
01:40:22,213 --> 01:40:24,382
TARS: Dr. Brand, CASE is
relaying a message for you

1733
01:40:24,416 --> 01:40:26,350
from the comm station.

1734
01:40:26,384 --> 01:40:28,220
Okay. Be right there.
Excuse me.

1735
01:40:40,965 --> 01:40:42,205
Dr. Brand,
I'm sorry to tell you

1736
01:40:42,233 --> 01:40:43,353
that your father died today.

1737
01:40:44,002 --> 01:40:45,402
He had no pain.

1738
01:40:48,807 --> 01:40:50,008
He was at peace.

1739
01:40:52,276 --> 01:40:53,812
I'm sorry for your loss.

1740
01:40:56,781 --> 01:40:57,781
BRAND: Is that Murph?

1741
01:40:58,315 --> 01:41:01,018
She's... She's grown.

1742
01:41:01,052 --> 01:41:02,420
MURPH: Brand, did you know?

1743
01:41:03,788 --> 01:41:05,290
He told you, right?

1744
01:41:05,890 --> 01:41:06,991
(BITTER LAUGH)

1745
01:41:08,259 --> 01:41:09,461
You knew.

1746
01:41:11,395 --> 01:41:12,763
This was all a sham.

1747
01:41:14,032 --> 01:41:15,533
You left us here.

1748
01:41:17,802 --> 01:41:19,037
To suffocate.

1749
01:41:21,305 --> 01:41:22,606
To starve.

1750
01:41:26,144 --> 01:41:27,612
Did my father know, too?

1751
01:41:30,215 --> 01:41:31,483
(SOBBING) Dad?

1752
01:41:33,518 --> 01:41:35,320
I just want to know

1753
01:41:36,855 --> 01:41:38,589
if you left me here to die.

1754
01:41:41,392 --> 01:41:43,328
I just have to know.

1755
01:41:44,061 --> 01:41:45,061
(CONTINUES SOBBING)

1756
01:41:49,000 --> 01:41:50,368
Cooper, my...

1757
01:41:51,969 --> 01:41:54,272
My father dedicated

1758
01:41:54,305 --> 01:41:56,373
his whole life to Plan A.

1759
01:41:56,407 --> 01:41:59,010
I have no idea
what she's talking about.

1760
01:42:00,812 --> 01:42:01,812
DR. MANN: I do.

1761
01:42:07,585 --> 01:42:09,754
He never even hoped to
get the people off the Earth?

1762
01:42:10,955 --> 01:42:11,955
No.

1763
01:42:16,461 --> 01:42:17,571
But he's been trying to solve

1764
01:42:17,595 --> 01:42:19,431
the gravity equation
for 40 years.

1765
01:42:20,965 --> 01:42:23,835
Amelia, your father
solved his equation
before I even left.

1766
01:42:25,002 --> 01:42:26,704
Then why wouldn't he use it?

1767
01:42:26,737 --> 01:42:28,740
The equation couldn't
reconcile relativity

1768
01:42:28,773 --> 01:42:30,875
with quantum mechanics.
You need more.

1769
01:42:30,909 --> 01:42:33,009
More? More what?

1770
01:42:33,043 --> 01:42:34,312
DR. MANN: More data.

1771
01:42:34,345 --> 01:42:36,247
You need to see
into a black hole.

1772
01:42:36,281 --> 01:42:38,349
The laws of nature prohibit
a naked singularity.

1773
01:42:38,383 --> 01:42:39,684
Romilly, is that true?

1774
01:42:41,252 --> 01:42:42,787
If a black hole is an oyster,

1775
01:42:42,820 --> 01:42:45,189
then the singularity's
the pearl inside.

1776
01:42:45,222 --> 01:42:47,925
The gravity's so strong,
it's always hidden
in darkness

1777
01:42:47,958 --> 01:42:49,127
behind the horizon.

1778
01:42:50,895 --> 01:42:53,129
That's why we call it
a black hole.

1779
01:42:53,163 --> 01:42:55,232
Okay, but (BREATHING HEAVILY)

1780
01:42:55,266 --> 01:42:56,506
if we see beyond the horizon...

1781
01:42:57,068 --> 01:42:59,036
We can't, Coop.

1782
01:42:59,070 --> 01:43:00,114
DR. MANN:
There are some things

1783
01:43:00,138 --> 01:43:01,539
that aren't meant to be known.

1784
01:43:01,572 --> 01:43:03,408
Your father had to
find another way

1785
01:43:03,441 --> 01:43:05,777
to save the human race
from extinction.

1786
01:43:05,810 --> 01:43:07,311
Plan B. A colony.

1787
01:43:07,344 --> 01:43:08,847
Why not tell people?

1788
01:43:10,681 --> 01:43:12,415
Why keep building
those damn stations?

1789
01:43:12,450 --> 01:43:13,885
Because he knew
how hard it would be

1790
01:43:13,918 --> 01:43:16,219
to get people to work together
to save the species

1791
01:43:16,254 --> 01:43:17,689
instead of themselves.

1792
01:43:18,222 --> 01:43:19,357
Or their children.

1793
01:43:19,390 --> 01:43:20,924
Bullshit.

1794
01:43:20,958 --> 01:43:22,469
You never would've come here
unless you believed

1795
01:43:22,493 --> 01:43:23,994
you were gonna save them.

1796
01:43:24,028 --> 01:43:26,230
Evolution has yet
to transcend
that simple barrier.

1797
01:43:26,263 --> 01:43:29,100
We can care deeply, selflessly

1798
01:43:29,133 --> 01:43:30,534
about those we know,

1799
01:43:30,567 --> 01:43:32,103
but that empathy rarely extends

1800
01:43:32,136 --> 01:43:33,303
beyond our line of sight.

1801
01:43:33,337 --> 01:43:34,906
But the lie.

1802
01:43:38,375 --> 01:43:40,478
That monstrous lie?

1803
01:43:41,846 --> 01:43:42,846
Unforgivable.

1804
01:43:43,347 --> 01:43:45,716
And he knew that.

1805
01:43:45,750 --> 01:43:47,752
He was prepared to
destroy his own humanity

1806
01:43:47,785 --> 01:43:50,120
in order to save the species.

1807
01:43:50,154 --> 01:43:51,298
He made an incredible sacrifice.

1808
01:43:51,322 --> 01:43:52,424
No.

1809
01:43:53,992 --> 01:43:56,427
No, an incredible sacrifice
is being made

1810
01:43:56,460 --> 01:43:58,696
by the people on Earth
who are gonna die!

1811
01:43:59,330 --> 01:44:02,132
Because in his arrogance

1812
01:44:02,166 --> 01:44:03,802
he declared their case hopeless.

1813
01:44:04,568 --> 01:44:05,937
I'm sorry, Cooper,

1814
01:44:06,604 --> 01:44:07,972
their case is hopeless.

1815
01:44:08,272 --> 01:44:10,008
No. No.

1816
01:44:11,008 --> 01:44:12,110
We are the future.

1817
01:44:16,247 --> 01:44:17,949
Cooper, what can I do?

1818
01:44:21,252 --> 01:44:23,687
Let me go home.

1819
01:44:23,721 --> 01:44:26,490
GETTY: You're
absolutely positive?

1820
01:44:26,524 --> 01:44:28,593
His solution was correct.
He'd had it for years.

1821
01:44:29,327 --> 01:44:30,662
It's worthless?

1822
01:44:30,695 --> 01:44:31,830
It's half the answer.

1823
01:44:33,231 --> 01:44:35,834
Okay. How do you find
the other half?

1824
01:44:36,634 --> 01:44:38,469
Out there? A black hole.

1825
01:44:38,502 --> 01:44:39,870
But stuck down here on Earth?

1826
01:44:39,904 --> 01:44:41,071
Yeah?

1827
01:44:42,606 --> 01:44:44,075
I'm not sure you can.

1828
01:44:46,443 --> 01:44:48,746
GETTY: God,
they just pack up and leave.

1829
01:44:50,447 --> 01:44:52,150
What are they hoping to find?

1830
01:44:52,916 --> 01:44:53,916
Survival.

1831
01:45:01,759 --> 01:45:02,759
Damn it.

1832
01:45:05,697 --> 01:45:07,031
Murph.

1833
01:45:07,064 --> 01:45:08,499
Don't... (SIGHS)

1834
01:45:08,533 --> 01:45:09,853
Don't people have
a right to know?

1835
01:45:10,234 --> 01:45:12,337
Well, panic won't help.

1836
01:45:12,370 --> 01:45:14,539
We just have to keep working,
same as ever.

1837
01:45:14,572 --> 01:45:16,574
Yeah. But isn't that exactly

1838
01:45:16,607 --> 01:45:17,984
what Professor Brand was
manipulating us to do?

1839
01:45:18,008 --> 01:45:19,376
Brand gave up on us.

1840
01:45:19,410 --> 01:45:21,012
I'm still trying to solve this.

1841
01:45:21,813 --> 01:45:22,813
So...

1842
01:45:24,348 --> 01:45:25,850
Do you have an idea?

1843
01:45:26,550 --> 01:45:27,886
A feeling.

1844
01:45:31,488 --> 01:45:33,156
I told you about my ghost.

1845
01:45:35,593 --> 01:45:37,795
My dad thought
I called it a ghost

1846
01:45:37,829 --> 01:45:39,297
because I was scared of it.

1847
01:45:43,200 --> 01:45:44,360
But I was never scared of it.

1848
01:45:46,804 --> 01:45:49,073
I called it a ghost
because it felt...

1849
01:45:51,676 --> 01:45:53,177
It felt like a person.

1850
01:45:56,013 --> 01:45:57,373
It was trying to
tell me something.

