123
00:17:43,897 --> 00:17:45,148
Pure.

124
00:18:04,376 --> 00:18:05,877
<i>Skol.</i>

125
00:18:09,464 --> 00:18:12,092
- One more.
- Make it two.

126
00:18:12,217 --> 00:18:15,804
A man this rich will buy
for a fellow outwater, I'm sure.

127
00:18:15,929 --> 00:18:17,306
One.

128
00:18:20,767 --> 00:18:24,146
That's an interesting pair of boots
you've got.

129
00:18:24,271 --> 00:18:26,857
- Trade?
- No.

130
00:18:26,982 --> 00:18:29,651
So how long you been out there, man?

131
00:18:33,238 --> 00:18:36,783
Don't hurt asking. Talking costs nothing.

132
00:18:44,166 --> 00:18:48,629
- Depends. What lunar is it?
- Well, let's see.

133
00:18:48,754 --> 00:18:51,965
April, March, June. It's August.

134
00:18:52,090 --> 00:18:54,635
- This August?
- Yep.

135
00:18:55,761 --> 00:18:57,054
So how long?

136
00:18:59,431 --> 00:19:02,434
- Fifteen.
- Fifteen lunars?

137
00:19:08,899 --> 00:19:10,067
(Whispers) That's her.

138
00:19:10,192 --> 00:19:12,653
Enola, hey, what are you doing?

139
00:19:13,278 --> 00:19:15,864
- No, you can't have that.
- I need another piece to draw some more.

140
00:19:15,989 --> 00:19:20,243
I'll get it. I'll give it to you.
Just stay in the back.

141
00:19:22,454 --> 00:19:25,123
With all those chits,
you could order up a bath.

142
00:19:25,248 --> 00:19:28,877
- Why are you talking to me?
- Just being friendly.

143
00:19:34,549 --> 00:19:36,843
- Is that a tomato plant?
- Yeah.

144
00:19:36,968 --> 00:19:41,264
- You have a keen eye.
- I saw one in a picture. How much?

145
00:19:47,437 --> 00:19:49,439
Half your chits.

146
00:20:01,076 --> 00:20:05,205
- I'll take them, too.
- Take what? You bought everything.

147
00:20:05,330 --> 00:20:07,207
I'll take them shelves.

148
00:20:09,584 --> 00:20:13,296
So, what did you see out there
in your 15 months?

149
00:20:13,422 --> 00:20:15,716
- Such as?
- An end to all this water.

150
00:20:15,841 --> 00:20:18,135
You're asking the wrong person.

151
00:20:19,428 --> 00:20:21,430
- The one they buried today.
- Uh-huh?

152
00:20:21,555 --> 00:20:23,765
She found the only end there is.

153
00:20:29,104 --> 00:20:31,106
I've got a proposition for you, Mariner.

154
00:20:31,231 --> 00:20:33,108
I'm not bargaining. I'm leaving.

155
00:20:33,233 --> 00:20:36,236
But you haven't even heard anything yet.
Or seen it.

156
00:20:40,282 --> 00:20:45,662
You may have noticed us burying a citizen
today. That makes room for one more.

157
00:20:47,664 --> 00:20:49,458
I'm not staying.

158
00:20:49,583 --> 00:20:52,544
Oh, we're not asking you to.
All we want is your seed.

159
00:20:52,669 --> 00:20:56,715
(Man) We can look to our own
for impregnation,

160
00:20:56,840 --> 00:21:01,803
but too much of that sort of thing gets...
undesirable.

161
00:21:01,928 --> 00:21:07,017
When she's pregnant, you go on your way
with all the supplies you need.

162
00:21:08,018 --> 00:21:11,229
You don't have anything. You're dying.

163
00:21:15,692 --> 00:21:20,489
No man stays out that long
and turns down a woman.

164
00:21:21,656 --> 00:21:23,658
He's hiding something.

165
00:21:23,784 --> 00:21:26,077
Maybe he's a Smoker spy.

166
00:21:28,163 --> 00:21:29,539
(Whistles)

167
00:21:36,379 --> 00:21:40,801
When the Elders say so, you can leave.
And not before.

168
00:21:59,402 --> 00:22:01,696
Ah. Gills.

169
00:22:03,573 --> 00:22:06,868
- Mutation!
- He's a Muto!

170
00:22:09,496 --> 00:22:11,206
(Grunting)

171
00:22:14,501 --> 00:22:15,585
Aaargh!

172
00:22:18,296 --> 00:22:20,257
(Man) Get him!

173
00:22:25,971 --> 00:22:27,264
(Man) Throw the nets!

174
00:22:46,283 --> 00:22:47,993
(Yelling)

175
00:22:51,830 --> 00:22:54,124
(Man) He's a murderer!

176
00:22:57,752 --> 00:22:59,129
Aargh!

177
00:22:59,880 --> 00:23:02,757
By what right?

178
00:23:04,134 --> 00:23:06,344
You pay me to keep the peace.

179
00:23:07,429 --> 00:23:10,974
- This isn't it.
- No! He has killed one of us.

180
00:23:11,099 --> 00:23:13,727
- He was defending himself.
- He needs to be destroyed!

181
00:23:13,852 --> 00:23:15,854
- Kill him!
- That may be.

182
00:23:15,979 --> 00:23:19,941
- Kill him!
- But not here, and not like this.

183
00:23:21,693 --> 00:23:23,737
(Metal gears turning)

184
00:23:51,890 --> 00:23:53,683
(Boy) What is it?

185
00:23:53,808 --> 00:23:55,769
Hey!

186
00:23:56,978 --> 00:24:00,148
(Man) Too tight! I can't get it off.

187
00:24:03,818 --> 00:24:05,195
(Man) Open the gate!

188
00:24:09,199 --> 00:24:10,867
(Chuckling)

189
00:24:25,215 --> 00:24:27,217
(People arguing)

190
00:24:28,218 --> 00:24:29,844
(Man) Order!

191
00:24:29,970 --> 00:24:32,555
This is another device we found
on the boat.

192
00:24:32,681 --> 00:24:36,977
A garrote cord for strangulation!

193
00:24:38,687 --> 00:24:41,523
We, we don't know what this is all about,

194
00:24:41,648 --> 00:24:46,611
but we believe it to be
some sort of torturing device!

195
00:24:48,405 --> 00:24:51,658
And this - this is a spy tool!

196
00:24:52,200 --> 00:24:55,537
For listening to the unsuspecting!

197
00:24:58,248 --> 00:25:01,084
The evidence speaks for itself.

198
00:25:02,085 --> 00:25:06,548
I move that we dispense with the Muto
as soon as possible and...

199
00:25:06,673 --> 00:25:08,133
(Helen) Why?

200
00:25:10,427 --> 00:25:12,220
Why not use him?

201
00:25:12,345 --> 00:25:16,558
Because he is a threat to the safety
and the purity of this atoll.

202
00:25:16,683 --> 00:25:19,853
- He is not a threat. He's in a cage.
- He killed one of ours, Helen.

203
00:25:19,978 --> 00:25:22,397
(Shouts of agreement)

204
00:25:22,522 --> 00:25:26,693
- Is he dangerous or not?
- I'd say he is now.

205
00:25:27,694 --> 00:25:30,321
But he came in here with all this dirt,

206
00:25:30,447 --> 00:25:33,533
the likes of which we haven't seen
since Enola came.

207
00:25:33,658 --> 00:25:36,327
Oh, what about it?

208
00:25:36,870 --> 00:25:39,372
So it had to come from somewhere.

209
00:25:40,874 --> 00:25:44,627
- What if it came from Dryland?
- Ah, don't start!

210
00:25:44,753 --> 00:25:46,796
He came from the west, I can tell you.

211
00:25:46,921 --> 00:25:50,008
Smokers come from there, from the west.

212
00:25:50,133 --> 00:25:52,635
But if he is a spy,

213
00:25:52,761 --> 00:25:57,265
this ichthy man will give away
our position, our weaknesses.

214
00:25:57,390 --> 00:25:58,850
And if he isn't?

215
00:25:58,975 --> 00:26:03,063
He is still a Muto and he could
contaminate our community!

216
00:26:03,188 --> 00:26:05,982
- And others!
- What others?

217
00:26:06,107 --> 00:26:08,610
We haven't seen another atoll
in over a year.

218
00:26:08,735 --> 00:26:13,156
- Let's keep to the issue at hand.
- No, this is the issue at hand.

219
00:26:13,281 --> 00:26:16,242
Every year, every month, it gets worse.

220
00:26:16,367 --> 00:26:20,080
There are fewer atollers, fewer traders.

221
00:26:20,205 --> 00:26:22,248
Dead gardens,

222
00:26:22,373 --> 00:26:25,251
these windmills that don't work.

223
00:26:25,376 --> 00:26:28,338
Desalinators that can't be fixed.

224
00:26:29,339 --> 00:26:31,257
This place,

225
00:26:31,382 --> 00:26:34,552
this whole way of living, it's ending.

226
00:26:35,678 --> 00:26:39,516
- Doesn't anyone else see that?
- When I was a boy, we had lots of atolls.

227
00:26:39,641 --> 00:26:44,437
You keep on praying for help and now
one man comes here who might actually...

228
00:26:44,562 --> 00:26:48,566
- He's not a man!
- It doesn't matter what he is!

229
00:26:49,359 --> 00:26:54,239
I say, if he knows the way to Dryland,
make him show us where it is!

230
00:26:54,364 --> 00:26:57,408
People have looked for centuries
and death is all they found.

231
00:26:57,534 --> 00:27:00,370
- At least they died trying!
- It's a hoax!

232
00:27:00,495 --> 00:27:05,083
The sooner you realize that, Helen,
the better off we're all going to be!

233
00:27:05,208 --> 00:27:09,129
We'd be better off if we got rid
of that girl of hers, too.

234
00:27:09,254 --> 00:27:10,880
(Man) Right!

235
00:27:11,005 --> 00:27:14,676
Smokers are looking for her!
I heard it from a trader.

236
00:27:15,969 --> 00:27:19,597
- (Bangs gavel)
- One matter at a time!

237
00:27:19,722 --> 00:27:22,392
I say get rid of both of them!

238
00:27:22,517 --> 00:27:25,645
- The Muto and the girl!
- Yes!

239
00:27:25,770 --> 00:27:29,899
- (Clamor)
- Yes! Kill them!

240
00:27:30,024 --> 00:27:31,442
Order!

241
00:27:37,240 --> 00:27:39,242
(Humming)

242
00:27:46,833 --> 00:27:49,252
(Footsteps approach)

243
00:27:51,421 --> 00:27:53,423
(Sniggering)

244
00:27:53,548 --> 00:27:55,550
You'd like this, wouldn't you?

245
00:27:55,675 --> 00:27:59,137
- Stick him.
- He sure is quieter than he was.

246
00:27:59,262 --> 00:28:02,807
- Come on, let's go.
- No! Stick him again.

247
00:28:02,932 --> 00:28:07,604
I know you want it. I know -
maybe he don't eat his own kind.

248
00:28:07,729 --> 00:28:08,897
Aaaargh!

249
00:28:26,247 --> 00:28:29,125
(Gregor) Aha! That's it!

250
00:28:30,710 --> 00:28:35,048
A-ha-ha! That's it!
Don't move, my dear!

251
00:28:35,173 --> 00:28:39,010
Polaris to Taurus.
I forgot Taurus, the bull.

252
00:28:39,135 --> 00:28:41,554
In the shoulder of the bull

253
00:28:41,679 --> 00:28:44,807
there's six sisters.
Or seven, but you can only see six.

254
00:28:44,933 --> 00:28:49,479
At the beginning of each lunar,
one sister is lined up with Scorpius!

255
00:28:49,604 --> 00:28:54,817
And Scorpius has a tail just like an arrow
on the circle on the back of the child!

256
00:28:54,943 --> 00:28:59,197
If I take into account the seventh sister,
and give the seventh sister a lunar,

257
00:28:59,322 --> 00:29:02,659
that lunar would run perpendicular
to Scorpius,

258
00:29:02,784 --> 00:29:05,703
creating a horizon, a straight line,

259
00:29:05,828 --> 00:29:09,332
that would run directly...
directly toward...

260
00:29:10,750 --> 00:29:12,585
Dryland?

261
00:29:14,504 --> 00:29:15,505
No.

262
00:29:18,466 --> 00:29:20,635
(Screams) Is it a map?

263
00:29:21,678 --> 00:29:23,638
Is it calendar?

264
00:29:27,475 --> 00:29:30,061
Is it symbols? Is it language?

265
00:29:30,186 --> 00:29:33,773
- You'd tell me if you knew, eh, Enola?
- Mm-hm.

266
00:29:37,360 --> 00:29:40,196
- What are you drawing?
- I don't know.

267
00:29:41,447 --> 00:29:45,952
Helen, look. Look at
the prodigal child's latest vision.

268
00:29:48,788 --> 00:29:50,623
(He chuckles)

269
00:29:51,791 --> 00:29:54,085
We've got to get out of here.

270
00:29:55,086 --> 00:29:59,590
- I take it the meeting didn't go well.
- They're cutting us adrift, Gregor.

271
00:29:59,716 --> 00:30:03,594
No, they'll not hurt you.
I'd turn their lights off if they did.

272
00:30:04,554 --> 00:30:06,556
How soon before we can go?

273
00:30:06,681 --> 00:30:08,891
Another week, ideally.

274
00:30:09,017 --> 00:30:11,019
We don't have a week.

275
00:30:11,144 --> 00:30:15,064
Helen, I don't have any idea yet
where we can go.

276
00:30:15,189 --> 00:30:18,192
Try. Try it once again.

277
00:30:19,485 --> 00:30:23,156
There's nothing in them.
I've been through the books.

278
00:30:23,281 --> 00:30:28,786
There's nothing in these books.
She is the annunciation. I know it.

279
00:30:28,911 --> 00:30:30,913
I just don't know how.

280
00:30:33,374 --> 00:30:36,753
I'm a stupid man.
The answer's right there. It's...

281
00:30:36,878 --> 00:30:38,880
It's just beyond me.

282
00:30:41,966 --> 00:30:43,885
Maybe he knows.

283
00:30:56,022 --> 00:30:58,232
Ah, yes, I see.

284
00:30:58,358 --> 00:31:00,193
They are webbed.

285
00:31:00,318 --> 00:31:04,614
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven,
eight, nine, ten digits. That's wonderful.

286
00:31:04,739 --> 00:31:08,743
They tell me, too, that you have gills.
Isotropic gills.

287
00:31:08,868 --> 00:31:11,120
Are they merely vestigial or functional?

288
00:31:12,163 --> 00:31:16,167
My name is Gregor. I've just come
to pay you a little vi...vi...

289
00:31:17,460 --> 00:31:19,670
Oh, my God.

290
00:31:20,671 --> 00:31:24,801
I'm sorry. I'm not laughing at you.
I'm excited.

291
00:31:24,926 --> 00:31:29,514
Your gills, they are functional. Ichthys
sapien. You can breathe in the water.

292
00:31:29,639 --> 00:31:31,933
How deep can you go?

293
00:31:32,058 --> 00:31:37,188
Look, I'm only here because I want
to learn more about you.

294
00:31:37,313 --> 00:31:38,898
(Mariner spits)

295
00:31:42,276 --> 00:31:45,446
You don't like humans very much, do you?

296
00:31:45,571 --> 00:31:48,116
I can't say that I blame you.

297
00:31:48,241 --> 00:31:51,536
But, tell me, are all of your kind
as bad-tempered as you?

298
00:31:55,415 --> 00:31:58,000
- I have no kind.
- Oh, fish rot.

299
00:31:58,126 --> 00:32:02,839
I'd be surprised if there weren't others.
If there aren't, there will be eventually.

300
00:32:05,049 --> 00:32:08,886
Anyway, I come here
because I need to ask you a question.

301
00:32:09,011 --> 00:32:13,724
Where... Where did your dirt come from?
Is it from Dryland?

302
00:32:14,851 --> 00:32:17,061
Do you know what this is?

303
00:32:19,021 --> 00:32:22,900
The Ancients, they did something terrible,
didn't they? To cause all this water.

304
00:32:23,025 --> 00:32:27,280
- Hundreds, hundreds of years ago.
- If I tell you, will you open this lock?

305
00:32:30,658 --> 00:32:32,869
I haven't a key.

306
00:32:33,744 --> 00:32:36,539
- There's a mooring cleat down there.
- What?

307
00:32:36,664 --> 00:32:39,667
- As good as any key.
- A mooring cleat?

308
00:32:41,794 --> 00:32:44,505
I won't hurt anyone. I'll just leave.

309
00:32:45,840 --> 00:32:49,093
- I'll be right back.
- (Man) Gregor!

310
00:32:49,218 --> 00:32:53,764
- What's your business there? Move along!
- I'm not a brave man.

311
00:32:53,890 --> 00:32:57,727
If you know anything about Dryland,
please, tell me.

312
00:32:57,852 --> 00:33:00,980
Please. Don't let it die with you.

313
00:33:01,105 --> 00:33:02,690
No, no, no.

314
00:33:02,815 --> 00:33:03,983
Stop!

315
00:33:04,108 --> 00:33:05,818
(Man) Gregor?

316
00:33:05,943 --> 00:33:07,778
Move along!

317
00:33:21,584 --> 00:33:23,794
(Smokers howl like wolves)

318
00:33:30,760 --> 00:33:32,762
(Bell tolls)

319
00:34:07,964 --> 00:34:10,383
- Get out of the way!
- Oh!

320
00:34:15,972 --> 00:34:21,102
(Elder) After considerable deliberation
of the evidence at hand,

321
00:34:21,936 --> 00:34:27,066
it is our decision that this Muto
does indeed constitute a threat.

322
00:34:27,191 --> 00:34:31,320
Therefore,
in the interest of public safety,

323
00:34:31,445 --> 00:34:34,657
he is hereby sentenced to be recycled

324
00:34:34,782 --> 00:34:37,243
in the customary fashion.

325
00:34:37,368 --> 00:34:38,661
Proceed.

326
00:34:49,130 --> 00:34:50,631
I'm sorry.

327
00:34:59,098 --> 00:35:02,393
Bones to berries, veins to vines,

328
00:35:03,728 --> 00:35:07,898
these tendons to trees,
this blood to brine.

329
00:35:08,024 --> 00:35:10,610
Too strange for life he was,

330
00:35:10,735 --> 00:35:15,156
this Muto now does leave us,

331
00:35:15,281 --> 00:35:17,533
recycled and entombed,

332
00:35:17,658 --> 00:35:21,579
in the presence of him who leads us...

333
00:35:31,589 --> 00:35:33,341
Smokers!

334
00:35:33,466 --> 00:35:36,052
Dead out of the sun!

335
00:35:39,305 --> 00:35:42,224
To your posts!

336
00:35:55,404 --> 00:35:57,365
(Alarmed yelling)

337
00:35:57,490 --> 00:35:59,575
(Woman) Oh, my God! Oh, my God!

338
00:36:14,715 --> 00:36:15,758
Kill!

339
00:36:15,883 --> 00:36:17,385
There!

340
00:36:17,510 --> 00:36:19,553
Aaah! Aaah!

341
00:36:25,101 --> 00:36:27,311
Get to your posts!

342
00:36:27,436 --> 00:36:30,439
We are safe, behind this wall!

343
00:36:31,649 --> 00:36:33,734
Aren't we?

344
00:36:41,450 --> 00:36:44,912
Let me out! Let me out! I'll fight!

345
00:36:54,630 --> 00:36:56,632
Get those bullets loaded!

346
00:37:05,141 --> 00:37:08,561
- I can't find my dad.
- He's probably on the wall.

347
00:37:08,686 --> 00:37:11,897
Go in, get a weapon and fight! Go now! Go!
Go, go!

348
00:37:29,248 --> 00:37:31,250
Give me the key to the city now.

349
00:37:34,628 --> 00:37:37,339
Let's go! Let's go! Let's go!

350
00:37:39,842 --> 00:37:42,970
Floor it! Floor it! Go on!

351
00:37:59,028 --> 00:38:00,738
(Woman screaming)

352
00:38:04,283 --> 00:38:06,577
Swab it! Swab it!

353
00:38:08,329 --> 00:38:10,331
Hurry them up!

354
00:38:38,526 --> 00:38:40,528
Burn down the door!

355
00:38:44,365 --> 00:38:46,033
Burn it down!

356
00:38:46,158 --> 00:38:47,409
Aargh!

357
00:39:00,005 --> 00:39:02,967
We'll have this atoll in no time.

358
00:39:05,970 --> 00:39:08,514
Crank it! Crank it!

359
00:39:12,309 --> 00:39:13,394
Look!

360
00:39:26,031 --> 00:39:27,992
(Yelling)

361
00:39:33,247 --> 00:39:35,416
- Now!
- Aaaah!

362
00:39:58,731 --> 00:40:00,107
(Screams)

363
00:40:08,866 --> 00:40:10,659
Oh, no!

364
00:40:34,934 --> 00:40:35,935
Oh, my...!

365
00:40:38,938 --> 00:40:40,856
Helen!

366
00:40:42,733 --> 00:40:45,319
Keep that gas going! Fill 'em up!

367
00:40:56,747 --> 00:40:58,749
Aaargh!

368
00:41:23,607 --> 00:41:24,900
Aargh!

369
00:41:25,025 --> 00:41:29,446
It's the girl they want!
Give them Enola and they'll leave!

370
00:41:30,322 --> 00:41:33,659
Come quickly! Helen!

371
00:41:46,213 --> 00:41:48,549
Aah! Aaargh!

372
00:42:08,777 --> 00:42:13,615
You're not supposed to go yet!
Infernal machine!

373
00:42:15,784 --> 00:42:17,661
Damn you!

374
00:42:25,502 --> 00:42:27,963
Infernal machine!

375
00:42:31,508 --> 00:42:34,136
Gregor? Gregor! Wait!

376
00:42:34,261 --> 00:42:37,639
Helen, I tried. There was an accident.
I couldn't make it stop. Hurry!

377
00:42:37,765 --> 00:42:41,143
You can make it if you try!
Up those stairs! Run!

378
00:42:41,268 --> 00:42:44,229
- Wait!
- Quickly! I'll throw you a rope!

379
00:42:44,354 --> 00:42:47,483
- Run quickly!
- Throw the rope now!

380
00:42:47,608 --> 00:42:50,319
Throw the rope! No!

381
00:42:50,444 --> 00:42:52,529
- No!
- Wait!

382
00:42:54,656 --> 00:42:56,241
- Don't leave us!
- No!

383
00:42:56,366 --> 00:42:58,535
I'm sorry! It was an accident!

384
00:43:02,998 --> 00:43:04,374
Helen!

385
00:43:04,500 --> 00:43:06,710
Enola! Helen, I'm sorry!

386
00:43:26,355 --> 00:43:28,774
Shoot him. Shoot him.

387
00:43:36,490 --> 00:43:39,201
Aaargh!

388
00:43:55,592 --> 00:43:59,304
If I let you out of here,
you're taking us with you.

389
00:44:00,264 --> 00:44:01,265
Sure.

390
00:44:04,893 --> 00:44:06,937
Enola, get down.

391
00:44:07,938 --> 00:44:09,982
Come here. Get down.

392
00:44:10,107 --> 00:44:12,109
Hurry! Come on!

393
00:44:15,154 --> 00:44:16,363
Get the gate!

394
00:44:43,390 --> 00:44:44,683
Argh!

395
00:45:06,496 --> 00:45:07,623
Argh!

396
00:45:16,465 --> 00:45:18,300
(Mariner) Hurry up!

397
00:45:18,425 --> 00:45:20,260
Kamikaze! Come on!

398
00:45:48,997 --> 00:45:50,958
That made a hole.

399
00:46:09,142 --> 00:46:11,645
Find her! Get the girl!

400
00:46:16,775 --> 00:46:17,818
There!

401
00:46:25,826 --> 00:46:29,037
Go! Get that guy! Go! Kill him!

402
00:46:33,208 --> 00:46:35,585
- Wow!
- Enola!

403
00:46:45,929 --> 00:46:49,016
- You're too slow!
- Run to the other side.

404
00:46:50,934 --> 00:46:52,269
Come on!

405
00:46:58,275 --> 00:47:01,320
Grab on! Hold on, hold on.

406
00:47:05,449 --> 00:47:08,952
It's stuck! I can't make it through!
Let her go!

407
00:47:10,412 --> 00:47:13,415
- (Bullets fly)
- Just drop her!

408
00:47:28,180 --> 00:47:30,265
Turn the wheel! The wheel! Turn it.

409
00:47:34,936 --> 00:47:36,396
That!

410
00:47:36,521 --> 00:47:39,066
- Come on, push it!
- I am!

411
00:47:39,191 --> 00:47:41,485
Hurry! Push it hard!

412
00:47:41,610 --> 00:47:43,653
Push it hard!

413
00:47:43,779 --> 00:47:45,739
OK, OK!

414
00:47:45,864 --> 00:47:49,201
Now pull it! Pull it! Go! Go!

415
00:47:49,326 --> 00:47:51,161
Pull it!

416
00:48:02,798 --> 00:48:05,842
- Enola, jump.
- (Bullets hit hull)

417
00:48:06,843 --> 00:48:09,346
- Just look at me! Jump!
- OK!

418
00:48:25,904 --> 00:48:27,823
Well, excuse me!

419
00:48:27,948 --> 00:48:31,952
Did I say anybody could leave
before the battle was over? Did I?

420
00:48:32,077 --> 00:48:35,455
- No!
- Well, do something! I hate sails.

421
00:48:44,798 --> 00:48:46,258
Hey!

422
00:48:46,383 --> 00:48:50,095
- Can you steer?
- Can I trust you?

423
00:49:24,546 --> 00:49:28,550
Answer me this, somebody.
Why is that boat still firing?

424
00:49:28,675 --> 00:49:31,803
- What's that cousin's name?
- Chuck.

425
00:49:31,928 --> 00:49:35,098
- Hey, Chuck!
- He's pulling him right into us!

426
00:49:36,224 --> 00:49:39,561
Maybe he doesn't answer to Chuck.
Call him Charles. Charles!

427
00:49:41,771 --> 00:49:45,775
- Stop him! Stop him!
- (Machine gun roars)

428
00:49:50,447 --> 00:49:52,240
(Men cry out)

429
00:49:53,283 --> 00:49:54,284
Charles!

430
00:49:56,953 --> 00:49:59,289
Adios, cousins.

431
00:50:37,285 --> 00:50:40,664
(Woman) Put me down! Put me down!

432
00:50:51,424 --> 00:50:53,593
She's here somewhere. Keep looking!

433
00:51:00,225 --> 00:51:02,227
(Chainsaw buzzes)

434
00:51:06,606 --> 00:51:07,607
Ah!

435
00:51:09,943 --> 00:51:11,778
(Stammers)

436
00:51:11,903 --> 00:51:15,073
660 Gs of hydro,
three-quarter grade or better,

437
00:51:15,198 --> 00:51:19,119
120 keys of assorted edibles -
fish and plankton cakes -

438
00:51:19,244 --> 00:51:22,622
and 60 keys lamp oil,
44 old-grow grapevines,

439
00:51:22,747 --> 00:51:24,833
ten assorted fruit trees,

440
00:51:24,958 --> 00:51:29,379
zero reloads - no ammo storage
on this particular atoll.

441
00:51:29,504 --> 00:51:33,592
Uh, zero go-juice.
No refining capability.

442
00:51:33,717 --> 00:51:35,552
Primitive savages!

443
00:51:37,262 --> 00:51:39,973
Oh... How about smokes?

444
00:51:40,098 --> 00:51:42,267
Uh, zero. Zero smokes.

445
00:51:43,852 --> 00:51:46,438
I remember when this used to be fun.

446
00:51:46,563 --> 00:51:49,524
How long since we had
a really good crusade?

447
00:51:49,649 --> 00:51:53,278
- I know, I know.
- Tell me, how long?

448
00:51:53,403 --> 00:51:55,405
- I don't know...
- Remember,

449
00:51:55,530 --> 00:51:58,742
there used to be atolls on every horizon.

450
00:51:58,867 --> 00:51:59,868
Mm-hm.

451
00:52:01,077 --> 00:52:03,747
Where the hell are they all going?

452
00:52:03,872 --> 00:52:05,874
Well, we sunk a few.

453
00:52:05,999 --> 00:52:10,337
- I found this.
- Nord... Oh, now that's warmer.

454
00:52:10,462 --> 00:52:14,966
- All right. And the girl?
- Not here. She might have gotten away.

455
00:52:15,091 --> 00:52:18,720
That's why we came here!
We didn't come here to practice!

456
00:52:18,845 --> 00:52:20,805
We don't need practice!

457
00:52:26,227 --> 00:52:28,813
- What you got?
- A couple of heartbeats.

458
00:52:28,938 --> 00:52:30,940
Aren't saying much.

459
00:52:32,275 --> 00:52:36,446
If you notice the arterial nature
of the blood from the hole in my head,

460
00:52:36,571 --> 00:52:40,533
you can assume we're all having
a real lousy day.

461
00:52:40,659 --> 00:52:44,663
So here it is. I need to know
about that tattooed girl.

462
00:52:46,081 --> 00:52:50,710
- First one that tells me lives.
- I saw a girl! I saw her!

463
00:52:50,835 --> 00:52:52,837
She had a big tattoo on her.

464
00:52:55,507 --> 00:52:57,342
You won. Start over.

465
00:52:58,468 --> 00:53:00,553
I-I saw a girl. I'm not sure,

466
00:53:00,679 --> 00:53:04,432
but I think she got on that boat
with three hulls.

467
00:53:05,475 --> 00:53:08,436
The boat that cost me a thousand Gs
of go-juice?

468
00:53:08,561 --> 00:53:11,064
- The Muto's boat.
- Muto?

469
00:53:11,189 --> 00:53:13,942
Yeah, he's got these slits here,

470
00:53:14,067 --> 00:53:17,404
like...like fish gills.

471
00:53:17,529 --> 00:53:19,739
He wasn't really a man.

472
00:53:19,864 --> 00:53:22,450
A fluke of evolution!

473
00:53:24,035 --> 00:53:26,413
Oh, I'm sorry. A fluke of...

474
00:53:26,538 --> 00:53:28,707
- Evolution.
- I know!

475
00:53:28,832 --> 00:53:31,292
Let's have an intelligent conversation.

476
00:53:31,418 --> 00:53:34,504
I'll talk and you listen.

477
00:53:34,629 --> 00:53:38,633
In the beginning,
the provider said,

478
00:53:38,758 --> 00:53:42,429
"Let there be water!"
and the seas came forth.

479
00:53:42,554 --> 00:53:47,183
- He created everything that we know...
- Hey, hey! The Deacon!

480
00:53:47,308 --> 00:53:49,227
The air that we breathe!

481
00:53:49,352 --> 00:53:52,313
He made also both man and fish

482
00:53:52,439 --> 00:53:55,150
and no combination thereof!

483
00:53:55,275 --> 00:53:58,987
He does not abide the notion of evolution!

484
00:53:59,112 --> 00:54:00,905
Amen!

485
00:54:01,030 --> 00:54:06,619
- No! You said you wouldn't kill me!
- Did I say that? Witnesses? Anybody?

486
00:54:06,745 --> 00:54:10,248
- Yes, yes, yes, you did.
- Ah, I may have!

487
00:54:12,500 --> 00:54:14,461
I may have.

488
00:54:15,920 --> 00:54:17,255
No!

489
00:54:21,426 --> 00:54:23,470
We get to the 'Dez,

490
00:54:24,763 --> 00:54:28,558
take up that sky boat,
send it out on patrol.

491
00:54:29,184 --> 00:54:34,439
We got to keep an eye out
for that ichthy freak!

492
00:55:31,120 --> 00:55:33,122
I know what you're thinking.

493
00:55:33,248 --> 00:55:38,378
How much longer that hydro would last
if there weren't three of us on this boat.

494
00:55:40,505 --> 00:55:43,132
Well, Enola won't drink much.

495
00:55:44,509 --> 00:55:46,553
And I won't...

496
00:55:47,262 --> 00:55:49,264
I won't drink at all.

497
00:55:49,389 --> 00:55:51,558
Not till we get there.

498
00:55:51,683 --> 00:55:53,810
Get where?

499
00:55:53,935 --> 00:55:55,937
Wherever you're going.

500
00:55:57,272 --> 00:55:59,274
Wherever you got your dirt.

501
00:56:00,733 --> 00:56:04,237
I told you I salvaged it
off an atoll the Smokers hit.

502
00:56:05,738 --> 00:56:09,242
Smokers don't leave anything after a raid.

503
00:56:09,367 --> 00:56:11,202
Especially dirt.

504
00:56:12,871 --> 00:56:15,248
You've been there, haven't you?

505
00:56:19,085 --> 00:56:20,587
Dryland?

506
00:56:21,754 --> 00:56:23,756
You know where it is.

507
00:56:25,008 --> 00:56:28,636
- Yeah, I know where it is.
- Oh...

508
00:56:30,054 --> 00:56:31,514
And...

509
00:56:31,639 --> 00:56:35,393
- And we're going?
- You and I are.

510
00:56:37,770 --> 00:56:40,273
The kid we've got to pitch over the side.

511
00:56:42,942 --> 00:56:45,695
- What?
- My boat's tore up.

512
00:56:46,988 --> 00:56:51,951
I'm taking on water. I'll be lucky to get
half a hydro ration out of that.

513
00:56:52,076 --> 00:56:55,538
You know, I said I won't drink.

514
00:56:56,539 --> 00:56:58,207
For 12 days?

515
00:57:00,627 --> 00:57:05,924
No. It's better one of you dies now
than both of you die slow.

516
00:57:06,049 --> 00:57:07,884
Wait, wait.

517
00:57:08,009 --> 00:57:10,720
We saved your life. We got you out.

518
00:57:10,845 --> 00:57:14,849
No, you got me out so you could get out.
We're even.

519
00:57:14,974 --> 00:57:17,143
She can cook. She can fish.

520
00:57:17,268 --> 00:57:19,270
- So can I.
- Take my necklace.

521
00:57:19,395 --> 00:57:22,690
- I got better ones below.
- No, look! Oh.

522
00:57:24,692 --> 00:57:28,071
After what you went through
back there on the atoll,

523
00:57:28,196 --> 00:57:30,990
I can understand why you would want to.

524
00:57:31,115 --> 00:57:33,076
But she's a child.

525
00:57:35,203 --> 00:57:36,746
(Humming)

526
00:57:43,836 --> 00:57:46,506
Is there something else, then?

527
00:57:51,844 --> 00:57:54,514
Enola, go below.

528
00:57:55,515 --> 00:57:57,141
Enola.

529
00:58:19,664 --> 00:58:21,040
Yeah.

530
00:58:21,165 --> 00:58:23,084
You said so yourself.

531
00:58:24,419 --> 00:58:26,671
Been out there a long time.

532
00:59:14,886 --> 00:59:18,890
A couple of hours ago,
I was potential dirt to you.

533
00:59:19,015 --> 00:59:21,768
- We're not like that.
- You all are.

534
00:59:27,440 --> 00:59:29,901
Know what I was really thinking?

535
00:59:30,026 --> 00:59:33,696
Why I don't drop both of you
in my wake right now.

536
00:59:34,697 --> 00:59:36,657
You got nothing I need.

537
00:59:53,716 --> 00:59:56,260
You're taking us to Dryland.

538
01:00:00,723 --> 01:00:02,934
Killing's a hard thing to do well.

539
01:00:03,059 --> 01:00:06,729
- Believe me, I'm not the one to start on.
- Both of us!

540
01:00:12,110 --> 01:00:16,030
- How long do you plan to hold that on me?
- As long as it takes.

541
01:00:19,742 --> 01:00:20,785
OK.

542
01:00:20,910 --> 01:00:22,286
Ah!

543
01:00:23,996 --> 01:00:26,582
Let me out! Let me out of here!

544
01:00:28,167 --> 01:00:31,295
You coward! Don't you touch my child!

545
01:00:31,420 --> 01:00:33,589
Come here! I...

546
01:00:34,590 --> 01:00:36,592
(She grunts)

547
01:00:40,012 --> 01:00:41,097
Oh...

548
01:00:41,222 --> 01:00:42,223
Oh...

549
01:01:59,800 --> 01:02:02,011
OK, now don't move, OK?

550
01:02:02,136 --> 01:02:05,598
There. Oh, looking real good, yeah.

551
01:02:05,723 --> 01:02:06,933
There.

552
01:02:07,725 --> 01:02:09,727
There. All done.

553
01:02:09,852 --> 01:02:13,773
Now there may be some small problem
in depth perception.

554
01:02:13,898 --> 01:02:16,359
It better not screw up my short game.

555
01:02:18,527 --> 01:02:19,779
Well?

556
01:02:19,904 --> 01:02:23,241
- (Woman) Looks good.
- It's better than your real eye.

557
01:02:23,366 --> 01:02:27,161
- Much better.
- What do you say, Toby? The truth.

558
01:02:27,286 --> 01:02:31,499
- Looks like shit.
- That's why I love children. No guile.

559
01:02:35,044 --> 01:02:36,837
It does look like shit!

560
01:02:38,923 --> 01:02:42,051
- And it feels like cold shit!
- Deacon?

561
01:02:44,804 --> 01:02:50,017
Sorry It's just there's a problem
in the pit. Maybe you should come.

562
01:02:55,147 --> 01:02:56,732
Let's drive.

563
01:03:04,782 --> 01:03:07,994
To the pit.
Don't bother with the scenic route.

564
01:03:08,119 --> 01:03:09,453
Drive!

565
01:03:10,454 --> 01:03:13,291
(Deacon) Hey, it's driving better.

566
01:03:16,961 --> 01:03:18,963
(♪ "Peter Gunn Theme")

567
01:03:22,133 --> 01:03:24,176
(Rowdy yelling)

568
01:03:25,344 --> 01:03:26,554
Get off!

569
01:03:28,139 --> 01:03:30,099
Get off! Get out the way!

570
01:03:30,224 --> 01:03:34,186
- Get out the way!
- All right, all right. OK, OK.

571
01:03:36,480 --> 01:03:40,401
Bless you, cousins.
Bless all you cousins over there.

572
01:03:40,526 --> 01:03:44,447
Keep up the good work!
Growth is progress, growth is progress.

573
01:03:44,572 --> 01:03:46,282
(Man) Somebody!

574
01:03:46,407 --> 01:03:48,784
Hey, up there!

575
01:03:48,909 --> 01:03:51,120
Take it off!

576
01:03:53,956 --> 01:03:56,667
- Yes?
- Your Deaconship.

577
01:03:56,792 --> 01:03:58,169
Hello!

578
01:03:58,294 --> 01:04:02,631
Good morning. Or night.
Whichever the case may be.

579
01:04:02,757 --> 01:04:05,468
What is it? I'm a busy man.

580
01:04:05,593 --> 01:04:09,388
I thought you should know
you're down to exactly

581
01:04:10,389 --> 01:04:13,434
four feet nine inches of black stuff.

582
01:04:17,980 --> 01:04:21,067
- Thank you, sir.
- How many Gs after refining?

583
01:04:21,192 --> 01:04:25,279
- Maybe three refuelers.
- We'll burn through that in two lunars.

584
01:04:25,404 --> 01:04:28,240
Sweet Joe! What's happening to this place?

585
01:04:30,076 --> 01:04:33,079
- We outgrowed it.
- All right.

586
01:04:33,204 --> 01:04:36,665
The only thing that is important
is the tattooed girl.

587
01:04:36,791 --> 01:04:39,460
We don't spare any go-juice finding her.

588
01:04:39,585 --> 01:04:44,256
We don't waste it anywhere else. Cancel
all those tractor pulls and all that stuff

589
01:04:44,382 --> 01:04:46,842
until later. You got it?

590
01:04:48,344 --> 01:04:50,971
Dryland is the mother lode.

591
01:04:51,097 --> 01:04:53,265
Ha-ha! On your toes.

592
01:05:16,997 --> 01:05:19,208
Why don't you use sea hydro?

593
01:05:20,418 --> 01:05:22,753
The salt's harder on the filters.

594
01:05:45,401 --> 01:05:47,403
Can we have some?

595
01:05:50,448 --> 01:05:52,283
It's for her, not me.

596
01:06:03,544 --> 01:06:05,504
Here, come on.

597
01:06:06,338 --> 01:06:10,509
- Is he going to take us to Dryland?
- Sure he is.

598
01:06:10,634 --> 01:06:11,635
Yeah.

599
01:06:15,806 --> 01:06:18,017
All of it, all of it, all of it.

600
01:06:20,561 --> 01:06:23,439
Good. Good, good. Come on.

601
01:06:34,992 --> 01:06:37,369
Thanks for not killing us.

602
01:06:54,595 --> 01:06:56,597
Just stay away from him.

603
01:07:28,504 --> 01:07:30,798
- Hi.
- Move.

604
01:07:31,882 --> 01:07:34,260
(Helen) Enola! Enola, come here!

605
01:07:36,053 --> 01:07:37,930
Come on!

606
01:07:40,057 --> 01:07:42,601
Enola, come over here.

607
01:07:56,282 --> 01:07:57,700
Hey!

608
01:07:59,994 --> 01:08:04,873
- What are you doing?
- Decorating your boat. It's ugly.

609
01:08:08,544 --> 01:08:11,547
- Where did you get this?
- From down below.

610
01:08:11,672 --> 01:08:14,592
This is mine!
You don't touch anything of mine.

611
01:08:14,717 --> 01:08:18,721
- I drew it for you.
- Don't draw on anything! Understand?

612
01:08:27,813 --> 01:08:30,733
This is my boat.
I got it the way I like it.

613
01:08:30,858 --> 01:08:34,028
You take up space
and you're slowing me down.

614
01:08:37,323 --> 01:08:41,619
You know, she's just a little girl.
She doesn't know your rules.

615
01:08:41,744 --> 01:08:44,538
You wanna stay? You teach her.

616
01:09:02,848 --> 01:09:05,476
Enola, what did I tell you?

617
01:09:10,230 --> 01:09:12,900
You're not so tough, you know that?

618
01:09:17,071 --> 01:09:19,239
How many people have you killed?

619
01:09:21,950 --> 01:09:24,495
Ten? Twenty?

620
01:09:26,872 --> 01:09:28,666
You talk a lot.

621
01:09:28,791 --> 01:09:31,251
I talk a lot cos you don't talk at all.

622
01:09:31,377 --> 01:09:33,295
So how many?

623
01:09:35,255 --> 01:09:39,968
- Including little girls?
- I'm not afraid of you.

624
01:09:42,763 --> 01:09:46,767
I told Helen you wouldn't be so ugly
if you cut your hair.

625
01:09:49,478 --> 01:09:53,732
In fact, you talk all the time!
It's like a storm when you're around!

626
01:09:53,857 --> 01:09:56,568
(Helen) Enola! Hey, what are you doing?

627
01:09:56,694 --> 01:10:00,280
- Helen!
- She can't swim!

628
01:10:00,406 --> 01:10:03,283
(Enola) Help me! Helen!

629
01:10:03,409 --> 01:10:05,661
Helen, help me!

630
01:10:07,037 --> 01:10:08,831
Help!

631
01:10:08,956 --> 01:10:11,458
Helen, help me!

632
01:10:20,008 --> 01:10:22,010
Helen! Help!

633
01:10:22,136 --> 01:10:23,929
Hold on.

634
01:10:24,847 --> 01:10:26,724
Look at me, look at me.

635
01:10:28,892 --> 01:10:31,395
Oh... Wait. Come on.

636
01:10:31,520 --> 01:10:32,855
Please!

637
01:10:32,980 --> 01:10:33,981
Please!

638
01:10:34,106 --> 01:10:35,899
Oh, please!

639
01:10:36,024 --> 01:10:37,985
(Helen coughs)

640
01:10:41,071 --> 01:10:42,865
Hey!

641
01:10:45,075 --> 01:10:48,120
Hold on. OK... Almost.

642
01:10:48,746 --> 01:10:50,164
(Gasping)

643
01:10:59,256 --> 01:11:01,216
(Enola gasps)

644
01:11:02,634 --> 01:11:07,598
Thanks. But I swear,
if you ever touch her again...

645
01:11:07,723 --> 01:11:12,728
Sonofabitch! Look at me! You'll go to bed
that night and you will never wake up.

646
01:11:12,853 --> 01:11:14,938
- Shut up.
- What?

647
01:11:15,939 --> 01:11:17,983
- (Helen) Smokers?
- Yeah.

648
01:11:18,108 --> 01:11:20,068
Well, can't we outrun them?

649
01:11:20,194 --> 01:11:24,364
- (Plane engine hums)
- Not with my sail down.

650
01:11:42,549 --> 01:11:46,345
- What are you thinking about?
- That's a nice touch.

651
01:11:46,470 --> 01:11:48,263
That's them!

652
01:11:54,770 --> 01:11:56,980
Don't hit the kid!

653
01:12:00,692 --> 01:12:03,320
(Laughing)

654
01:12:12,496 --> 01:12:14,164
Hey!

655
01:12:19,127 --> 01:12:21,171
Coward!

656
01:12:27,886 --> 01:12:29,179
(Laughs)

657
01:12:29,304 --> 01:12:31,390
- (Gun jams)
- Fuck!

658
01:13:00,002 --> 01:13:01,837
No!

659
01:13:04,715 --> 01:13:07,217
Hey! Urgh!

660
01:13:23,400 --> 01:13:24,776
Cut it!

661
01:13:33,952 --> 01:13:35,662
Come on! Come on!

662
01:13:56,058 --> 01:13:57,851
(Mast creaking)

663
01:14:08,403 --> 01:14:09,905
Aaah!

664
01:15:12,592 --> 01:15:14,636
(Helen) Oh...I'm really sorry.

665
01:15:14,761 --> 01:15:17,973
I'm sorry! You didn't give me much choice.

666
01:15:19,307 --> 01:15:22,102
I know. But you ran away.

667
01:15:22,227 --> 01:15:24,104
I... What?

668
01:15:24,229 --> 01:15:27,065
What are you do...? No! Please, no!

669
01:15:32,487 --> 01:15:34,197
(Grunting)

670
01:15:36,867 --> 01:15:41,538
Don't ever touch anything
on my boat again.

671
01:15:45,083 --> 01:15:47,127
She said she was sorry!

672
01:15:50,630 --> 01:15:53,383
That means you're supposed to
say something back!

673
01:16:16,114 --> 01:16:19,076
- Did you say something?
- (Enola) Mm-mm.

674
01:16:52,400 --> 01:16:54,444
(Deacon) Fore!

675
01:16:54,569 --> 01:16:58,323
- Nice putt.
- It wasn't a putt. That was a drive.

676
01:16:58,448 --> 01:17:01,409
I wasn't even using my good eye. Damn it!

677
01:17:03,370 --> 01:17:05,789
You got an ashtray or something?

678
01:17:05,914 --> 01:17:07,916
Oh, man.

679
01:17:08,875 --> 01:17:10,877
Damn thing never did work right.

680
01:17:11,002 --> 01:17:13,588
- You said to bring the pilot.
- Yes, I did.

681
01:17:13,713 --> 01:17:17,342
- Well, he's here.
- Why didn't you tell me?

682
01:17:17,467 --> 01:17:21,012
Come on, Nord. Well, tell me about it.

683
01:17:21,138 --> 01:17:26,101
- The child. Did he have her with him?
- Yeah. And some atoll bitch!

684
01:17:27,602 --> 01:17:29,688
They killed Ed!

685
01:17:29,813 --> 01:17:34,067
Now, now. Don't you fret yourself.
Plenty more where Ed came from.

686
01:17:34,192 --> 01:17:37,445
- Heading west south-west?
- From here.

687
01:17:37,571 --> 01:17:41,199
If we launch now,
we can cut him down just about here.

688
01:17:41,324 --> 01:17:44,828
- If he doesn't change course.
- That's not likely.

689
01:17:44,953 --> 01:17:47,998
He's a wily one, that ichthy demon.

690
01:19:31,518 --> 01:19:33,520
(Drifter calls out)

691
01:19:34,688 --> 01:19:36,982
- Drifter?
- Mm-hm.

692
01:19:37,107 --> 01:19:38,900
Are we going to stop?

693
01:19:39,025 --> 01:19:40,986
- (Drifter) Look at the flag!
- His flag's up.

694
01:19:41,111 --> 01:19:43,780
I thought you all stopped for each other.

695
01:19:49,369 --> 01:19:51,121
Maybe he has some FOOD!

696
01:19:54,708 --> 01:19:57,252
Don't find many who follow the rules
any more.

697
01:19:57,377 --> 01:20:00,130
Make it quick. What's your business?

698
01:20:05,802 --> 01:20:07,595
Trade.

699
01:20:09,222 --> 01:20:11,391
Got any resin?

700
01:20:13,601 --> 01:20:17,689
Resin? He's out of his mind.
He's out of his mind completely. Resin?

701
01:20:17,814 --> 01:20:21,443
You've been outwater a long time,
haven't you?

702
01:20:22,444 --> 01:20:25,530
Don't be joking me, man! Resin!
You don't got enough.

703
01:20:25,655 --> 01:20:28,867
- How about food?
- Could you say that again, please?

704
01:20:28,992 --> 01:20:31,870
- How about food?
- Well, yeah, food.

705
01:20:31,995 --> 01:20:33,955
That'd be good, eh?

706
01:20:34,080 --> 01:20:37,500
I haven't eaten in, well, you know,
forever.

707
01:20:38,793 --> 01:20:43,506
Which one of you two is the cook, then?
I usually fall for the waitress.

708
01:20:45,133 --> 01:20:48,762
- Like you said, I don't have much.
- I'll decide.

709
01:20:48,887 --> 01:20:53,266
Look at you. We could start
with that wee orchard over there.

710
01:20:54,351 --> 01:20:55,393
Woo!

711
01:20:56,644 --> 01:20:58,688
(Mariner) All right. Hold it there.

712
01:20:58,813 --> 01:21:01,816
- We can talk.
- Fair enough.

713
01:21:02,859 --> 01:21:04,819
(Muttering)

714
01:21:07,781 --> 01:21:11,534
It's a nice rod, isn't it?
I like that rod. It's a nice rod.

715
01:21:11,659 --> 01:21:13,161
My favorite.

716
01:21:19,167 --> 01:21:22,295
Got yourself a wee harem going here,
don't you now?

717
01:21:28,426 --> 01:21:32,472
- What do you want for the women?
- We're not for sale.

718
01:21:32,597 --> 01:21:36,476
Not for sale? I mean, there's
no such thing as not for sale.

719
01:21:36,601 --> 01:21:38,561
Not for sale, not for sale. Aye.

720
01:21:40,647 --> 01:21:44,067
Are they a pair
or would you sell them separate?

721
01:21:44,192 --> 01:21:48,279
Our business is done here, unless
you've got some resin you can part with.

722
01:21:48,405 --> 01:21:52,742
I told you once already, I don't have any.
I don't have it, don't have it.

723
01:21:52,867 --> 01:21:57,205
Haven't seen any for trade in lunars now.
Wait. Wait, wait, wait.

724
01:22:00,083 --> 01:22:03,920
I do have something
that'll make you change your mind.

725
01:22:04,045 --> 01:22:06,256
Something you can't pass on.

726
01:22:07,757 --> 01:22:10,927
I took it off an atoller refugee camp.

727
01:22:12,429 --> 01:22:15,056
Life savings of the entire clan.

728
01:22:22,230 --> 01:22:25,024
Paper! Look at my wee paper.

729
01:22:26,317 --> 01:22:31,239
Paper! Have you ever seen paper?
Look at it, smell it.

730
01:22:34,075 --> 01:22:36,453
I'm saving it for a special trade.

731
01:22:39,247 --> 01:22:41,458
Don't you do it.

732
01:22:42,292 --> 01:22:46,546
Maybe I'm talking to the wrong person.
Whose boat is this anyway?

733
01:22:46,671 --> 01:22:51,259
- Is it your boat or your boat?
- It's his boat, but he doesn't own us.

734
01:22:57,891 --> 01:23:02,562
- Half an hour.
- He's obviously out of his mind.

735
01:23:02,687 --> 01:23:05,523
I've got two pages in here, man!

736
01:23:05,648 --> 01:23:09,235
- I'd get half a dozen girls with this.
- Half an hour.

737
01:23:10,487 --> 01:23:12,697
- You trading or not?
- Don't!

738
01:23:12,822 --> 01:23:14,824
Shut up.

739
01:23:16,034 --> 01:23:17,035
OK.

740
01:23:19,704 --> 01:23:23,917
45 minutes with the wee one. I like to do
the talkin', if you know what I mean.

741
01:23:25,960 --> 01:23:27,587
No!

742
01:23:28,588 --> 01:23:30,381
Fair enough.

743
01:23:30,507 --> 01:23:32,592
Come, come, come, come, come.

744
01:23:32,717 --> 01:23:35,053
No. My boat.

745
01:23:36,513 --> 01:23:39,140
That's fair enough.
Good, good, good, good, good.

746
01:23:39,265 --> 01:23:40,350
Helen...

747
01:23:40,475 --> 01:23:44,103
- Sit down.
- Enola, just do as he says.

748
01:24:13,800 --> 01:24:15,843
Half an hour.

749
01:24:59,846 --> 01:25:00,847
Well...

750
01:25:03,266 --> 01:25:05,476
It's been a while for me now.

751
01:25:06,603 --> 01:25:10,356
Guess it's been more than a while,
actually, but...

752
01:25:12,817 --> 01:25:14,819
I've only got half an hour.

753
01:25:14,944 --> 01:25:18,906
Half an hour, half an hour, half an hour,
half an hour, half an hour.

754
01:25:19,032 --> 01:25:21,075
OK, right, right, right.

755
01:25:22,660 --> 01:25:26,497
You're so beautiful.
Anyone ever told you that?

756
01:25:26,623 --> 01:25:30,293
Give me that! What are you doing?
It's just a game!

757
01:25:31,169 --> 01:25:33,379
Oh, I...

758
01:25:33,504 --> 01:25:35,381
I... We was just playing.

759
01:25:38,843 --> 01:25:40,553
Trade's off.

760
01:25:40,678 --> 01:25:42,513
I changed my mind.

761
01:25:42,639 --> 01:25:44,515
Well, um...

762
01:25:45,516 --> 01:25:49,145
Well, you can't do that.
I mean, a deal's a deal. Aye.

763
01:25:49,270 --> 01:25:51,481
I just did.

764
01:25:53,733 --> 01:25:56,944
She's mine, aye. No, no, no.
I won't have it.

765
01:25:57,070 --> 01:25:58,780
- No.
- Go on.

766
01:25:58,905 --> 01:26:02,617
Go, go, go, good. Aye, aye.
Don't go too far now!

767
01:26:02,742 --> 01:26:05,578
This won't take but a minute.

768
01:26:09,749 --> 01:26:11,751
I hate this boat.

769
01:26:11,876 --> 01:26:14,629
I...hate...this...boat!

770
01:26:15,963 --> 01:26:17,757
You garbage!

771
01:26:22,762 --> 01:26:23,763
You...

772
01:26:25,181 --> 01:26:29,185
You're pretty stingy for a man
who's got everything, aren't you?

773
01:26:41,280 --> 01:26:42,198
Aargh!

774
01:26:42,323 --> 01:26:44,409
(Crashing and yelling)

775
01:26:57,922 --> 01:26:59,799
Where's me boat?

776
01:27:00,925 --> 01:27:02,802
Where's me boat?

777
01:27:04,011 --> 01:27:06,013
(Mutters to himself)

778
01:27:10,601 --> 01:27:12,562
Help me to me boat.

779
01:27:14,021 --> 01:27:16,357
Ah! The boat...

780
01:27:51,601 --> 01:27:54,395
Yeah, if he knows he's been spotted,

781
01:27:54,520 --> 01:27:58,191
he'll expect us to expect him
to change course,

782
01:27:58,316 --> 01:28:02,153
which is exactly why
he'll keep his heading.

783
01:28:02,278 --> 01:28:05,114
The important question is
where's he headed?

784
01:28:05,239 --> 01:28:08,284
And does he know
how precious his cargo is?

785
01:28:09,285 --> 01:28:10,286
Dryland.

786
01:28:11,245 --> 01:28:12,663
Salvation.

787
01:28:12,789 --> 01:28:15,124
Room to grow 18 holes.

788
01:28:15,249 --> 01:28:17,293
36, 72!

789
01:28:18,461 --> 01:28:22,173
I say that he's headed here
and we take him here.

790
01:28:49,283 --> 01:28:52,370
How long before we get some wind?

791
01:28:53,371 --> 01:28:54,789
Days, maybe.

792
01:28:55,790 --> 01:28:57,667
Then why don't we fish?

793
01:28:57,792 --> 01:28:59,627
What for?

794
01:29:00,628 --> 01:29:04,465
- So we can get something to eat?
- We ate two days ago.

795
01:29:04,590 --> 01:29:06,008
You ate.

796
01:29:08,928 --> 01:29:09,929
Just...

797
01:29:12,932 --> 01:29:14,934
Just help me fix this.

798
01:29:15,935 --> 01:29:18,354
I'll catch something myself.

799
01:29:18,479 --> 01:29:22,233
You're not going to catch anything
with this around here.

800
01:29:23,734 --> 01:29:24,902
Look,

801
01:29:25,820 --> 01:29:28,239
we're not trying to make you angry.

802
01:29:31,117 --> 01:29:33,744
And you don't disappear
when you turn your back.

803
01:29:33,870 --> 01:29:38,165
- You don't know what fishing's like here.
- Then you do it, if you're the authority.

804
01:29:49,552 --> 01:29:52,179
Maybe he doesn't know how to fish.

805
01:29:53,806 --> 01:29:57,518
- I think you're right, Enola.
- Shut up, will ya?

806
01:29:57,643 --> 01:30:01,981
- I'm trying to listen for engines.
- I will not shut up!

807
01:30:02,106 --> 01:30:06,402
Until you stop what you're doing and help
me find something to eat for this child!

808
01:30:06,527 --> 01:30:09,405
I will scream so loud that it...

809
01:30:10,948 --> 01:30:13,117
Put that... No!

810
01:30:14,577 --> 01:30:17,788
You'll never catch anything with this.
It's useless.

811
01:30:23,419 --> 01:30:25,546
(Helen) Look, I'm sorry!

812
01:30:25,671 --> 01:30:28,257
You were right about the pole.

813
01:30:28,382 --> 01:30:30,259
You were right!

814
01:30:30,384 --> 01:30:32,386
But we have to eat.

815
01:30:37,099 --> 01:30:39,268
I know you can hear me!

816
01:30:39,393 --> 01:30:42,939
We can fish for ourselves.
Just show us what to do.

817
01:30:43,064 --> 01:30:46,943
- You must know. Even you've got to eat!
- You just sit there.

818
01:31:10,841 --> 01:31:12,635
What...?

819
01:31:42,707 --> 01:31:44,583
(Muffled explosion)

820
01:31:50,131 --> 01:31:52,341
Happy now?

821
01:31:56,345 --> 01:31:58,764
(Enola happily hums)

822
01:32:09,775 --> 01:32:12,403
You don't like my singing, do you?

823
01:32:16,157 --> 01:32:20,411
Helen says you don't like my singing
cos you can't sing.

824
01:32:27,209 --> 01:32:29,712
- Ever try and listen?
- To what?

825
01:32:32,256 --> 01:32:34,050
The sound of the world.

826
01:32:39,221 --> 01:32:42,850
- I don't hear anything.
- That's because you're too loud.

827
01:32:42,975 --> 01:32:46,353
And moving around all the time.
Try sitting still.

828
01:32:48,022 --> 01:32:50,107
Eyeball?

829
01:33:07,291 --> 01:33:09,919
Go ahead. Drink all you want.

830
01:33:11,170 --> 01:33:13,172
It's gonna rain tonight.

831
01:33:31,732 --> 01:33:33,692
I wish I had feet like his.

832
01:33:36,821 --> 01:33:40,449
- Then maybe I could swim.
- Enola...

833
01:33:43,994 --> 01:33:46,038
(Belches) Sorry.

834
01:33:51,043 --> 01:33:54,255
I never met a person
who couldn't swim before.

835
01:33:55,965 --> 01:33:57,466
I can't.

836
01:34:00,344 --> 01:34:02,513
People said I was weird.

837
01:34:02,638 --> 01:34:04,598
Maybe they're right.

838
01:34:07,810 --> 01:34:10,688
Maybe they were right about you, too.

839
01:34:37,423 --> 01:34:39,383
(Wind whistles)

840
01:34:42,052 --> 01:34:44,054
(♪ Mellow jazz trumpet plays)

841
01:35:14,293 --> 01:35:16,503
Is that from Dryland?

842
01:35:17,504 --> 01:35:19,340
(Turns music off)

843
01:35:19,465 --> 01:35:20,549
Yeah.

844
01:35:26,972 --> 01:35:28,390
(Sighs)

845
01:35:33,312 --> 01:35:37,191
- I don't even know your name.
- I don't need one.

846
01:35:38,859 --> 01:35:41,153
Enola wanted to give this to you.

847
01:35:45,449 --> 01:35:47,868
And this.

848
01:35:50,788 --> 01:35:52,998
She won't take it again.

849
01:35:59,171 --> 01:36:01,173
You don't look much like her.

850
01:36:01,298 --> 01:36:04,510
I'm not her mother,
if that's what you're asking.

851
01:36:04,635 --> 01:36:06,053
You act like it.

852
01:36:07,012 --> 01:36:09,014
About six years ago,

853
01:36:09,139 --> 01:36:13,811
this basket floated into the atoll
with Enola in it.

854
01:36:15,145 --> 01:36:19,358
Of course, everyone wanted to shove her
back out to sea. That was the law.

855
01:36:20,276 --> 01:36:22,236
She was so precious.

856
01:36:22,361 --> 01:36:24,530
I wanted to keep her.

857
01:36:25,531 --> 01:36:29,576
So the Elders talked and said
that if I wanted her so badly,

858
01:36:29,702 --> 01:36:32,329
I could never have a child of my own.

859
01:36:34,081 --> 01:36:37,042
There was no one else.
She would have died otherwise.

860
01:36:38,127 --> 01:36:39,211
So?

861
01:36:39,336 --> 01:36:41,380
It's called compassion.

862
01:36:42,965 --> 01:36:43,966
Oh...

863
01:36:45,050 --> 01:36:49,096
You probably wouldn't understand
after being alone so much.

864
01:36:49,221 --> 01:36:53,267
I'm not alone.
I've got this boat for a friend.

865
01:36:54,643 --> 01:36:59,440
It don't lie to me,
don't cut my throat when I'm asleep.

866
01:36:59,565 --> 01:37:01,900
Gives me a place to be.

867
01:37:02,026 --> 01:37:04,320
I pity you, really.

868
01:37:05,738 --> 01:37:08,073
- What's pity?
- You don't know?

869
01:37:08,198 --> 01:37:10,492
If I knew, I wouldn't ask.

870
01:37:11,744 --> 01:37:15,664
Well, if you don't know,
I could never make you understand.

871
01:37:18,083 --> 01:37:21,545
- What are those marks on her back?
- Nothing.

872
01:37:21,670 --> 01:37:26,342
- They're just fanciful things.
- Like what she draws?

873
01:37:26,467 --> 01:37:30,804
She draws what she sees.
She's like a mirror.

874
01:37:32,348 --> 01:37:34,892
People on the atoll thought she was a...

875
01:37:36,352 --> 01:37:38,270
Freak?

876
01:37:39,104 --> 01:37:43,567
Uh-huh. Yeah.
I just thought she was special.

877
01:37:52,159 --> 01:37:55,079
I'm not giving it to her. It's just...

878
01:37:55,204 --> 01:37:56,955
A loan.

879
01:37:57,081 --> 01:38:00,000
Yeah. I'm not giving it to her.

880
01:38:06,006 --> 01:38:08,008
Is Dryland beautiful?

881
01:38:10,177 --> 01:38:11,929
You'll see.

882
01:39:17,995 --> 01:39:19,997
(Enola giggles)

883
01:39:25,711 --> 01:39:27,171
Enola?

884
01:39:28,338 --> 01:39:30,340
Enola! What are you doing?

885
01:39:30,466 --> 01:39:33,927
- Those monsters will kill her!
- They're asleep now.

886
01:39:37,014 --> 01:39:39,016
Hands around my neck.

887
01:39:41,143 --> 01:39:45,856
Let the water tell your arms and legs
how to move. Going down. Hold your breath.

888
01:41:25,455 --> 01:41:28,417
- What is it?
- What is it?

889
01:41:30,252 --> 01:41:32,170
Barter outpost.

890
01:41:32,963 --> 01:41:37,801
- You said we'd get to Dryland today.
- Today, tomorrow. What does it matter?

891
01:41:39,428 --> 01:41:41,430
We need resin.

892
01:41:42,806 --> 01:41:45,017
(Speaks PortuGreek)

893
01:41:51,064 --> 01:41:53,775
- What is that?
- It's PortuGreek.

894
01:41:55,360 --> 01:41:57,738
Their own language.

895
01:41:59,489 --> 01:42:01,491
That's what I thought.

896
01:42:27,601 --> 01:42:29,102
Ah.

897
01:42:30,187 --> 01:42:33,815
There's my girl. Yes.

898
01:42:33,940 --> 01:42:37,527
Howdy, darling.
Come on in here now.

899
01:43:06,139 --> 01:43:09,476
- What's going on?
- Smokers.

900
01:43:12,896 --> 01:43:14,773
What the hell...?

901
01:43:18,402 --> 01:43:20,153
He's spotted us!

902
01:43:20,278 --> 01:43:23,031
Sound it! Sound it! Sound it!

903
01:43:23,156 --> 01:43:25,200
Sound it! Sound it!

904
01:43:36,294 --> 01:43:38,839
Woo-hoo!

905
01:43:46,722 --> 01:43:48,306
Enola!

906
01:44:00,777 --> 01:44:03,238
Starboard side! Now!

907
01:44:04,406 --> 01:44:06,241
Get in the chair!

908
01:44:12,622 --> 01:44:15,500
Watch it! He's clearing the net!

909
01:44:26,928 --> 01:44:29,014
Go to the helm!

910
01:44:30,891 --> 01:44:33,351
- Get the centerboard!
- Centerboard?

911
01:44:33,477 --> 01:44:37,272
What centerboard? Where exactly?
I don't know what to do!

912
01:44:37,397 --> 01:44:39,608
Under the helm, pull the handle!

913
01:44:42,152 --> 01:44:44,070
Hey. Hey!

914
01:44:46,615 --> 01:44:48,992
It's too late! Over here.

915
01:45:01,755 --> 01:45:03,131
Aaah!

916
01:45:07,969 --> 01:45:09,262
No!

917
01:45:26,613 --> 01:45:28,240
Give me that rifle.

918
01:45:28,365 --> 01:45:32,911
Boy, if you want to do something right,
you've got to do it yourself.

919
01:45:33,870 --> 01:45:35,872
All right.

920
01:45:36,957 --> 01:45:38,542
Ugh!

921
01:45:42,796 --> 01:45:44,047
I winged him.

922
01:45:44,172 --> 01:45:48,009
Load all the go-juice onto one boat
and run the freak down.

923
01:45:48,134 --> 01:45:51,263
You can't catch him with ten boats
and you want to send just one?

924
01:45:51,388 --> 01:45:53,932
Well, I pray that you're joking.

925
01:46:02,023 --> 01:46:03,817
Bring me the Trackers.

926
01:46:17,497 --> 01:46:22,168
You lied to us!
You were going to sell us back there!

927
01:46:22,294 --> 01:46:24,254
Then we both lied.

928
01:46:24,379 --> 01:46:25,422
What?

929
01:46:27,382 --> 01:46:28,800
I saw what I saw.

930
01:46:28,925 --> 01:46:31,928
- He's hurt.
- So he should be.

931
01:46:32,053 --> 01:46:33,388
He was going to sell us.

932
01:46:38,101 --> 01:46:40,770
No wonder you let her keep it!

933
01:46:40,896 --> 01:46:42,522
You leave it!

934
01:46:44,149 --> 01:46:48,820
- Why do they want her?
- There's nothing human about you.

935
01:46:48,945 --> 01:46:51,781
They should have killed you
the day you were born.

936
01:46:51,907 --> 01:46:53,825
They tried.

937
01:46:55,577 --> 01:46:57,579
No more lies.

938
01:46:59,581 --> 01:47:02,334
- Ah!
- What are the marks on her back?

939
01:47:03,376 --> 01:47:06,296
People say it's the way to Dryland.

940
01:47:06,421 --> 01:47:08,673
- Dryland's a myth!
- No!

941
01:47:08,798 --> 01:47:12,761
You said so yourself that you know
where it is. You did.

942
01:47:17,599 --> 01:47:21,186
You're a fool to believe in something
you've never seen before.

943
01:47:21,311 --> 01:47:25,690
I've seen it. I've touched it. Dirt
that was richer and darker than yours.

944
01:47:25,815 --> 01:47:27,651
In the basket we found Enola in!

945
01:47:27,776 --> 01:47:30,612
- It doesn't exist!
- How can you be so sure?

946
01:47:30,737 --> 01:47:35,200
I've sailed farther than most have
dreamed. And I've never seen it.

947
01:47:36,826 --> 01:47:41,623
- But the things on your boat.
- Things on my boat? What?

948
01:47:41,748 --> 01:47:45,919
There are things on your boat
that nobody has ever seen!

949
01:47:46,044 --> 01:47:48,046
What are these shells?

950
01:47:48,171 --> 01:47:50,715
And that reflecting glass?

951
01:47:50,840 --> 01:47:53,885
And...and...and the music box.

952
01:47:55,720 --> 01:47:59,516
If not from Dryland, then where? Where?

953
01:48:02,060 --> 01:48:03,937
You want to see Dryland?

954
01:48:05,647 --> 01:48:08,066
You really want to see it?

955
01:48:09,442 --> 01:48:11,736
I'll take you to Dryland.

956
01:48:25,041 --> 01:48:26,751
Get in.

957
01:48:32,841 --> 01:48:36,011
- Well, what about Enola?
- There's only air for one.

958
01:48:36,136 --> 01:48:38,847
- Get in the water.
- It'll be all right.

959
01:48:51,026 --> 01:48:53,069
Don't touch anything.

960
01:48:57,532 --> 01:48:58,950
OK?

961
01:52:35,792 --> 01:52:37,752
I didn't know.

962
01:52:39,796 --> 01:52:41,756
All this time?

963
01:52:43,007 --> 01:52:46,177
- I didn't know.
- Nobody does.

964
01:52:55,061 --> 01:52:59,983
- Can you get us out of here?
- I'd say there's two chances of that.

965
01:53:00,692 --> 01:53:03,027
- Hey!
- No way and no how.

966
01:53:03,152 --> 01:53:06,572
Should have bought me that drink.
Come on!

967
01:53:06,698 --> 01:53:08,574
This way. Come on!

968
01:53:09,867 --> 01:53:11,869
(Celebratory whooping)

969
01:53:11,995 --> 01:53:13,663
(Man) Yeah!

970
01:53:15,498 --> 01:53:19,836
Proper introductions first.
I'm the Deacon.

971
01:53:21,421 --> 01:53:23,214
(Laughing)

972
01:53:25,466 --> 01:53:30,346
If you don't recall the face, perhaps
it's cos I didn't always look like this.

973
01:53:33,266 --> 01:53:37,103
Now, I suspect
she's somewhere real close.

974
01:53:38,104 --> 01:53:40,273
So we could tear this boat apart,

975
01:53:40,398 --> 01:53:43,359
but I'd rather somebody just tell me
where she is.

976
01:53:43,484 --> 01:53:45,778
The first one that does that lives.

977
01:53:45,903 --> 01:53:50,408
And the runner-up... Well, actually,
there are no runners-up.

978
01:53:53,286 --> 01:53:55,663
Oh, sweet Joe, I love this part.

979
01:53:55,788 --> 01:53:58,833
Choose 'em. One, two. Live or die.

980
01:54:00,168 --> 01:54:02,170
You know, personally,

981
01:54:03,171 --> 01:54:06,966
I'd rather shoot
the sperm of the devil here. Huh?

982
01:54:07,091 --> 01:54:09,093
But you know something?

983
01:54:09,218 --> 01:54:14,140
I don't think you're going to tell me,
are you? Huh? Too bad.

984
01:54:15,016 --> 01:54:16,934
Come on. Eh?

985
01:54:17,060 --> 01:54:20,104
What do you say? She's not your kind.

986
01:54:21,689 --> 01:54:23,775
You don't even have a kind.

987
01:54:23,900 --> 01:54:25,902
If you say it,

988
01:54:26,027 --> 01:54:28,529
he'll still kill us both.

989
01:54:33,117 --> 01:54:35,328
Let's not get ahead of ourselves.

990
01:54:36,788 --> 01:54:38,748
If you don't tell me,

991
01:54:38,873 --> 01:54:42,293
I swear to Poseidon
that we'll torch your boat.

992
01:54:48,549 --> 01:54:51,928
Refresh my memory-
what if neither one of them talks?

993
01:54:52,053 --> 01:54:55,098
- Never happened before.
- Never happened before.

994
01:54:55,932 --> 01:55:00,853
All right! If they won't tell us
where she is, do 'em! Both of them!

995
01:55:00,978 --> 01:55:03,189
- Just kill 'em now!
- No!

996
01:55:05,817 --> 01:55:07,693
So gullible! Ha-ha! Bring her here.

997
01:55:09,237 --> 01:55:12,657
- (Smokers cheer)
- Seek and ye shall receive!

998
01:55:12,782 --> 01:55:16,285
So ends your daily sermonette!
Ha-ha-ha-ha-ha!

999
01:55:16,411 --> 01:55:18,871
- Yes!
- Yeah!

1000
01:55:18,996 --> 01:55:20,206
Yes!

1001
01:55:21,207 --> 01:55:24,127
Here, take her, boys. Take care of her.

1002
01:55:25,878 --> 01:55:27,922
What is it?

1003
01:55:29,382 --> 01:55:30,800
Stunning.

1004
01:55:30,925 --> 01:55:35,596
I don't have words to even begin to...
It's magnificent.

1005
01:55:35,721 --> 01:55:39,600
Look at that! That square footage.

1006
01:55:39,725 --> 01:55:41,102
Huh? Huh?

1007
01:55:41,227 --> 01:55:46,274
Now figure this map out. Turn her upside
down. Does that mean anything to you?

1008
01:55:46,399 --> 01:55:47,400
No.

1009
01:55:47,525 --> 01:55:52,655
All right. We'll figure it out
back at the 'Dez, boys. Careful with her.

1010
01:55:52,780 --> 01:55:57,076
- What about them?
- Do 'em both. Torch the boat.

1011
01:55:58,077 --> 01:55:59,454
Aargh!

1012
01:56:01,539 --> 01:56:03,332
We have to go under!

1013
01:56:05,585 --> 01:56:08,212
No! I can't breathe like you!

1014
01:56:08,337 --> 01:56:11,048
I'll breathe for both of us.

1015
01:56:35,072 --> 01:56:36,073
Woo!

1016
01:56:41,120 --> 01:56:42,788
(Enola) Helen, help!

1017
01:56:42,914 --> 01:56:44,624
Helen!

1018
01:56:44,749 --> 01:56:46,501
Helen!

1019
01:57:33,631 --> 01:57:35,466
My boat.

1020
01:57:45,268 --> 01:57:46,852
Enola...

1021
01:57:52,858 --> 01:57:54,735
(Deacon) A-ha!

1022
01:57:54,860 --> 01:57:57,113
All right!

1023
01:57:57,238 --> 01:58:02,368
I can't wait to get this thing out,
build some highways and some freeways!

1024
01:58:02,493 --> 01:58:06,706
There you go, cuz. Be careful now.
You break 'em, you can't use 'em.

1025
01:58:06,831 --> 01:58:09,166
Come on! What's happening, cousin?

1026
01:58:09,292 --> 01:58:12,753
Not a word.
She just sits there and leaks.

1027
01:58:12,878 --> 01:58:16,591
A shiver to the liver. This'll make her
give up all her secrets, huh?

1028
01:58:16,716 --> 01:58:20,970
Yeah, or kill her. Let me talk to her
first. I'm real good with kids.

1029
01:58:23,889 --> 01:58:27,393
What is this? Get those chains off her!

1030
01:58:27,518 --> 01:58:29,729
What are we, barbarians here?

1031
01:58:29,854 --> 01:58:32,773
Goodness gracious. Snakes alive.

1032
01:58:32,898 --> 01:58:35,901
Come on, out of here,
you big, nasty animal, you!

1033
01:58:36,986 --> 01:58:39,238
Rub-a-dub-dub. (Chuckles)

1034
01:58:41,032 --> 01:58:44,619
You want to come over here
and sit on my lap?

1035
01:58:44,744 --> 01:58:46,162
No.

1036
01:58:47,413 --> 01:58:49,665
How about a cigarette?

1037
01:58:50,666 --> 01:58:53,961
Nothing like a good smoke
when you miss your mom.

1038
01:58:54,086 --> 01:58:56,005
Never too young to start.

1039
01:58:57,465 --> 01:58:58,841
No.

1040
01:58:58,966 --> 01:59:01,636
Well, I got something right here
I know you'd like.

1041
01:59:02,887 --> 01:59:06,098
Like to draw, don't you? Huh?

1042
01:59:09,769 --> 01:59:11,979
Now they're yours,

1043
01:59:12,104 --> 01:59:16,901
if you help me
with just one problem. All right?

1044
01:59:18,819 --> 01:59:20,821
Now I got this parish.

1045
01:59:20,946 --> 01:59:22,948
A good parish.

1046
01:59:23,074 --> 01:59:25,117
A large parish.

1047
01:59:26,118 --> 01:59:28,621
Getting larger all the time, in fact.

1048
01:59:28,746 --> 01:59:31,040
Now, you know,

1049
01:59:31,165 --> 01:59:33,668
I just don't have enough space

1050
01:59:35,044 --> 01:59:38,756
- for all these people.
- Why don't you make less people?

1051
01:59:38,881 --> 01:59:40,257
Pardon?

1052
01:59:41,342 --> 01:59:45,346
The atoll. Babies are born
only when there's room.

1053
01:59:45,471 --> 01:59:49,100
That way,
there's food and hydro for everyone.

1054
01:59:49,225 --> 01:59:52,812
Well, that's a...quaint suggestion,

1055
01:59:53,813 --> 01:59:56,232
but it don't really play here,

1056
01:59:56,357 --> 02:00:00,653
considering we are, in fact,
the Church of Eternal Growth.

1057
02:00:02,071 --> 02:00:07,243
See, what we need is more land,
for more people.

1058
02:00:07,368 --> 02:00:10,496
Now... Now that tattoo on your back.

1059
02:00:10,621 --> 02:00:13,541
I've been told that that...

1060
02:00:13,666 --> 02:00:15,459
that's actually a map?

1061
02:00:18,003 --> 02:00:20,047
It's the way to Dryland.

1062
02:00:20,172 --> 02:00:22,258
Now we're getting someplace.

1063
02:00:24,677 --> 02:00:27,596
Could you teach me how to read that?

1064
02:00:29,348 --> 02:00:31,350
Setback.

1065
02:00:34,645 --> 02:00:39,275
Well, have you ever heard
any of your friends talk about it?

1066
02:00:39,400 --> 02:00:44,029
You know, like your mommy
or your pet fish? He say anything?

1067
02:00:44,155 --> 02:00:46,490
You shouldn't make fun of him.
He wouldn't like it.

1068
02:00:46,615 --> 02:00:51,537
Girl, I don't give a shit what he'd like.
He took out my eye!

1069
02:00:51,662 --> 02:00:54,874
And if I ever see him again,
I'm gonna cut open his head

1070
02:00:54,999 --> 02:00:59,879
and I'm gonna eat his brain!
You think he'd like that?

1071
02:01:00,671 --> 02:01:04,091
You can't kill him.
He's even meaner than you are.

1072
02:01:05,134 --> 02:01:07,136
But he's not here.

1073
02:01:07,261 --> 02:01:09,263
And he ain't coming.

1074
02:01:09,388 --> 02:01:11,265
And no one's gonna save you.

1075
02:01:12,600 --> 02:01:14,602
He'll come for me. He will.

1076
02:01:14,727 --> 02:01:16,812
Well, you better tell me
what I wanna know

1077
02:01:16,937 --> 02:01:21,317
or he can save what's left of you
in a goddamn jar!

1078
02:01:24,987 --> 02:01:27,031
I'm glad we had this little talk.

1079
02:01:28,574 --> 02:01:30,493
Chain her.

1080
02:01:32,787 --> 02:01:34,622
Chain her up.

1081
02:01:35,623 --> 02:01:38,584
He'll come for me! He'll take me away!

1082
02:01:50,012 --> 02:01:52,431
We're going to die here, aren't we?

1083
02:02:12,243 --> 02:02:14,119
Aren't we?

1084
02:02:23,462 --> 02:02:25,339
After the atoll,

1085
02:02:25,464 --> 02:02:28,008
when I offered myself to you,

1086
02:02:31,095 --> 02:02:33,305
why didn't you take me?

1087
02:02:35,891 --> 02:02:37,893
Cos you didn't really want me.

1088
02:02:39,979 --> 02:02:41,647
Not really.

1089
02:03:47,421 --> 02:03:49,632
Have I been sleeping?

1090
02:03:55,638 --> 02:03:57,431
I was dreaming.

1091
02:04:00,434 --> 02:04:02,227
It's funny.

1092
02:04:03,228 --> 02:04:05,606
I always thought Dryland floated.

1093
02:04:05,731 --> 02:04:09,610
Or drifted with the wind.
That's why it was so hard to find.

1094
02:04:09,735 --> 02:04:12,112
Why did you believe in it so much?

1095
02:04:13,322 --> 02:04:15,658
Cos we weren't made for the sea.

1096
02:04:17,201 --> 02:04:19,995
We've got our hands and our feet.

1097
02:04:20,496 --> 02:04:22,456
We're supposed to walk.

1098
02:04:26,210 --> 02:04:28,170
I miss her sound.

1099
02:04:31,090 --> 02:04:32,883
Don't you?

1100
02:04:33,008 --> 02:04:35,260
Might get some hydro out of this.

1101
02:04:35,386 --> 02:04:37,388
I can't go on.

1102
02:04:39,473 --> 02:04:42,601
Not without her, or Dryland.

1103
02:04:42,726 --> 02:04:46,105
I don't want to live
if there's nothing left,

1104
02:04:47,272 --> 02:04:49,191
there's no hope.

1105
02:04:49,316 --> 02:04:51,068
You're still here.

1106
02:04:58,242 --> 02:05:00,536
Thank you for saving me.

1107
02:05:00,661 --> 02:05:02,705
You can thank the Ancients.

1108
02:05:04,123 --> 02:05:08,669
- This is what they had.
- This is what they made of it.

1109
02:05:09,420 --> 02:05:12,047
That's why I am what I am.

1110
02:05:12,172 --> 02:05:14,633
I may not be human, but I don't quit.

1111
02:05:15,300 --> 02:05:17,136
Never have.

1112
02:05:18,137 --> 02:05:20,556
No matter what they throw at me, I...

1113
02:05:51,920 --> 02:05:54,131
(Gregor) Helen!

1114
02:05:54,256 --> 02:05:56,216
Helen!

1115
02:05:56,341 --> 02:05:59,344
No, no, no, no! Helen, up! Above you!

1116
02:06:00,637 --> 02:06:01,972
(Helen) Gregor!

1117
02:06:03,307 --> 02:06:05,100
(Gregor laughs)

1118
02:06:06,393 --> 02:06:09,063
Smart thinking to burn your boat!

1119
02:06:09,188 --> 02:06:12,983
Without the smoke,
I never would have found you.

1120
02:06:13,108 --> 02:06:17,696
Who's that with you?
Ichthys sapien! Is that really you?

1121
02:06:18,906 --> 02:06:22,826
I'll throw the rope down.
You catch it. I'll help you climb up.

1122
02:06:25,120 --> 02:06:26,121
Helen!

1123
02:06:27,539 --> 02:06:30,542
- Where's Enola?
- Smokers took her.

1124
02:06:31,627 --> 02:06:33,796
They'd have me, too,
if it weren't for him.

1125
02:06:33,921 --> 02:06:35,339
My friend,

1126
02:06:35,464 --> 02:06:38,258
thank you. Very human of you.

1127
02:06:39,259 --> 02:06:41,887
Grab your things quickly. Quickly.

1128
02:06:42,012 --> 02:06:43,013
Come.

1129
02:06:50,521 --> 02:06:52,606
You see? Right down there.

1130
02:06:52,731 --> 02:06:56,527
There's several other survivors.
We'll just start over again.

1131
02:06:59,196 --> 02:07:03,200
Don't worry. They'll welcome you,
just like Gregor did.

1132
02:07:19,550 --> 02:07:21,760
(Man) You can't ask us to go and get her.

1133
02:07:21,885 --> 02:07:24,930
(Woman) Enola's the reason
we're in all this trouble. Forget it!

1134
02:07:25,055 --> 02:07:28,725
(Helen) They need to find Dryland
just like we do.

1135
02:07:28,851 --> 02:07:30,811
Of course.

1136
02:07:30,936 --> 02:07:33,564
(Helen) If the Mariner's willing to go
after her, then why not us?

1137
02:07:33,689 --> 02:07:37,734
(Woman) We don't want you here!
You or the girl!

1138
02:07:38,986 --> 02:07:40,571
Helen...

1139
02:07:40,696 --> 02:07:43,615
The papers the Mariner brought you.

1140
02:07:43,740 --> 02:07:47,619
It's the same language
the tattoo is written in.

1141
02:07:47,744 --> 02:07:50,539
86...56.

1142
02:07:50,664 --> 02:07:56,044
27, 59. If I can figure out
what these numbers refer to...

1143
02:07:56,170 --> 02:07:58,338
- They refer to nothing.
- What?

1144
02:07:58,463 --> 02:08:01,258
Dryland doesn't exist.

1145
02:08:01,383 --> 02:08:03,218
(Man) You're as crazy as she is!

1146
02:08:03,343 --> 02:08:08,473
We're wasting valuable time. More Smokers
will come. We need to be moving now.

1147
02:08:08,599 --> 02:08:12,436
- We need this child to find Dryland!
- I'm not going.

1148
02:08:12,561 --> 02:08:16,481
- (Man) I say let him go.
- (Woman) We're better off without them!

1149
02:08:24,489 --> 02:08:26,575
You won't go after her either?

1150
02:08:30,537 --> 02:08:34,041
- I thought you were different.
- I am different.

1151
02:08:36,710 --> 02:08:38,503
(Man) Hey, hey! That's my sail!

1152
02:08:39,671 --> 02:08:41,798
- What's he doing?
- Leaving.

1153
02:08:41,924 --> 02:08:43,842
Not in one of our boats!

1154
02:08:45,510 --> 02:08:48,138
You can give it to him or he'll take it.

1155
02:09:01,860 --> 02:09:04,488
Enola said you were her friend.

1156
02:09:04,613 --> 02:09:06,615
What do I tell her when I see her again?

1157
02:09:08,659 --> 02:09:10,035
Lies.

1158
02:09:12,120 --> 02:09:14,748
If it makes you feel better.

1159
02:09:27,761 --> 02:09:31,974
Don't blame him.
Survival is all he knows.

1160
02:09:32,099 --> 02:09:35,686
That's why someday there will be
so many like him,

1161
02:09:35,811 --> 02:09:38,772
probably so few of us.

1162
02:11:21,666 --> 02:11:23,668
(Engines roar)

1163
02:11:31,760 --> 02:11:35,889
- What do you want?
- Uh, all kinds of things.

1164
02:11:37,057 --> 02:11:39,226
But, uh, right now

1165
02:11:40,227 --> 02:11:44,147
we'll settle for everything you've got.
Ain't that right, Bones?

1166
02:11:44,272 --> 02:11:47,984
(Man) You destroyed our homes!
Why can't you leave us alone?

1167
02:11:48,110 --> 02:11:51,363
I don't know.
It's a character thing, I guess.

1168
02:11:52,364 --> 02:11:54,366
Ain't that right, Bones?

1169
02:11:55,534 --> 02:11:56,910
Bones?

1170
02:11:57,494 --> 02:11:59,121
Bones?

1171
02:12:16,096 --> 02:12:18,348
I'm going after Enola.

1172
02:12:26,523 --> 02:12:31,278
Here, you know,
for a hideous freak, you're OK.

1173
02:12:32,487 --> 02:12:34,406
It was a joke!

1174
02:12:35,282 --> 02:12:38,994
- Know what that is yet?
- The numbers? Yes, I think I do.

1175
02:12:39,119 --> 02:12:43,039
It seems to be some ancient form
of geographic location.

1176
02:12:43,165 --> 02:12:46,626
Latitude, longitude.
It doesn't make sense, though.

1177
02:12:46,751 --> 02:12:49,421
The numbers,
they seem to be backwards or something.

1178
02:12:49,546 --> 02:12:52,757
- It's upside down.
- The world?

1179
02:12:52,883 --> 02:12:56,970
- The poles have reversed themselves?
- I've been mapping the cities below.

1180
02:12:59,431 --> 02:13:02,976
The world wasn't created in a deluge.
It was covered by it.

1181
02:13:03,101 --> 02:13:05,896
- (Man) That's blasphemy!
- No, it's true.

1182
02:13:06,021 --> 02:13:09,399
I've seen it with my own eyes.
There's land.

1183
02:13:09,524 --> 02:13:13,236
- Right under our keel. None of it's dry.
- Some is.

1184
02:13:14,738 --> 02:13:19,284
Enola's been there. I know that now.
I saw what she drew.

1185
02:13:19,409 --> 02:13:23,205
That's why he's going after Enola.
To find Dryland.

1186
02:13:23,330 --> 02:13:25,957
I don't care about Dryland.

1187
02:13:26,082 --> 02:13:29,669
This is ridiculous.
Going after the Smokers?

1188
02:13:29,794 --> 02:13:33,340
He doesn't even know
which direction they came from.

1189
02:13:51,691 --> 02:13:54,653
If she's alive,
I'll bring her back to you.

1190
02:14:02,327 --> 02:14:06,790
(Woman) Forget about the Muto, Helen!
If he brings her back, they'll kill us!

1191
02:14:06,915 --> 02:14:10,585
We've got to go help him.
I can't ask him to do this alone.

1192
02:14:10,710 --> 02:14:14,756
Don't worry, my dear.
You're not going to have to.

1193
02:14:29,980 --> 02:14:32,649
- Hey, Doc, what's this?
- Where?

1194
02:14:32,774 --> 02:14:36,111
- Above the squiggle. Looks like a star.
- Or a meteor.

1195
02:14:36,236 --> 02:14:37,779
It's a mole.

1196
02:14:37,904 --> 02:14:42,534
- You got that tattoo figured out yet?
- It'd be easier if it was flat.

1197
02:14:42,659 --> 02:14:45,245
Big and flat. It needs to be flat.

1198
02:14:45,370 --> 02:14:49,165
- What have you got in mind?
- Well, you cut it off her back,

1199
02:14:49,291 --> 02:14:51,876
stretch it, mount it,
give us a proper look.

1200
02:14:52,002 --> 02:14:54,212
(Deacon)
Take her down below until I holler.

1201
02:14:55,422 --> 02:14:58,008
Saint Joe, we're close.

1202
02:14:59,509 --> 02:15:01,803
After centuries of shame.

1203
02:15:57,609 --> 02:15:59,653
(Distant echoing voices)

1204
02:16:32,227 --> 02:16:34,229
(Laughter and yelling)

1205
02:16:38,650 --> 02:16:42,529
- They're getting ugly.
- Don't I know it.

1206
02:16:42,654 --> 02:16:44,906
Announce me, cousin.

1207
02:16:49,285 --> 02:16:52,080
- Hey, here he is.
- (Crowd roars)

1208
02:16:52,205 --> 02:16:55,792
Rise up, brothers and sisters,

1209
02:16:57,293 --> 02:16:59,295
turn your eyes

1210
02:16:59,421 --> 02:17:03,049
and open your hearts
to your humble benefactor,

1211
02:17:03,174 --> 02:17:07,011
your spiritual shepherd
and dictator for life,

1212
02:17:07,137 --> 02:17:10,098
the Deacon of the 'Dez!

1213
02:17:10,223 --> 02:17:12,308
(Crowd roars)

1214
02:18:02,192 --> 02:18:04,027
(Deacon) Children,

1215
02:18:04,152 --> 02:18:06,529
children of the provider,

1216
02:18:07,906 --> 02:18:12,619
citizens of the good ship,
please now, hear me speak.

1217
02:18:16,873 --> 02:18:19,834
- I've had a vision.
- (Man) We're tired of your visions!

1218
02:18:19,959 --> 02:18:22,212
What about the land you promised us?

1219
02:18:22,337 --> 02:18:24,088
(Crowd cheers)

1220
02:18:24,214 --> 02:18:26,174
- Yeah!
- (Deacon) Oh, ye of little faith.

1221
02:18:27,509 --> 02:18:29,719
I've had a vision so great,

1222
02:18:29,844 --> 02:18:32,722
that as it came to me, I wept.

1223
02:18:32,847 --> 02:18:38,353
- And in this splenditudinous...
- (Smoker) Is that Bone's vehicle?

1224
02:18:38,478 --> 02:18:42,649
(Deacon) I saw - and you know
what it is that I saw.

1225
02:18:43,608 --> 02:18:45,151
I saw...

1226
02:18:46,402 --> 02:18:48,863
- the land.
- (Cheering)

1227
02:19:15,265 --> 02:19:17,267
(Crowd chanting)

1228
02:19:28,069 --> 02:19:31,406
- Horse, is that you?
- (Jet ski engine revs)

1229
02:19:35,869 --> 02:19:39,539
Look, just bring it in slow, OK?
I don't have all day.

1230
02:19:39,664 --> 02:19:40,957
(Engine revs)

1231
02:19:41,082 --> 02:19:42,542
Horse!

1232
02:19:42,667 --> 02:19:45,295
Just bring it up slow.

1233
02:19:46,296 --> 02:19:48,006
I said slow!

1234
02:20:07,400 --> 02:20:09,777
You killed Smitty, cousin.

1235
02:20:13,406 --> 02:20:15,950
- Nice landing!
- (Laughter)

1236
02:20:16,075 --> 02:20:18,912
Smitty, man, always in the way!

1237
02:20:22,206 --> 02:20:24,626
Smitty? I quit!

1238
02:20:26,544 --> 02:20:28,713
I'm in charge now, baby!

1239
02:20:28,838 --> 02:20:31,591
Yeah, I'm in charge.

1240
02:20:31,716 --> 02:20:34,177
I'm in charge!

1241
02:20:40,224 --> 02:20:43,853
(Deacon)
'And he said this to me personally.

1242
02:20:45,647 --> 02:20:49,776
'We are to go there
and we are to settle it.

1243
02:20:49,901 --> 02:20:52,111
'And we are to build the...'

1244
02:20:53,071 --> 02:20:57,075
You shouldn't be doing that.
You're going to get in trouble.

1245
02:20:57,200 --> 02:20:59,118
Huh! That's right.

1246
02:20:59,243 --> 02:21:03,665
You're not afraid. You've got
your pet freak coming to rescue you.

1247
02:21:03,790 --> 02:21:06,209
He's not a freak
and he can take you any time!

1248
02:21:08,211 --> 02:21:12,632
He's killed dozens of people.
He doesn't have any mercy or anything.

1249
02:21:12,757 --> 02:21:14,676
He even kills little girls.

1250
02:21:16,594 --> 02:21:18,137
Haven't we all?

1251
02:21:20,139 --> 02:21:21,182
Dang!

1252
02:21:22,392 --> 02:21:23,476
It's Horse.

1253
02:21:25,770 --> 02:21:28,314
Find him! Find him!

1254
02:21:30,233 --> 02:21:32,694
Yes! Yes! Yes!

1255
02:21:32,819 --> 02:21:36,406
- Come on.
- Getting nervous, aren't you?

1256
02:21:40,368 --> 02:21:42,370
I don't get nervous.

1257
02:21:43,871 --> 02:21:46,708
(Deacon)
And if there's a river, we'll dam it!

1258
02:21:46,833 --> 02:21:50,461
And if there's a tree, we'll ram it!

1259
02:21:51,462 --> 02:21:54,132
Cos I'm talkin' progress here!

1260
02:21:54,257 --> 02:21:55,675
Yes, sir!

1261
02:21:55,800 --> 02:21:58,803
- I'm talkin' development!
- Yeah!

1262
02:21:58,928 --> 02:22:03,266
We shall suck and savor
the sweet flavor

1263
02:22:03,391 --> 02:22:05,935
of Dryland.

1264
02:22:06,060 --> 02:22:07,937
(Enola) Your face is all red.

1265
02:22:09,522 --> 02:22:14,110
Helen said anybody that has a face
that red has either had too much sun

1266
02:22:14,235 --> 02:22:17,447
- or too much to drink.
- All right, that's it.

1267
02:22:17,572 --> 02:22:20,491
- I'm gonna burn your face!
- All right.

1268
02:22:20,616 --> 02:22:24,620
- What's up?
- We're just talking about her friend.

1269
02:22:26,039 --> 02:22:28,833
- What's his name?
- He doesn't have a name.

1270
02:22:28,958 --> 02:22:33,337
- So Death can't find him.
- (Mocking noises)

1271
02:22:36,841 --> 02:22:39,927
He doesn't have a home
or people to care for.

1272
02:22:40,928 --> 02:22:43,723
He's not afraid of anything,
men least of all.

1273
02:22:43,848 --> 02:22:46,768
He's fast and strong like a big wind.

1274
02:22:47,769 --> 02:22:51,564
He can hear 100 miles
and see 100 miles underwater.

1275
02:22:51,689 --> 02:22:54,192
He can hide in the shadow of a noon sun.

1276
02:22:54,984 --> 02:22:59,197
He could be right behind you and you won't
even know it till you're dead!

1277
02:23:00,656 --> 02:23:02,575
Give it a rest.

1278
02:23:04,077 --> 02:23:07,497
- He'll come for me. He will.
- Yeah?

1279
02:23:08,664 --> 02:23:10,625
Well, I hope he does.

1280
02:23:14,170 --> 02:23:16,130
Remember you said that.

1281
02:23:17,507 --> 02:23:20,051
(Deacon) Look at us.

1282
02:23:20,176 --> 02:23:22,303
Look at us here today.

1283
02:23:22,428 --> 02:23:26,015
Dryland is not just our destination,

1284
02:23:26,849 --> 02:23:29,769
but it is our destiny!

1285
02:23:31,145 --> 02:23:33,106
(Speech continues)

1286
02:23:38,069 --> 02:23:40,446
Find him! Find him!

1287
02:23:40,571 --> 02:23:44,951
How can I find this glorious place?

1288
02:23:45,952 --> 02:23:48,079
And he said to me,

1289
02:23:49,080 --> 02:23:50,915
"A child

1290
02:23:51,040 --> 02:23:53,501
"shall lead you."

1291
02:23:54,502 --> 02:23:56,295
A child.

1292
02:23:56,420 --> 02:23:58,756
- And behold...
- It's time.

1293
02:23:58,881 --> 02:24:01,843
The instrument of our salvation!

1294
02:24:03,845 --> 02:24:05,721
(Crowd roars)

1295
02:24:09,433 --> 02:24:11,853
Our guide in the wild!

1296
02:24:11,978 --> 02:24:14,313
Our beacon in the darkness!

1297
02:24:14,438 --> 02:24:16,524
Turn her around, Nord.

1298
02:24:16,649 --> 02:24:19,152
She has shown me the path!

1299
02:24:23,447 --> 02:24:27,076
And before the holy-most moment
is upon us,

1300
02:24:27,201 --> 02:24:30,580
let's sacrifice one to old Saint Joe!

1301
02:24:33,875 --> 02:24:37,461
And let's get this tub of shit
up to speed!

1302
02:24:39,547 --> 02:24:42,049
(Chaotic yelling)

1303
02:24:43,259 --> 02:24:44,385
Yep.

1304
02:25:23,299 --> 02:25:26,677
- Stroke!
- Pull!

1305
02:25:27,929 --> 02:25:29,138
Stroke!

1306
02:25:29,263 --> 02:25:31,057
Pull!

1307
02:25:32,516 --> 02:25:34,393
Stroke!

1308
02:25:37,730 --> 02:25:39,523
(Galley master) Stroke!

1309
02:25:41,317 --> 02:25:42,944
Stroke!

1310
02:25:50,576 --> 02:25:53,412
- So which way are we rowing?
- I don't have a goddamn clue!

1311
02:25:53,537 --> 02:25:58,960
Don't worry. They'll row for a month
before they figure out I'm faking it.

1312
02:25:59,085 --> 02:26:02,922
- But, um... Why?
- Oh, you want details?

1313
02:26:03,047 --> 02:26:07,134
Well, I'm not telling these savages
we haven't solved the map yet.

1314
02:26:07,260 --> 02:26:12,306
I promised them results and I'll get 'em
if I gotta cut 'em out of her back!

1315
02:26:14,183 --> 02:26:17,186
Who is that? Who is that?

1316
02:26:18,354 --> 02:26:20,690
(Man) Maybe one of the spare rowers?

1317
02:26:28,572 --> 02:26:31,367
Why aren't you rowing?

1318
02:26:40,001 --> 02:26:42,336
- It's him!
- It is him.

1319
02:26:43,337 --> 02:26:46,340
You guys are in so much trouble.

1320
02:26:49,051 --> 02:26:52,430
Well, I'll be damned.
It's the gentleman guppy.

1321
02:26:53,431 --> 02:26:55,433
He's like a turd that won't flush.

1322
02:26:56,559 --> 02:26:58,436
I want the girl.

1323
02:27:02,606 --> 02:27:07,069
You know,
I thought you were stupid, friend.

1324
02:27:08,195 --> 02:27:10,656
But I underestimated you.

1325
02:27:10,781 --> 02:27:13,784
You are a total freakin' retard!

1326
02:27:13,909 --> 02:27:15,911
(Maniacal laughter)

1327
02:27:17,038 --> 02:27:20,124
I want the girl. That's all.

1328
02:27:20,249 --> 02:27:23,961
What on this screwed-up earth
makes you think you're going to get her?

1329
02:27:33,471 --> 02:27:35,473
You know what this is?

1330
02:27:39,560 --> 02:27:42,021
I drop it, you burn.

1331
02:27:42,146 --> 02:27:44,398
We all burn.

1332
02:27:44,523 --> 02:27:46,484
No, wait, wait, wait.

1333
02:27:47,234 --> 02:27:49,779
Let's not do anything rash here.

1334
02:27:49,904 --> 02:27:53,157
I mean, are you sure she's worth all this?

1335
02:27:53,282 --> 02:27:56,702
She never does stop talking.
She never shuts up.

1336
02:27:56,827 --> 02:27:58,788
- I noticed.
- What is it, then?

1337
02:27:58,913 --> 02:28:01,207
Huh? It's the map.

1338
02:28:02,208 --> 02:28:03,876
She's my friend.

1339
02:28:05,586 --> 02:28:08,798
Golly gee.
A single tear rolls down my cheek.

1340
02:28:08,923 --> 02:28:11,509
You're gonna die for your friend.

1341
02:28:12,760 --> 02:28:14,678
If it comes to that.

1342
02:28:17,014 --> 02:28:18,641
He's bluffing! I'll kill him.

1343
02:28:18,766 --> 02:28:22,645
- He's not bluffing. He never bluffs.
- Shut up!

1344
02:28:24,063 --> 02:28:27,817
You know, I don't think you're going to
drop that torch, my friend.

1345
02:28:28,818 --> 02:28:32,613
- Why not?
- Because you're not crazy.

1346
02:28:36,492 --> 02:28:38,244
No!

1347
02:28:46,293 --> 02:28:48,045
Oh, thank God.

1348
02:28:52,758 --> 02:28:54,260
Aargh!

1349
02:29:00,724 --> 02:29:02,726
(Heavy gunfire)

1350
02:29:05,896 --> 02:29:08,149
(Man) Look out!

1351
02:29:08,274 --> 02:29:10,693
Get him!

1352
02:29:10,818 --> 02:29:13,028
Let's go, goddamnit!

1353
02:29:14,363 --> 02:29:15,739
(Man screams)

1354
02:29:15,865 --> 02:29:19,118
Don't just stand there - kill something!

1355
02:29:22,121 --> 02:29:24,248
Was this your big vision?

1356
02:29:31,255 --> 02:29:32,840
Aaargh!

1357
02:29:32,965 --> 02:29:34,467
Ah!

1358
02:29:34,592 --> 02:29:36,844
I've always wanted to drive this monster!

1359
02:29:39,263 --> 02:29:42,057
(Man) There he is! There he is!

1360
02:29:46,437 --> 02:29:48,189
That's him there!

1361
02:29:51,025 --> 02:29:52,026
Aargh!

1362
02:29:56,739 --> 02:29:57,740
Aaaargh!

1363
02:30:08,834 --> 02:30:10,836
(Enola) Let me go!

1364
02:30:10,961 --> 02:30:12,963
Let go!

1365
02:30:18,260 --> 02:30:20,221
(Explosion)

1366
02:30:22,139 --> 02:30:23,516
Let me go!

1367
02:30:27,811 --> 02:30:30,272
(Enola) Let me go! Let go!

1368
02:30:30,397 --> 02:30:32,233
Let me go!

1369
02:30:33,108 --> 02:30:35,861
Let go! Let go!

1370
02:30:38,864 --> 02:30:41,617
Let me go! Let go!

1371
02:30:45,120 --> 02:30:48,332
(Laughs)
You should have stayed on the water.

1372
02:30:48,457 --> 02:30:50,251
(Clicks)

1373
02:30:57,800 --> 02:31:01,345
You know how to fly an airplane?
You're lucky I do.

1374
02:31:01,470 --> 02:31:05,224
Ow! Now you stop it!
You behave yourself now!

1375
02:32:00,279 --> 02:32:01,447
Up!

1376
02:32:31,101 --> 02:32:32,895
(Explosion)

1377
02:32:41,445 --> 02:32:43,947
It's going down. It's sinking!

1378
02:32:44,073 --> 02:32:48,661
- Gregor, bring us right down on top.
- Hurry, Gregor!

1379
02:32:48,786 --> 02:32:50,913
- (Gregor) Don't worry!
- Hurry.

1380
02:32:55,918 --> 02:32:57,836
(Hull creaks)

1381
02:33:05,469 --> 02:33:07,846
Enola! Up here! Grab on!

1382
02:33:14,186 --> 02:33:15,854
Are they on yet?

1383
02:33:19,358 --> 02:33:22,027
- What is it?
- I don't know!

1384
02:33:23,237 --> 02:33:25,114
No!

1385
02:33:34,039 --> 02:33:38,585
Gotcha! I'm gonna rip
your cute little lungs out!

1386
02:33:42,423 --> 02:33:44,341
Aaaah!

1387
02:33:47,928 --> 02:33:49,430
Aaargh!

1388
02:33:52,474 --> 02:33:54,977
Pull! Almost!

1389
02:34:00,274 --> 02:34:02,276
(Gregor laughs)

1390
02:34:03,402 --> 02:34:04,987
(Explosion)

1391
02:34:34,099 --> 02:34:35,100
No!

1392
02:34:35,225 --> 02:34:37,770
- Aaaaargh!
- No! Enola!

1393
02:34:40,314 --> 02:34:42,566
Saint Joe! Hole in one.

1394
02:34:42,691 --> 02:34:45,110
- Helen!
- Enola!

1395
02:34:45,235 --> 02:34:47,696
- (Gregor) Helen!
- Hey!

1396
02:34:47,821 --> 02:34:49,198
Hey!

1397
02:34:53,660 --> 02:34:57,247
If I can't have Dryland, no one will!

1398
02:35:00,751 --> 02:35:04,713
Oh... Oh, no, quick!
What are we going to do?

1399
02:35:08,091 --> 02:35:09,176
Tie this off!

1400
02:35:14,056 --> 02:35:15,808
Hurry! Tie it!

1401
02:35:21,438 --> 02:35:23,941
- Got it!
- Ah!

1402
02:35:27,069 --> 02:35:28,987
Aaaargh!

1403
02:35:36,912 --> 02:35:38,831
Get them up now!

1404
02:35:45,921 --> 02:35:47,714
(Straining)

1405
02:35:56,139 --> 02:35:58,141
Of course.

1406
02:36:00,227 --> 02:36:02,145
Of course, the numbers.

1407
02:36:02,271 --> 02:36:04,481
The numbers! They...

1408
02:36:04,606 --> 02:36:07,276
(Giggling) That must be it!

1409
02:36:07,401 --> 02:36:08,944
What?

1410
02:36:09,069 --> 02:36:12,531
- I was swimming.
- I saw.

1411
02:36:12,656 --> 02:36:14,908
(Gregor) My friends, my friends, look!

1412
02:36:15,033 --> 02:36:18,161
Look, this map...

1413
02:36:19,246 --> 02:36:23,500
This map, it bears a grid system
with numbers the Ancients used

1414
02:36:23,625 --> 02:36:26,295
to determine geographic location
on the world,

1415
02:36:26,420 --> 02:36:30,090
just like the numbers and symbols
on Enola's back.

1416
02:36:31,967 --> 02:36:36,430
First, they would determine
the angle of the sun using this

1417
02:36:36,555 --> 02:36:41,059
and that would tell them where they were
and which direction they had to go.

1418
02:36:42,686 --> 02:36:47,733
If I take a bearing from the sun and
reverse the co-ordinates on Enola's back,

1419
02:36:50,485 --> 02:36:52,362
then Dryland is that way!

1420
02:36:52,487 --> 02:36:54,072
(He chuckles)

1421
02:38:01,974 --> 02:38:04,059
(Seagulls cry)

1422
02:38:56,028 --> 02:38:59,698
- (Helen laughs)
- It's fresh! All of this!

1423
02:38:59,823 --> 02:39:01,616
It's fresh!

1424
02:39:04,327 --> 02:39:06,329
(Gregor laughs)

1425
02:39:07,789 --> 02:39:09,791
(Helen) Come on!

1426
02:39:14,963 --> 02:39:16,089
Woo!

1427
02:39:17,257 --> 02:39:19,968
I've found something!

1428
02:40:17,692 --> 02:40:20,946
Maybe we should put them under the dirt.

1429
02:40:21,530 --> 02:40:23,532
I think it was their way.

1430
02:40:25,659 --> 02:40:27,744
(Gregor)
They must have known they were dying.

1431
02:40:27,869 --> 02:40:29,746
(Helen laughs)

1432
02:40:52,269 --> 02:40:54,437
(Music box plays)

1433
02:40:58,441 --> 02:41:00,277
I'm home.

1434
02:41:11,079 --> 02:41:14,374
- Where's the Mariner?
- He was outside.

1435
02:41:18,920 --> 02:41:21,756
Wait! Wait, I want to show you this.

1436
02:41:37,397 --> 02:41:39,399
(Thunder of hooves)

1437
02:41:43,069 --> 02:41:44,905
(Whinnying)

1438
02:41:54,039 --> 02:41:56,249
(Chorus of bird calls)

1439
02:42:39,459 --> 02:42:42,337
First time in your life you got nothing
to say?

1440
02:42:56,476 --> 02:42:58,853
Enola, I have to go now.

1441
02:42:59,854 --> 02:43:02,148
But you came back for me.

1442
02:43:03,483 --> 02:43:05,402
I like you.

1443
02:43:10,657 --> 02:43:12,617
Why are you leaving?

1444
02:43:16,121 --> 02:43:20,041
- I don't belong here. I belong out there.
- You belong here.

1445
02:43:22,043 --> 02:43:25,463
It's too strange here.
It doesn't move right.

1446
02:43:25,588 --> 02:43:28,883
Helen said that it's only landsickness.

1447
02:43:29,592 --> 02:43:31,928
We're all feeling it. It'll go away soon.

1448
02:43:33,638 --> 02:43:35,598
It's more than that.

1449
02:44:22,395 --> 02:44:24,397
Well, goodbye, my friend.

1450
02:44:27,317 --> 02:44:29,778
Oh, I have something for you.

1451
02:44:31,154 --> 02:44:32,989
It's dirt!

1452
02:44:34,157 --> 02:44:36,785
Don't trade it all in one place.

1453
02:44:38,536 --> 02:44:42,665
Or do! It will give you reason
to come back for more!

1454
02:44:42,791 --> 02:44:44,793
(Gregor laughs)

1455
02:44:46,461 --> 02:44:50,382
- It's all I got, Drifter.
- It's enough.

1456
02:44:59,933 --> 02:45:03,103
Is it that easy for you
to just drift away?

1457
02:45:03,228 --> 02:45:05,397
I never said it was easy.

1458
02:45:07,732 --> 02:45:09,734
I don't understand.

1459
02:45:15,323 --> 02:45:17,283
I don't understand.

1460
02:45:18,410 --> 02:45:20,412
I mean, you brought us here.

1461
02:45:20,537 --> 02:45:23,123
You belong here as much as anyone.
Maybe more.

1462
02:45:29,003 --> 02:45:33,299
What do you think you're going to find?
What are you looking for out there?

1463
02:45:33,425 --> 02:45:37,053
Gregor once said there might be
others like me somewhere.

1464
02:45:39,597 --> 02:45:42,058
I have to know.

1465
02:45:43,643 --> 02:45:45,478
Helen, if...

1466
02:45:45,603 --> 02:45:48,690
If I find any others out there like you,

1467
02:45:50,358 --> 02:45:52,360
I'll tell them about this place

1468
02:45:52,485 --> 02:45:57,282
and how one woman with hope and courage
found it.

1469
02:46:37,197 --> 02:46:39,866
I have something for you.

1470
02:46:40,617 --> 02:46:44,913
- Something you'll need on your journey.
- I don't have much to barter with.

1471
02:46:45,038 --> 02:46:47,040
It's no trade. It's a gift.

1472
02:46:48,124 --> 02:46:52,295
- No such thing in Waterworld.
- Well, then, let this be the first.

1473
02:46:54,214 --> 02:46:56,049
It's a name.

1474
02:46:57,050 --> 02:47:01,012
It's from an old story about a great
warrior returning from battle.

1475
02:47:01,137 --> 02:47:04,933
He just set sail
and the water god cursed him,

1476
02:47:05,058 --> 02:47:07,685
and for the next ten years
he drifted on the seas.

1477
02:47:07,810 --> 02:47:11,523
The warrior drifted on the seas,
unable to find his way home,

1478
02:47:11,648 --> 02:47:14,067
until finally the gods took pity on him.

1479
02:47:14,192 --> 02:47:17,403
And they called up a warm wind
that blew him home.

1480
02:47:17,529 --> 02:47:19,614
To his family.

1481
02:47:20,823 --> 02:47:23,243
And he never left them again.

1482
02:47:25,703 --> 02:47:28,373
His name was Ulysses.

1483
02:47:31,501 --> 02:47:33,461
It's a good name.

1484
02:48:22,510 --> 02:48:24,345
(Panting)

